{"title_page": "Ferroplasma", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| domain = [[Archaea]]\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Euryarchaeota]]\n| phylum = [[Euryarchaeota]]\n| classis = [[Thermoplasmata]]\n| ordo = [[Thermoplasmatales]]\n| familia = [[Ferroplasmaceae]]\n| genus = '''''Ferroplasma'''''\n| genus_authority = Golyshina ''et al.'' 2000\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species (biology)|Species]]\n| subdivision = * ''[[Ferroplasma acidiphilum|F. acidiphilum]]''\n* ''[[Ferroplasma acidarmanus|F. acidarmanus]]''\n* ''[[Ferroplasma thermophilum|F. thermophilum]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Ferroplasma''''' is a genus of [[Archaea]] that belong to the family [[Ferroplasmaceae]]. Members of the ''Ferroplasma'' are typically acidophillic, pleomorphic, irregularly shaped cocci.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite journal|last=Dopson|first=M.|last2=Baker-Austin|first2=C.|last3=Hind|first3=A.|last4=Bowman|first4=J. P.|last5=Bond|first5=P. L.|date=2004-04-01|title=Characterization of Ferroplasma Isolates and Ferroplasma acidarmanus sp. nov., Extreme Acidophiles from Acid Mine Drainage and Industrial Bioleaching Environments|url=http://aem.asm.org/cgi/doi/10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=70|issue=4|pages=2079\u20132088|doi=10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|issn=0099-2240|pmc=383147|pmid=15066799}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|last2=Timmis|first2=Kenneth N.|date=2005|title=Ferroplasma and relatives, recently discovered cell wall-lacking archaea making a living in extremely acid, heavy metal-rich environments|url=https://sfamjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|journal=Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=7|issue=9|pages=1277\u20131288|doi=10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|issn=1462-2920}}</ref>\n\nThe Ferroplasmaceae family of archaea was first described in the early 2000s.<ref name=\":64\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|date=2011-08-01|title=Environmental, Biogeographic, and Biochemical Patterns of Archaea of the Family Ferroplasmaceae|url=http://aem.asm.org/lookup/doi/10.1128/AEM.00726-11|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=77|issue=15|pages=5071\u20135078|doi=10.1128/AEM.00726-11|issn=0099-2240|pmc=3147448|pmid=21685165}}</ref> To date very few species of ''Ferroplasma'' have been isolated and characterized. Isolated species include ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'', ''Ferroplasma acidarmanus,'' and ''Ferroplasma thermophilum''.<ref name=\":03\"/><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhou|first=H.|last2=Zhang|first2=R.|last3=Hu|first3=P.|last4=Zeng|first4=W.|last5=Xie|first5=Y.|last6=Wu|first6=C.|last7=Qiu|first7=G.|date=August 2008|title=Isolation and characterization of Ferroplasma thermophilum sp. nov., a novel extremely acidophilic, moderately thermophilic archaeon and its role in bioleaching of chalcopyrite|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/j.1365-2672.2008.03807.x|journal=Journal of Applied Microbiology|language=en|volume=105|issue=2|pages=591\u2013601|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2672.2008.03807.x}}</ref> A fourth isolate ''Ferroplasma cupricumulans'' was later determined to belong to a separate genus''.''<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite journal|last=Hawkes|first=Rebecca B.|last2=Franzmann|first2=Peter D.|last3=Plumb|first3=Jason J.|date=2006-09-01|title=Moderate thermophiles including \"Ferroplasma cupricumulans\" sp. nov. dominate an industrial-scale chalcocite heap bioleaching operation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304386X06000934|journal=Hydrometallurgy|series=16th International Biohydrometallurgy Symposium|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=229\u2013236|doi=10.1016/j.hydromet.2006.03.027|issn=0304-386X}}</ref><ref name=\"Golyshina 2815\u20132823\"/> All known ''Ferroplasma sp.'' are iron-oxidizers.\n\n== Cell characteristics and Physiology ==\n''Ferroplasma'' cells are pleomorphic and lack a cell-wall.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|last2=Timmis|first2=Kenneth N.|date=2005|title=Ferroplasma and relatives, recently discovered cell wall-lacking archaea making a living in extremely acid, heavy metal-rich environments|url=https://sfamjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|journal=Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=7|issue=9|pages=1277\u20131288|doi=10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|issn=1462-2920}}</ref> All known members of the genera are acidophiles that thrive in environments where pH ranges from 0.0 to 2.0.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Dopson|first=M.|last2=Baker-Austin|first2=C.|last3=Hind|first3=A.|last4=Bowman|first4=J. P.|last5=Bond|first5=P. L.|date=2004-04-01|title=Characterization of Ferroplasma Isolates and Ferroplasma acidarmanus sp. nov., Extreme Acidophiles from Acid Mine Drainage and Industrial Bioleaching Environments|url=http://aem.asm.org/cgi/doi/10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=70|issue=4|pages=2079\u20132088|doi=10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|issn=0099-2240|pmc=PMC383147|pmid=15066799}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> They are also mesophilic to moderately thermophilic with optimal temperatures ranging from 35-55\u00b0C.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|date=2011-08-01|title=Environmental, Biogeographic, and Biochemical Patterns of Archaea of the Family Ferroplasmaceae|url=http://aem.asm.org/lookup/doi/10.1128/AEM.00726-11|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=77|issue=15|pages=5071\u20135078|doi=10.1128/AEM.00726-11|issn=0099-2240|pmc=PMC3147448|pmid=21685165}}</ref>\n\nTetraether-based lipids are an important part of the ''Ferroplasma'' cellular membrane and allow cells to maintain a pH gradient. A study of ''F.'' ''acidarmanus'' found that cytoplasmic pH was maintained ~5.6 while the environmental pH ranged from ~0-1.2.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Macalady|first=Jennifer L.|last2=Vestling|first2=Martha M.|last3=Baumler|first3=David|last4=Boekelheide|first4=Nick|last5=Kaspar|first5=Charles W.|last6=Banfield|first6=Jillian F.|date=2004\u201310|title=Tetraether-linked membrane monolayers in Ferroplasma spp: a key to survival in acid|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s00792-004-0404-5|journal=Extremophiles|language=en|volume=8|issue=5|pages=411\u2013419|doi=10.1007/s00792-004-0404-5|issn=1431-0651|via=}}</ref> Variations in the tetraether lipids of the ''Ferroplasmaceae'' family are used for chemotaxonomic identification at the genus and species level because many members possess identical 16S rRNA sequences.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nMembers of the genus ''Ferroplasma'' are chemomixotrophs that can oxidize ferrous iron to acquire energy, but despite evidence of carbon fixation, lab cultures often require an organic carbon source such as yeast extract for growth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> In the absence of iron, some lab-grown strains have been capable of chemoorganotrophic growth.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Ecological Importance ==\nIron is the fourth most abundant mineral in earth's crust. As iron-oxidizers ''Ferroplasma sp.'' participate in the biogeochemical of iron. ''Ferroplasma sp.'' are often identified at acid mine drainage (AMD) sites.<ref name=\":64\"/>\n\n''Ferroplasma sp.'' may have important applications for bioleaching metals. Microbial [[bioleaching]] occurs naturally in the highly acidic environments that are home to ''Ferroplasma sp.'' Harnessing the power of bioleaching to recover metal from low quality ores and waste material is energetically advantageous compared to smelting and purifying.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rohwerder|first=T.|last2=Gehrke|first2=T.|last3=Kinzler|first3=K.|last4=Sand|first4=W.|date=2003-12-01|title=Bioleaching review part A:|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00253-003-1448-7|journal=Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology|language=en|volume=63|issue=3|pages=239\u2013248|doi=10.1007/s00253-003-1448-7|issn=1432-0614}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olson|first=G. J.|last2=Brierley|first2=J. A.|last3=Brierley|first3=C. L.|date=2003-12-01|title=Bioleaching review part B:|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00253-003-1404-6|journal=Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology|language=en|volume=63|issue=3|pages=249\u2013257|doi=10.1007/s00253-003-1404-6|issn=1432-0614}}</ref> It also produces fewer toxic byproducts. Studies have shown that the inclusion of ''Ferroplasma thermophilum'' along with the bacteria ''[[Acidithiobacillus caldus]]'' and ''[[Leptospirillum ferriphilum]]'' can bioaugment the leaching process of chalcopyrite and increase the rate at which copper is recovered.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Lijuan|last2=Wu|first2=Junzi|last3=Wang|first3=Yuguang|last4=Wan|first4=Lili|last5=Mao|first5=Feng|last6=Zhang|first6=Wei|last7=Chen|first7=Xinhua|last8=Zhou|first8=Hongbo|date=May 2014|title=Influence of bioaugmentation with Ferroplasma thermophilum on chalcopyrite bioleaching and microbial community structure|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0304386X1400053X|journal=Hydrometallurgy|language=en|volume=146|pages=15\u201323|doi=10.1016/j.hydromet.2014.02.013}}</ref>\n\n== Isolated Species ==\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' ===\n''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' has been shown to grow as a chemomixotroph and to grow synergistically with the acidophilic bacteria ''Leptospirillum ferriphilum''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Merino|first=M. P.|last2=Andrews|first2=B. A.|last3=Parada|first3=P.|last4=Asenjo|first4=J. A.|date=November 2016|title=Characterization of Ferroplasma acidiphilum growing in pure and mixed culture with Leptospirillum ferriphilum|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1002/btpr.2340|journal=Biotechnology Progress|language=en|volume=32|issue=6|pages=1390\u20131396|doi=10.1002/btpr.2340}}</ref> The strain ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' Y<sup>T</sup> is a facultative anaerobe with all the required genes for arginine fermentation.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|last2=Tran|first2=Hai|last3=Reva|first3=Oleg N.|last4=Lemak|first4=Sofia|last5=Yakunin|first5=Alexander F.|last6=Goesmann|first6=Alexander|last7=Nechitaylo|first7=Taras Y.|last8=LaCono|first8=Violetta|last9=Smedile|first9=Francesco|last10=Slesarev|first10=Alexei|last11=Rojo|first11=David|date=December 2017|title=Metabolic and evolutionary patterns in the extremely acidophilic archaeon Ferroplasma acidiphilum YT|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-017-03904-5|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=3682|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-03904-5|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5473848|pmid=28623373}}</ref> Although it is unclear whether ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' Y<sup>T</sup> uses its arginine fermentation pathway, the pathway itself is an ancient metabolism that traces back to the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of the three domains of life.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|first=Manuel|last2=P\u00e9rez|first2=Gaspar|last3=Gonz\u00e1lez-Candelas|first3=Fernando|date=2002-12-01|title=Evolution of arginine deiminase (ADI) pathway genes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790302002774|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|language=en|volume=25|issue=3|pages=429\u2013444|doi=10.1016/S1055-7903(02)00277-4|issn=1055-7903}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma acidarmanus'' ===\n''Ferroplasma acidarmanus'' Fer1 was isolated from mine samples collected at [[Iron Mountain, California|Iron Mountain]], California.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Baker-Austin|first=Craig|last2=Dopson|first2=Mark|last3=Wexler|first3=Margaret|last4=Sawers|first4=R. Gary|last5=Bond|first5=Philip L.|date=2005-08-01|title=Molecular insight into extreme copper resistance in the extremophilic archaeon \u2018Ferroplasma acidarmanus\u2019 Fer1|url=https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/micro/10.1099/mic.0.28076-0|journal=Microbiology|language=en|volume=151|issue=8|pages=2637\u20132646|doi=10.1099/mic.0.28076-0|issn=1350-0872}}</ref> Iron Mountain (CA) is a former mine that is known for its acid mine drainage (AMD) and heavy metal contamination. In addition to being acidophilic, ''F. acidarmanus'' Fer1 is highly resistant to both copper and arsenic.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baker-Austin|first=Craig|last2=Dopson|first2=Mark|last3=Wexler|first3=Margaret|last4=Sawers|first4=R. Gary|last5=Stemmler|first5=Ann|last6=Rosen|first6=Barry P.|last7=Bond|first7=Philip L.|date=2007-05-08|title=Extreme arsenic resistance by the acidophilic archaeon \u2018Ferroplasma acidarmanus\u2019 Fer1|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s00792-006-0052-z|journal=Extremophiles|language=en|volume=11|issue=3|pages=425\u2013434|doi=10.1007/s00792-006-0052-z|issn=1431-0651}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma cupricumulans (formerly Ferroplasma cyprexacervatum)'' ===\nIn 2006 ''Ferroplasma cupricumulans'' was isolated from leachate solution collected from the Myanmar Ivanhoe Copper company (MICCL) mining site in Myanmar.<ref name=\":42\"/> It was noted to be the first slightly thermophilic member of the ''Ferroplasma'' genus. However, in 2009 a new genus of acidophilic, thermophilic archaea, ''Acidiplasma'', was identified. It was proposed that, based on 16S rRNA similarity and DNA-DNA hybridization, be transferred to the ''Acidiplasma'' genus and renamed ''Acidiplasma cupricumulans.''<ref name=\"Golyshina 2815\u20132823\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=O. V.|last2=Yakimov|first2=M. M.|last3=Lunsdorf|first3=H.|last4=Ferrer|first4=M.|last5=Nimtz|first5=M.|last6=Timmis|first6=K. N.|last7=Wray|first7=V.|last8=Tindall|first8=B. J.|last9=Golyshin|first9=P. N.|date=2009-11-01|title=Acidiplasma aeolicum gen. nov., sp. nov., a euryarchaeon of the family Ferroplasmaceae isolated from a hydrothermal pool, and transfer of Ferroplasma cupricumulans to Acidiplasma cupricumulans comb. nov.|url=https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/ijsem/10.1099/ijs.0.009639-0|journal=INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF SYSTEMATIC AND EVOLUTIONARY MICROBIOLOGY|language=en|volume=59|issue=11|pages=2815\u20132823|doi=10.1099/ijs.0.009639-0|issn=1466-5026}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma thermophilum'' ===\nIn 2008, Zhou, et al. described the isolation of the organism ''Ferroplasma thermophilum'' L1<sup>T</sup> from an acid mine drainage (AMD) sample procured at the Daye copper mine in China\u2019s Hubei province.<ref name=\":32\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|last1=Grigor\u2019eva|first1=N. V.|last2=Tsaplina|first2=I. A.|last3=Panyushkina|first3=A. E.|last4=Kondrat\u2019eva|first4=T. F.|title=Optimization of bioleaching and oxidation of gold-bearing pyrite-arsnopyrite ore concentrate in batch mode|journal=Microbiology|date=25 September 2014|volume=83|issue=5|pages=550\u2013557|doi=10.1134/S0026261714040043}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Chen|first1=Ya-Ting|last2=Li|first2=Jin-Tian|last3=Chen|first3=Lin-Xing|last4=Hua|first4=Zheng-Shuang|last5=Huang|first5=Li-Nan|last6=Liu|first6=Jun|last7=Xu|first7=Bi-Bo|last8=Liao|first8=Bin|last9=Shu|first9=Wen-Sheng|title=Biogeochemical Processes Governing Natural Pyrite Oxidation and Release of Acid Metalliferous Drainage|date=20 May 2014|volume=48|issue=10|pages=5537\u20135545|doi=10.1021/es500154z|pmid=24730689|url=|journal=Environ Sci Technol|bibcode=2014EnST...48.5537C}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ohara|first1=Kazuhiro|last2=Unno|first2=Hideaki|last3=Oshima|first3=Yasuhiro|title=Structural Insights into the Low pH Adaptation of a Unique Carboxylesterase from Ferroplasma|doi=10.1074/jbc.M113.521856|publisher=JBC Papers in Press|volume=289|journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry|pages=24499\u201324510|pmid=25043762|pmc=4148875}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Gihring|first1=Thomas M.|last2=Bond|first2=Philip L.|last3=Peters|first3=Stephen C.|last4=Banfield|first4=Jillian F.|title=Arsenic resistance in the archaeon \"Ferroplasma acidarmanus\": new insights into the structure and evolution of the ars genes|journal=Extremophiles|date=2003-04-01|volume=7|issue=2|pages=123\u2013130|doi=10.1007/s00792-002-0303-6|publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]]|issn=1433-4909|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/42444/1/s00792-002-0303-6.pdf}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Eppley|first1=John|last2=Tyson|first2=Gene|last3=Getz|first3=Wayne|last4=Banfield|first4=Jilliam|title=Genetic Exchange Across a Species Boundary in the Archaeal Genus Ferroplasma|date=September 2007|volume=177|issue=1|pages=407\u2013416|doi=10.1534/genetics.107.072892|url=|pmid=17603112|pmc=2013692|journal=Genetics}}\n\n===Scientific journals===\n\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Golyshina OV, Pivovarova TA, Karavaiko GI |display-authors=etal |title=Ferroplasma acidiphilum gen. nov., sp. nov., an acidophilic, autotrophic, ferrous-iron-oxidizing, cell-wall-lacking, mesophilic member of the Ferroplasmaceae fam. nov., comprising a distinct lineage of the Archaea |journal=Int. J. Syst. Evol. Microbiol. |volume=50 |pages=997\u20131006 |date=1 May 2000 |pmid=10843038 |url=http://ijs.sgmjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=10843038 |issue=3 |doi=10.1099/00207713-50-3-997 |doi-access=free }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n===Scientific books===\n\n* {{ cite book |author1=Madigan, M.T.  |author2=Martinko, J.M. | title=Brock Biology of Microorganisms, 11th Ed. | publisher=[[Pearson Prentice Hall]] | date=2005 }}\n\n===Scientific databases===\n\n{{Taxonomic references|taxon=Ferroplasma}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Taxonomic links|microbe=yes|NCBI_taxID=74968|taxoname=Ferroplasma|LSPN_letter=f|LSPN_taxoname=ferroplasma}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2666248}}\n\n[[Category:Archaea genera]]\n[[Category:Metallotolerants]]\n[[Category:Acidophiles]]\n[[Category:Euryarchaeota]]\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| domain = [[Archaea]]\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Euryarchaeota]]\n| phylum = [[Euryarchaeota]]\n| classis = [[Thermoplasmata]]\n| ordo = [[Thermoplasmatales]]\n| familia = [[Ferroplasmaceae]]\n| genus = '''''Ferroplasma'''''\n| genus_authority = Golyshina ''et al.'' 2000\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species (biology)|Species]]\n| subdivision = * ''[[Ferroplasma acidiphilum|F. acidiphilum]]''\n* ''[[Ferroplasma acidarmanus|F. acidarmanus]]''\n* ''[[Ferroplasma thermophilum|F. thermophilum]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Ferroplasma''''' is a genus of [[Archaea]] that belong to the family [[Ferroplasmaceae]]. Members of the ''Ferroplasma'' are typically acidophillic, pleomorphic, irregularly shaped cocci.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite journal|last=Dopson|first=M.|last2=Baker-Austin|first2=C.|last3=Hind|first3=A.|last4=Bowman|first4=J. P.|last5=Bond|first5=P. L.|date=2004-04-01|title=Characterization of Ferroplasma Isolates and Ferroplasma acidarmanus sp. nov., Extreme Acidophiles from Acid Mine Drainage and Industrial Bioleaching Environments|url=http://aem.asm.org/cgi/doi/10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=70|issue=4|pages=2079\u20132088|doi=10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|issn=0099-2240|pmc=383147|pmid=15066799}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|last2=Timmis|first2=Kenneth N.|date=2005|title=Ferroplasma and relatives, recently discovered cell wall-lacking archaea making a living in extremely acid, heavy metal-rich environments|url=https://sfamjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|journal=Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=7|issue=9|pages=1277\u20131288|doi=10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|issn=1462-2920}}</ref>\n\nThe Ferroplasmaceae family of archaea was first described in the early 2000s.<ref name=\":64\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|date=2011-08-01|title=Environmental, Biogeographic, and Biochemical Patterns of Archaea of the Family Ferroplasmaceae|url=http://aem.asm.org/lookup/doi/10.1128/AEM.00726-11|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=77|issue=15|pages=5071\u20135078|doi=10.1128/AEM.00726-11|issn=0099-2240|pmc=3147448|pmid=21685165}}</ref> To date very few species of ''Ferroplasma'' have been isolated and characterized. Isolated species include ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'', ''Ferroplasma acidarmanus,'' and ''Ferroplasma thermophilum''.<ref name=\":03\"/><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhou|first=H.|last2=Zhang|first2=R.|last3=Hu|first3=P.|last4=Zeng|first4=W.|last5=Xie|first5=Y.|last6=Wu|first6=C.|last7=Qiu|first7=G.|date=August 2008|title=Isolation and characterization of Ferroplasma thermophilum sp. nov., a novel extremely acidophilic, moderately thermophilic archaeon and its role in bioleaching of chalcopyrite|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/j.1365-2672.2008.03807.x|journal=Journal of Applied Microbiology|language=en|volume=105|issue=2|pages=591\u2013601|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2672.2008.03807.x}}</ref> A fourth isolate ''Ferroplasma cupricumulans'' was later determined to belong to a separate genus''.''<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite journal|last=Hawkes|first=Rebecca B.|last2=Franzmann|first2=Peter D.|last3=Plumb|first3=Jason J.|date=2006-09-01|title=Moderate thermophiles including \"Ferroplasma cupricumulans\" sp. nov. dominate an industrial-scale chalcocite heap bioleaching operation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304386X06000934|journal=Hydrometallurgy|series=16th International Biohydrometallurgy Symposium|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=229\u2013236|doi=10.1016/j.hydromet.2006.03.027|issn=0304-386X}}</ref><ref name=\"Golyshina 2815\u20132823\"/> All known ''Ferroplasma sp.'' are iron-oxidizers.\n\n== Cell characteristics and Physiology ==\n''Ferroplasma'' cells are pleomorphic and lack a cell-wall.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|last2=Timmis|first2=Kenneth N.|date=2005|title=Ferroplasma and relatives, recently discovered cell wall-lacking archaea making a living in extremely acid, heavy metal-rich environments|url=https://sfamjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|journal=Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=7|issue=9|pages=1277\u20131288|doi=10.1111/j.1462-2920.2005.00861.x|issn=1462-2920}}</ref> All known members of the genera are acidophiles that thrive in environments where pH ranges from 0.0 to 2.0.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Dopson|first=M.|last2=Baker-Austin|first2=C.|last3=Hind|first3=A.|last4=Bowman|first4=J. P.|last5=Bond|first5=P. L.|date=2004-04-01|title=Characterization of Ferroplasma Isolates and Ferroplasma acidarmanus sp. nov., Extreme Acidophiles from Acid Mine Drainage and Industrial Bioleaching Environments|url=http://aem.asm.org/cgi/doi/10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=70|issue=4|pages=2079\u20132088|doi=10.1128/AEM.70.4.2079-2088.2004|issn=0099-2240|pmc=PMC383147|pmid=15066799}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> They are also mesophilic to moderately thermophilic with optimal temperatures ranging from 35-55\u00b0C.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|date=2011-08-01|title=Environmental, Biogeographic, and Biochemical Patterns of Archaea of the Family Ferroplasmaceae|url=http://aem.asm.org/lookup/doi/10.1128/AEM.00726-11|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=77|issue=15|pages=5071\u20135078|doi=10.1128/AEM.00726-11|issn=0099-2240|pmc=PMC3147448|pmid=21685165}}</ref>\n\nTetraether-based lipids are an important part of the ''Ferroplasma'' cellular membrane and allow cells to maintain a pH gradient. A study of ''F.'' ''acidarmanus'' found that cytoplasmic pH was maintained ~5.6 while the environmental pH ranged from ~0-1.2.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Macalady|first=Jennifer L.|last2=Vestling|first2=Martha M.|last3=Baumler|first3=David|last4=Boekelheide|first4=Nick|last5=Kaspar|first5=Charles W.|last6=Banfield|first6=Jillian F.|date=2004-10|title=Tetraether-linked membrane monolayers in Ferroplasma spp: a key to survival in acid|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s00792-004-0404-5|journal=Extremophiles|language=en|volume=8|issue=5|pages=411\u2013419|doi=10.1007/s00792-004-0404-5|issn=1431-0651}}</ref> Variations in the tetraether lipids of the ''Ferroplasmaceae'' family are used for chemotaxonomic identification at the genus and species level because many members possess identical 16S rRNA sequences.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nMembers of the genus ''Ferroplasma'' are chemomixotrophs that can oxidize ferrous iron to acquire energy, but despite evidence of carbon fixation, lab cultures often require an organic carbon source such as yeast extract for growth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> In the absence of iron, some lab-grown strains have been capable of chemoorganotrophic growth.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Ecological Importance ==\nIron is the fourth most abundant mineral in earth's crust. As iron-oxidizers ''Ferroplasma sp.'' participate in the biogeochemical of iron. ''Ferroplasma sp.'' are often identified at acid mine drainage (AMD) sites.<ref name=\":64\"/>\n\n''Ferroplasma sp.'' may have important applications for bioleaching metals. Microbial [[bioleaching]] occurs naturally in the highly acidic environments that are home to ''Ferroplasma sp.'' Harnessing the power of bioleaching to recover metal from low quality ores and waste material is energetically advantageous compared to smelting and purifying.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rohwerder|first=T.|last2=Gehrke|first2=T.|last3=Kinzler|first3=K.|last4=Sand|first4=W.|date=2003-12-01|title=Bioleaching review part A:|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00253-003-1448-7|journal=Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology|language=en|volume=63|issue=3|pages=239\u2013248|doi=10.1007/s00253-003-1448-7|issn=1432-0614}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olson|first=G. J.|last2=Brierley|first2=J. A.|last3=Brierley|first3=C. L.|date=2003-12-01|title=Bioleaching review part B:|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00253-003-1404-6|journal=Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology|language=en|volume=63|issue=3|pages=249\u2013257|doi=10.1007/s00253-003-1404-6|issn=1432-0614}}</ref> It also produces fewer toxic byproducts. Studies have shown that the inclusion of ''Ferroplasma thermophilum'' along with the bacteria ''[[Acidithiobacillus caldus]]'' and ''[[Leptospirillum ferriphilum]]'' can bioaugment the leaching process of chalcopyrite and increase the rate at which copper is recovered.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Lijuan|last2=Wu|first2=Junzi|last3=Wang|first3=Yuguang|last4=Wan|first4=Lili|last5=Mao|first5=Feng|last6=Zhang|first6=Wei|last7=Chen|first7=Xinhua|last8=Zhou|first8=Hongbo|date=May 2014|title=Influence of bioaugmentation with Ferroplasma thermophilum on chalcopyrite bioleaching and microbial community structure|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0304386X1400053X|journal=Hydrometallurgy|language=en|volume=146|pages=15\u201323|doi=10.1016/j.hydromet.2014.02.013}}</ref>\n\n== Isolated Species ==\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' ===\n''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' has been shown to grow as a chemomixotroph and to grow synergistically with the acidophilic bacteria ''Leptospirillum ferriphilum''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Merino|first=M. P.|last2=Andrews|first2=B. A.|last3=Parada|first3=P.|last4=Asenjo|first4=J. A.|date=November 2016|title=Characterization of Ferroplasma acidiphilum growing in pure and mixed culture with Leptospirillum ferriphilum|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1002/btpr.2340|journal=Biotechnology Progress|language=en|volume=32|issue=6|pages=1390\u20131396|doi=10.1002/btpr.2340}}</ref> The strain ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' Y<sup>T</sup> is a facultative anaerobe with all the required genes for arginine fermentation.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=Olga V.|last2=Tran|first2=Hai|last3=Reva|first3=Oleg N.|last4=Lemak|first4=Sofia|last5=Yakunin|first5=Alexander F.|last6=Goesmann|first6=Alexander|last7=Nechitaylo|first7=Taras Y.|last8=LaCono|first8=Violetta|last9=Smedile|first9=Francesco|last10=Slesarev|first10=Alexei|last11=Rojo|first11=David|date=December 2017|title=Metabolic and evolutionary patterns in the extremely acidophilic archaeon Ferroplasma acidiphilum YT|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-017-03904-5|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=3682|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-03904-5|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5473848|pmid=28623373}}</ref> Although it is unclear whether ''Ferroplasma acidiphilum'' Y<sup>T</sup> uses its arginine fermentation pathway, the pathway itself is an ancient metabolism that traces back to the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of the three domains of life.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|first=Manuel|last2=P\u00e9rez|first2=Gaspar|last3=Gonz\u00e1lez-Candelas|first3=Fernando|date=2002-12-01|title=Evolution of arginine deiminase (ADI) pathway genes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790302002774|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|language=en|volume=25|issue=3|pages=429\u2013444|doi=10.1016/S1055-7903(02)00277-4|issn=1055-7903}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma acidarmanus'' ===\n''Ferroplasma acidarmanus'' Fer1 was isolated from mine samples collected at [[Iron Mountain, California|Iron Mountain]], California.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Baker-Austin|first=Craig|last2=Dopson|first2=Mark|last3=Wexler|first3=Margaret|last4=Sawers|first4=R. Gary|last5=Bond|first5=Philip L.|date=2005-08-01|title=Molecular insight into extreme copper resistance in the extremophilic archaeon \u2018Ferroplasma acidarmanus\u2019 Fer1|url=https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/micro/10.1099/mic.0.28076-0|journal=Microbiology|language=en|volume=151|issue=8|pages=2637\u20132646|doi=10.1099/mic.0.28076-0|issn=1350-0872}}</ref> Iron Mountain (CA) is a former mine that is known for its acid mine drainage (AMD) and heavy metal contamination. In addition to being acidophilic, ''F. acidarmanus'' Fer1 is highly resistant to both copper and arsenic.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baker-Austin|first=Craig|last2=Dopson|first2=Mark|last3=Wexler|first3=Margaret|last4=Sawers|first4=R. Gary|last5=Stemmler|first5=Ann|last6=Rosen|first6=Barry P.|last7=Bond|first7=Philip L.|date=2007-05-08|title=Extreme arsenic resistance by the acidophilic archaeon \u2018Ferroplasma acidarmanus\u2019 Fer1|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s00792-006-0052-z|journal=Extremophiles|language=en|volume=11|issue=3|pages=425\u2013434|doi=10.1007/s00792-006-0052-z|issn=1431-0651}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma cupricumulans (formerly Ferroplasma cyprexacervatum)'' ===\nIn 2006 ''Ferroplasma cupricumulans'' was isolated from leachate solution collected from the Myanmar Ivanhoe Copper company (MICCL) mining site in Myanmar.<ref name=\":42\"/> It was noted to be the first slightly thermophilic member of the ''Ferroplasma'' genus. However, in 2009 a new genus of acidophilic, thermophilic archaea, ''Acidiplasma'', was identified. It was proposed that, based on 16S rRNA similarity and DNA-DNA hybridization, be transferred to the ''Acidiplasma'' genus and renamed ''Acidiplasma cupricumulans.''<ref name=\"Golyshina 2815\u20132823\">{{Cite journal|last=Golyshina|first=O. V.|last2=Yakimov|first2=M. M.|last3=Lunsdorf|first3=H.|last4=Ferrer|first4=M.|last5=Nimtz|first5=M.|last6=Timmis|first6=K. N.|last7=Wray|first7=V.|last8=Tindall|first8=B. J.|last9=Golyshin|first9=P. N.|date=2009-11-01|title=Acidiplasma aeolicum gen. nov., sp. nov., a euryarchaeon of the family Ferroplasmaceae isolated from a hydrothermal pool, and transfer of Ferroplasma cupricumulans to Acidiplasma cupricumulans comb. nov.|url=https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/ijsem/10.1099/ijs.0.009639-0|journal=INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF SYSTEMATIC AND EVOLUTIONARY MICROBIOLOGY|language=en|volume=59|issue=11|pages=2815\u20132823|doi=10.1099/ijs.0.009639-0|issn=1466-5026}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ferroplasma thermophilum'' ===\nIn 2008, Zhou, et al. described the isolation of the organism ''Ferroplasma thermophilum'' L1<sup>T</sup> from an acid mine drainage (AMD) sample procured at the Daye copper mine in China\u2019s Hubei province.<ref name=\":32\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|last1=Grigor\u2019eva|first1=N. V.|last2=Tsaplina|first2=I. A.|last3=Panyushkina|first3=A. E.|last4=Kondrat\u2019eva|first4=T. F.|title=Optimization of bioleaching and oxidation of gold-bearing pyrite-arsnopyrite ore concentrate in batch mode|journal=Microbiology|date=25 September 2014|volume=83|issue=5|pages=550\u2013557|doi=10.1134/S0026261714040043}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Chen|first1=Ya-Ting|last2=Li|first2=Jin-Tian|last3=Chen|first3=Lin-Xing|last4=Hua|first4=Zheng-Shuang|last5=Huang|first5=Li-Nan|last6=Liu|first6=Jun|last7=Xu|first7=Bi-Bo|last8=Liao|first8=Bin|last9=Shu|first9=Wen-Sheng|title=Biogeochemical Processes Governing Natural Pyrite Oxidation and Release of Acid Metalliferous Drainage|date=20 May 2014|volume=48|issue=10|pages=5537\u20135545|doi=10.1021/es500154z|pmid=24730689|url=|journal=Environ Sci Technol|bibcode=2014EnST...48.5537C}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ohara|first1=Kazuhiro|last2=Unno|first2=Hideaki|last3=Oshima|first3=Yasuhiro|title=Structural Insights into the Low pH Adaptation of a Unique Carboxylesterase from Ferroplasma|doi=10.1074/jbc.M113.521856|publisher=JBC Papers in Press|volume=289|journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry|pages=24499\u201324510|pmid=25043762|pmc=4148875}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Gihring|first1=Thomas M.|last2=Bond|first2=Philip L.|last3=Peters|first3=Stephen C.|last4=Banfield|first4=Jillian F.|title=Arsenic resistance in the archaeon \"Ferroplasma acidarmanus\": new insights into the structure and evolution of the ars genes|journal=Extremophiles|date=2003-04-01|volume=7|issue=2|pages=123\u2013130|doi=10.1007/s00792-002-0303-6|publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]]|issn=1433-4909|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/42444/1/s00792-002-0303-6.pdf}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Eppley|first1=John|last2=Tyson|first2=Gene|last3=Getz|first3=Wayne|last4=Banfield|first4=Jilliam|title=Genetic Exchange Across a Species Boundary in the Archaeal Genus Ferroplasma|date=September 2007|volume=177|issue=1|pages=407\u2013416|doi=10.1534/genetics.107.072892|url=|pmid=17603112|pmc=2013692|journal=Genetics}}\n\n===Scientific journals===\n\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Golyshina OV, Pivovarova TA, Karavaiko GI |display-authors=etal |title=Ferroplasma acidiphilum gen. nov., sp. nov., an acidophilic, autotrophic, ferrous-iron-oxidizing, cell-wall-lacking, mesophilic member of the Ferroplasmaceae fam. nov., comprising a distinct lineage of the Archaea |journal=Int. J. Syst. Evol. Microbiol. |volume=50 |pages=997\u20131006 |date=1 May 2000 |pmid=10843038 |url=http://ijs.sgmjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=10843038 |issue=3 |doi=10.1099/00207713-50-3-997 |doi-access=free }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n===Scientific books===\n\n* {{ cite book |author1=Madigan, M.T.  |author2=Martinko, J.M. | title=Brock Biology of Microorganisms, 11th Ed. | publisher=[[Pearson Prentice Hall]] | date=2005 }}\n\n===Scientific databases===\n\n{{Taxonomic references|taxon=Ferroplasma}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Taxonomic links|microbe=yes|NCBI_taxID=74968|taxoname=Ferroplasma|LSPN_letter=f|LSPN_taxoname=ferroplasma}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2666248}}\n\n[[Category:Archaea genera]]\n[[Category:Metallotolerants]]\n[[Category:Acidophiles]]\n[[Category:Euryarchaeota]]\n", "name_user": "Rhoover5", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed dash in date error.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferroplasma"}
{"title_page": "Citizen science", "text_new": "{{short description|Scientific research conducted, in whole or in part, by amateur or nonprofessional scientists}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n'''Citizen science''' ('''CS'''; also known as '''community science''', '''crowd science''', '''crowd-sourced science''', '''civic science''', '''volunteer monitoring''', or '''online citizen science''') is [[scientific research]] conducted, in whole or in part, by [[amateur]] (or nonprofessional) [[scientist]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Gura, Trisha|title=Citizen science: amateur experts|journal=Nature|volume=496|issue=7444|year=2013|pages=259\u2013261|doi=10.1038/nj7444-259a|pmid=23586092}}</ref> Citizen science is sometimes described as \"[[public participation]] in scientific research,\" [[participatory monitoring]], and [[participatory action research]] whose outcomes are often advancements in scientific research, as well as an increase in the public's understanding of science.<ref name=Hand_1>{{Cite journal |last1 = Hand |first1 = E. |title = Citizen science: People power |doi = 10.1038/466685a |journal = Nature |volume = 466 |issue = 7307 |pages = 685\u2013687 |year = 2010 |pmid = 20686547}}</ref><ref name=UTW_1>{{Cite book| title=Using the Web for Science in the Classroom: Online Citizen Science Participation in Teaching and Learning| author1=C. Doyle| author2=R. David| author3=Y.Li| author4=M. Luczak-Roesch| author5=D. Anderson| author6=C.M Pearson| url=https://osf.io/n953p| date=30 June 2019| access-date=30 July 2019| doi=10.1145/3292522.3326022| isbn=978-1-4503-6202-3}}</ref> Based on Alexa rankings<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com|title=Alexa.com}}</ref> [[iNaturalist]] is currently the most popular citizen science website<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/inaturalist.org|title=Alexa.com: inaturalist.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic}}</ref> followed by [[eBird]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/ebird.org|title=Alexa.com: ebird.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic}}</ref> and then [[Zooniverse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/zooniverse.org|title=Alexa.com: zooniverse.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic}}</ref> in second and third place respectively.{{Update-inline|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Scanning the cliffs near Logan Pass for mountain goats (Citizen Science) (4427399123).jpg|thumb|right|Scanning the cliffs near [[Logan Pass]] for mountain goats as part of the [[Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Glacier National Park]] Citizen Science Program]]\n\n== Definition ==\n\nThe term CS has multiple origins, as well as differing concepts.<ref name=\"Re&Po\">{{cite journal|title=Citizen science as seen by scientists: Methodological, epistemological and ethical dimensions|author1=H. Riesch|author2=C. Potter|date=2014|pages=107\u2013120|doi=10.1177/0963662513497324|pmid=23982281|journal=Public Understanding of Science|volume=23|issue=1|url=http://bura.brunel.ac.uk/handle/2438/10337}}</ref> It was first defined independently in the mid-1990s by [[Rick Bonney]] in the United States and [[Alan Irwin (academic)|Alan Irwin]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name=Re&Po/><ref name=\"A.I.\">{{cite book|title=Citizen Science: A Study of People, Expertise and Sustainable Development|last=Irwin|first=Alan|date=1995|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415130103|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=R.Bonney>{{cite report |first1=Rick |last1=Bonney |first2=Heidi |last2=Ballard |first3=Rebecca |last3=Jordan |first4=Ellen |last4=McCallie |first5=Tina |last5=Phillips |first6=Jennifer |last6=Shirk |first7=Candie C. |last7=Wilderman |date=July 2009 |title=Public Participation in Scientific Research: Defining the Field and Assessing Its Potential for Informal Science Education |publisher=Center for Advancement of Informal Science Education |url=http://www.birds.cornell.edu/citscitoolkit/publications/CAISE-PPSR-report-2009.pdf/view }}</ref> Alan Irwin, a British sociologist, defines CS as \"developing concepts of scientific citizenship which foregrounds the necessity of opening up science and science policy processes to the public\".<ref name=Re&Po/> Irwin sought to reclaim two dimensions of the relationship between citizens and science: 1) that science should be responsive to citizens' concerns and needs; and 2) that citizens themselves could produce reliable scientific knowledge.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=The Rightful Place of Science: Citizen Science|last=Cavalier|first=Darlene|last2=Kennedy|first2=Eric|publisher=Consortium for Science, Policy & Outcomes|year=2016|isbn=9780692694831|location=Tempe, AZ|page=54|via=}}</ref> The American ornithologist Rick Bonney, unaware of Irwin's work, defined CS as projects in which nonscientists, such as amateur birdwatchers, voluntarily contributed scientific data. This describes a more limited role for citizens in scientific research than Irwin's conception of the term.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe terms ''citizen science'' and ''citizen scientists'' entered the [[Oxford English Dictionary]] (''OED'') in June 2014.<ref>{{cite dictionary|title=New words list June 2014|url=http://public.oed.com/the-oed-today/recent-updates-to-the-oed/previous%20updates/june-2014-update/new-words-list-june-2014|dictionary=Oxford English Dictionary|accessdate=3 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509083230/http://public.oed.com/the-oed-today/recent-updates-to-the-oed/previous%20updates/june-2014-update/new-words-list-june-2014|archivedate=9 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Zoo_OED>{{cite web|title='Citizen science' added to Oxford English Dictionary|url=https://daily.zooniverse.org/2014/09/16/citizen-science-in-dictionary|publisher=The Daily Zooniverse|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=3 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616165001/https://daily.zooniverse.org/2014/09/16/citizen-science-in-dictionary/|archivedate=16 June 2016}}</ref> \"Citizen science\" is defined as \"scientific work undertaken by members of the general public, often in collaboration with or under the direction of professional scientists and scientific institutions\".<ref name=Zoo_OED/> \"Citizen scientist\" is defined as: (a) \"a scientist whose work is characterized by a sense of responsibility to serve the best interests of the wider community (now rare)\"; or (b) \"a member of the general public who engages in scientific work, often in collaboration with or under the direction of professional scientists and scientific institutions; an amateur scientist\".<ref name=Zoo_OED/> The first use of the term \"citizen scientist\" can be found in the magazine ''[[New Scientist]]'' in an article about [[ufology]] from October 1979.<ref name=Oberg>{{cite magazine|title=The Failure of the 'Science' of Ufology|author=James Oberg|journal=New Scientist|date=11 October 1979|volume=84|issue=1176|pages=102\u2013105}}</ref>\n\nMuki Haklay cites, from a policy report for the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|Wilson Center]] entitled \"Citizen Science and Policy: A European Perspective\", an alternate first use of the term \"citizen science\" by R. Kerson in the magazine ''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' from January 1989.<ref name=1stUse>{{cite web|author=Muki Haklay|title=Citizen Science and Policy: A European Perspective|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/Citizen_Science_Policy_European_Perspective_Haklay.pdf|publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|page=11|date=2015|accessdate=3 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018170921/https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/Citizen_Science_Policy_European_Perspective_Haklay.pdf|archivedate=18 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=Kerson>{{cite magazine|author=R. Kerson|title=Lab for the Environment|journal=MIT Technology Review|date=1989|volume=92|issue=1|pages=11\u201312}}</ref> Quoting from the Wilson Center report: \"The new form of engagement in science received the name 'citizen science'. The first recorded example of the use of the term is from 1989, describing how 225 volunteers across the US collected rain samples to assist the [[National Audubon Society|Audubon Society]] in an acid-rain awareness raising campaign.\"<ref name=1stUse/><ref name=Kerson/>\n\nA ''\"Green Paper on Citizen Science\"'' was published in 2013 by the [[European Commission]]'s Digital Science Unit and Socientize.eu, which included a definition for CS, referring to \"the general public engagement in scientific research activities when citizens actively contribute to science either with their intellectual effort or surrounding knowledge or with their tools and resources. Participants provide experimental data and facilities for researchers, raise new questions and co-create a new scientific culture.\"<ref name=GP_CS_EU>{{cite web|title=Green paper on Citizen Science for Europe: Towards a society of empowered citizens and enhanced research|url=https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/news/green-paper-citizen-science-europe-towards-society-empowered-citizens-and-enhanced-research|publisher=European Commission|date=21 January 2014|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017015723/https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/news/green-paper-citizen-science-europe-towards-society-empowered-citizens-and-enhanced-research|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=EU_GrPa>{{cite web|title=Green paper on Citizen Science|url=http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/dae/document.cfm?doc_id=4122|publisher=Socientize.eu|page=6|date=2013|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226063915/http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/dae/document.cfm?doc_id=4122|archivedate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nCitizen science may be performed by individuals, teams, or networks of volunteers. Citizen scientists often partner with professional scientists to achieve common goals. Large volunteer networks often allow scientists to accomplish tasks that would be too expensive or time-consuming to accomplish through other means.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Silvertown|first=Jonathan|title=A new dawn for citizen science|journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution|volume=24|issue=9|pages=467\u2013471|doi=10.1016/j.tree.2009.03.017|pmid=19586682|year=2009}}</ref>\n\nMany citizen-science projects serve education and outreach goals.<ref>{{Cite book |last1 = Osborn |first1 = D. A. |doi = 10.1061/40761(175)57 |chapter = Monitoring Rocky Intertidal Shorelines: A Role for the Public in Resource Management |title = California and the World Ocean 02 |volume = 175 |page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780784407615/page/57 57] |year = 2002 |isbn = 978-0-7844-0761-5 |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780784407615/page/57 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Brossard |first1 = D. |last2 = Lewenstein |first2 = B. |last3 = Bonney |first3 = R. |doi = 10.1080/09500690500069483 |title = Scientific knowledge and attitude change: The impact of a citizen science project |journal = International Journal of Science Education |volume = 27 |issue = 9 |pages = 1099\u20131121 |year = 2005 |bibcode = 2005IJSEd..27.1099B|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6ef660acdad8b5faf8b5be387292eb45a9a3afc9 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Bauer |first1 = M. W. |last2 = Petkova |first2 = K. |last3 = Boyadjieva |first3 = P. |title = Public Knowledge of and Attitudes to Science: Alternative Measures That May End the \"Science War\" |doi = 10.1177/016224390002500102 |journal = Science, Technology & Human Values |volume = 25 |pages = 30\u201351 |year = 2000 }}</ref> These projects may be designed for a formal classroom environment or an informal education environment such as museums.\n\nCitizen science has evolved over the past four decades. Recent projects place more emphasis on scientifically sound practices and measurable goals for public education.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Bonney |first1 = R. |last2 = Cooper |first2 = C. B. |last3 = Dickinson |first3 = J. |last4 = Kelling |first4 = S. |last5 = Phillips |first5 = T. |last6 = Rosenberg |first6 = K. V. |last7 = Shirk |first7 = J. |doi = 10.1525/bio.2009.59.11.9 |title = Citizen Science: A Developing Tool for Expanding Science Knowledge and Scientific Literacy |journal = BioScience |volume = 59 |issue = 11 |pages = 977\u2013984 |year = 2009 }}</ref> Modern citizen science differs from its historical forms primarily in the access for, and subsequent scale of, public participation; technology is credited as one of the main drivers of the recent explosion of citizen science activity.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Silvertown |first1 = J. |title = A new dawn for citizen science |doi = 10.1016/j.tree.2009.03.017 |journal = Trends in Ecology & Evolution |volume = 24 |issue = 9 |pages = 467\u2013471|year = 2009 |pmid =  19586682}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, the [[Office of Science and Technology Policy]] published a factsheet entitled \"Empowering Students and Others through Citizen Science and Crowdsourcing\".<ref name=OSTP_2015>{{cite web|title=Fact Sheet: Empowering Students and Others through Citizen Science and Crowdsourcing|author=OSTP|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/citizen_science_backgrounder_03-23-15.pdf|publisher=The White House|date=23 March 2015|accessdate=24 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322013634/https://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/citizen_science_backgrounder_march-23.pdf|archivedate=22 March 2016}}</ref> Quoting: \"Citizen science and crowdsourcing projects are powerful tools for providing students with skills needed to excel in science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM). Volunteers in citizen science, for example, gain hands-on experience doing real science, and in many cases take that learning outside of the traditional classroom setting\".<ref name=OSTP_2015/>\n\n[[File:Cascades Butterfly Project Team (8273990532).jpg|thumb|right|Members of the [[Cascade Range|Cascades]] Butterfly Citizen Science Team pictured on Sauk mountain]]\nIn May 2016, a new [[open-access journal]] was started by the [[Citizen Science Association]] along with [[Ubiquity Press]] called ''Citizen Science: Theory and Practice'' (CS:T&P).<ref name=CS:T&P_Web>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science: Theory and Practice|url=http://theoryandpractice.citizenscienceassociation.org|publisher=The Citizen Science Association and Ubiquity Press|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=22 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524120333/http://theoryandpractice.citizenscienceassociation.org/|archivedate=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=CS_T&P>{{cite journal|author1=R. Bonney|author2=C. Cooper|author3=H. Ballard|title=The Theory and Practice of Citizen Science: Launching a New Journal|date=20 May 2016|journal=Citizen Science: Theory and Practice|volume=1|issue=1|page=1|doi=10.5334/cstp.65}}</ref> Quoting from the editorial article titled \"The Theory and Practice of Citizen Science: Launching a New Journal\", \"CS:T&P provides the space to enhance the quality and impact of citizen science efforts by deeply exploring the citizen science concept in all its forms and across disciplines. By examining, critiquing, and sharing findings across a variety of citizen science endeavors, we can dig into the underpinnings and assumptions of citizen science and critically analyze its practice and outcomes.\"<ref name=CS_T&P/>\n\n===Alternative definitions===\n\nOther definitions for citizen science have also been proposed. For example, Bruce Lewenstein of [[Cornell University]]'s [[Communication studies|Communication]] and [[Science and technology studies|S&TS]] departments describes 3 possible definitions:<ref name=\"Lewenstein_2004\">{{cite journal|last=Lewenstein|first=B.|date=8 June 2004|title=What does citizen science accomplish?|url=http://ecommons.library.cornell.edu/handle/1813/37362|url-status=live|journal=|publisher=Cornell University|volume=|pages=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009065556/http://ecommons.library.cornell.edu/handle/1813/37362|archivedate=9 October 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014|via=}}</ref>\n* The participation of nonscientists in the process of gathering data according to specific scientific protocols and in the process of using and interpreting that data.<ref name=Lewenstein_2004/>\n* The engagement of nonscientists in true decision-making about policy issues that have technical or scientific components.<ref name=Lewenstein_2004/>\n* The engagement of research scientists in the democratic and policy process.<ref name=Lewenstein_2004/>\n\nScientists and scholars who have used other definitions include [[Frank N. von Hippel]], [[Stephen Schneider]], [[Neal Francis Lane|Neal Lane]] and [[Jon Beckwith]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Von Hippel, Frank |title=Citizen scientist |publisher=[[American Institute of Physics]] |location=New York |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-88318-709-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Beckwith, Jonathan R. |authorlink=Jon Beckwith|title=Making genes, making waves: a social activist in science |url=https://archive.org/details/makinggenesmakin0000beck |url-access=registration |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-674-00928-8 }}</ref><ref>Neal Lane, \"Remarks\" at Panel Discussion on Future of Federal Funding for Science and Engineering, [[Rutgers University]], 8 April 1996. [https://www.nsf.gov/news/speeches/lane/slrtgrs.htm Steve Schneider remarks at AAAS meeting, February 1997] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929095756/https://www.nsf.gov/news/speeches/lane/slrtgrs.htm |date=29 September 2007 }}; see here {{cite web |url=http://news-service.stanford.edu/pr/97/970210schneider.html |title=Schneider offers three questions to make a citizen-scientist (2/97) |accessdate=18 August 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609092054/http://news-service.stanford.edu/pr/97/970210schneider.html |archivedate=9 June 2007 }}</ref> Other alternative terminologies proposed are \"civic science\" and \"civic scientist\".<ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Clark |first1 = F. |last2 = Illman |first2 = D. L. |doi = 10.1177/1075547001023001002 |title = Dimensions of Civic Science: Introductory Essay |journal = Science Communication |volume = 23 |pages = 5\u201327 |year = 2001 }}</ref>\n\nFurther, Muki Haklay offers an overview of the typologies of the level of citizen participation in citizen science, which range from \"crowdsourcing\" (level 1), where the citizen acts as a sensor, to \"distributed intelligence\" (level 2), where the citizen acts as a basic interpreter, to \"participatory science\", where citizens contribute to problem definition and data collection (level 3), to \"extreme citizen science\", which involves collaboration between the citizen and scientists in problem definition, collection and data analysis.<ref>Haklay, Muki (2012) in Citizen Science and Volunteered Geographic Information: Overview and Typology of Participation. Crowdsourcing Geographic Knowledge. 2013, pp. 105\u2013122.</ref>\n\nA 2014 [[Mashable]] article defines a citizen scientist as: \"Anybody who voluntarily contributes his or her time and resources toward scientific research in partnership with professional scientists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2014/05/26/citizen-science/|title=What Is Citizen Science, and How Can You Get Involved?|author=Eric Larson|date=26 May 2014|work=Mashable|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110231048/http://mashable.com/2014/05/26/citizen-science/|archivedate=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the [[Australian Citizen Science Association]] released their definition which states \"Citizen science involves public participation and collaboration in scientific research with the aim to increase scientific knowledge.\"<ref name=ACSA_1>{{cite web| title=What is Citizen Science?| url=https://citizenscience.org.au/who-we-are| publisher=Australian Citizen Science Association| access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=ACSA_2>{{cite web| title=Discover Another Side of Scientific Research| url=https://citizenscience.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Australian-Citizen-Science-Association-brochure.pdf| publisher=Australian Citizen Science Association| access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the book \"Analyzing the Role of Citizen Science in Modern Research\" defined citizen science as \"work undertaken by civic educators together with citizen communities to advance science, foster a broad scientific mentality, and/or encourage democratic engagement, which allows society to deal rationally with complex modern problems\".<ref>{{cite book| title=Analyzing the role of citizen science in modern research|author=Ceccaroni, L., & Piera, J. (Eds.)|date=2016| url=https://www.igi-global.com/book/analyzing-role-citizen-science-modern/154745| publisher=IGI Global| access-date=27 September 2018|isbn=9781522509622}}</ref>\n\n===Related fields===\n\nIn a [[Smart City]] era, Citizen Science relays on various web-based tools (eg.[[Web mapping|WebGIS)]] and becomes Cyber Citizen Science.<ref name=WebGIS_1>{{cite journal| title=Citizen science and WebGIS for outdoor advertisement visual pollution assessment| author1=S. Chmielewski| author2=M. Samulowska| author3=M. Lupa| author4=B. Zagajewski| journal=Computers Environment and Urban Systems| volume=67| pages=97\u2013109| doi=10.1016/j.compenvurbsys.2017.09.001| year=2018}}</ref> Some projects, such as [[SETI@home]], use the Internet to take advantage of [[distributed computing]]. These projects are generally passive. Computation tasks are performed by volunteers' computers and require little involvement beyond initial setup. There is disagreement as to whether these projects should be classified as citizen science.\n\nThe astrophysicist and [[Galaxy Zoo]] co-founder [[Kevin Schawinski]] stated: \"We prefer to call this [Galaxy Zoo] citizen science because it's a better description of what you're doing; you're a regular citizen but you're doing science. Crowd sourcing sounds a bit like, well, you're just a member of the crowd and you're not; you're our collaborator. You're pro-actively involved in the process of science by participating.\"<ref name=AnthonyWilliams>{{cite web|title=Crowdsourcing versus citizen science|author=A. Williams|url=http://anthonydwilliams.com/2009/02/09/crowdsourcing-versus-citizen-science|publisher=Anthony D. Williams|date=9 February 2009|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915231600/http://anthonydwilliams.com/2009/02/09/crowdsourcing-versus-citizen-science/|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nCompared to SETI@home, \"Galaxy Zoo volunteers do real work. They're not just passively running something on their computer and hoping that they'll be the first person to find aliens. They have a stake in science that comes out of it, which means that they are now interested in what we do with it, and what we find.\"<ref name=AnthonyWilliams/>\n\nCitizen policy may be another result of citizen science initiatives. Bethany Brookshire (pen name SciCurious) writes: \"If citizens are going to live with the benefits or potential consequences of science (as the vast majority of them will), it's incredibly important to make sure that they are not only well informed about changes and advances in science and technology, but that they also ... are able to ... influence the science policy decisions that could impact their lives.\"<ref name=SciCur>{{cite magazine|title=Citizen Science, Citizen Policy|author=SciCurious|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/scicurious-brain/citizen-science-citizen-policy/|magazine=Scientific American|date=7 January 2013|accessdate=23 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423064500/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/scicurious-brain/citizen-science-citizen-policy/|archivedate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits and limitations===\n\nCitizen involvement in scientific projects has become a means of encouraging curiosity and greater understanding of science whilst providing an unprecedented engagement between professional scientists and the general public.<ref name=UTW_1/> In a research report published by the [[National Park Service]] in 2008, Brett Amy Thelen and Rachel K. Thiet mention the following concerns, previously reported in the literature, about the validity of volunteer-generated data:<ref name=Cape_Cod_CS>{{cite journal |title=Cultivating connection: Incorporating meaningful citizen science into Cape Cod National Seashore's estuarine research and monitoring programs |last1=Thelen |first1=Brett Amy |last2=Thiet |first2=Rachel K. |journal=Park Science |volume=25 |issue=1 |year=2008 |citeseerx=10.1.1.692.656 }} </ref>\n* Some projects may not be suitable for volunteers, for instance, when they use complex research methods or require a lot of (often repetitive) work.<ref name=Cape_Cod_CS/>\n* If volunteers lack proper training in research and monitoring protocols, they are at risk of introducing bias into the data.<ref name=Cape_Cod_CS/>\n\nThe question of data accuracy, in particular, remains open.<ref name=\"Fr\u00edas 2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Fr\u00edas |first1=O. |last2=Bautista |first2=L. M. |last3=D\u00e9nes |first3=F. V.  |last4=Cuevas |first4=J. A. |last5= Mart\u00ednez |first5=F. |last6=Blanco |first6=G. |year=2018 |title=Influence of habitat suitability and sex-related detectability on density and population size estimates of habitat-specialist warblers |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=13 |issue=7 |page=020148 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0201482|pmid=30059562 |pmc=6066240 |bibcode=2018PLoSO..1301482F }}</ref> John Losey, who created the [[Lost Ladybug Project|Lost Ladybug]] citizen science project, has argued that the cost-effectiveness of citizen science data can outweigh data quality issues, if properly managed.<ref name=LadyBeatles>{{cite journal|author1=M. M. Gardiner |author2=L. L. Allee |author3=P. M. J. Brown |author4=J. E. Losey |author5=H. E. Roy |author6=R. Rice Smyth |title=Lessons from lady beetles: accuracy of monitoring data from US and UK citizen-science programs|journal=[[Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment]]|date=November 2012|volume=10|issue=9 |doi=10.1890/110185 |pages=471\u2013476|url=http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/id/eprint/20992/1/N020992JA.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, authors M. Kosmala, A. Wiggins, A. Swanson and B. Simmons published a study in the journal [[Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment]] called \"Assessing Data Quality in Citizen Science\".<ref name=ADQ>{{cite journal| author1=Margaret Kosmala| author2=Andrea Wiggins| author3=Alexandra Swanson| author4=Brooke Simmons| title=Assessing Data Quality in Citizen Science| journal=[[Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment]]| volume=14| issue=10| pages=551\u2013560| date=1 December 2016| doi=10.1002/fee.1436| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ee013b1477e8f81cb5c66a9a93a342281f740042}}</ref> The abstract describes how ecological and environmental CS projects have enormous potential to advance science. Also, CS projects can influence policy and guide resource management by producing [[dataset]]s that are otherwise infeasible to generate.<ref name=ADQ/> In the section \"In a Nutshell\" (pg3), four condensed conclusions are stated. They are:<ref name=ADQ/>\n\n{{quote frame|\n# Datasets produced by volunteer CSs can have reliably high quality, on par with those produced by professionals.\n# Individual volunteer accuracy varies, depending on task difficulty and volunteer experience. Multiple methods exist for boosting accuracy to required levels for a given project.\n# Most types of [[bias]] found in CS datasets are also found in professionally produced datasets and can be accommodated using existing statistical tools.\n# Reviewers of CS projects should look for iterated project design, standardization and appropriateness of volunteer protocols and data analyses, capture of [[metadata]], and accuracy assessment.\n}}\n\nThey conclude that as CS continues to grow and mature, a key metric of project success they expect to see will be a growing awareness of data quality. They also conclude that CS will emerge as a general tool helping \"to collect otherwise unobtainable high-quality data in support of policy and resource management, conservation monitoring, and basic science.\"<ref name=ADQ/>\n\nA study of Canadian lepidoptera datasets published in 2018 compared the use of a professionally curated dataset of butterfly specimen records with four years of data from a CS program, [[eButterfly]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Semeniuk |first1=Ivan |title=The butterfly effect: How Canadians and their smartphones are helping scientists map species diversity |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/technology/science/article-the-butterfly-effect-how-canadians-and-their-smartphones-are-helping/ |accessdate=13 October 2018 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=7 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013040152/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/technology/science/article-the-butterfly-effect-how-canadians-and-their-smartphones-are-helping/ |archivedate=13 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Soroye |first1=Peter |last2=Ahmed |first2=Najeeba |last3=Kerr |first3=Jeremy T. |title=Opportunistic citizen science data transform understanding of species distributions, phenology, and diversity gradients for global change research |journal=Global Change Biology |volume=24 |issue=11 |pages=5281\u20135291 |date=3 July 2018 |doi=10.1111/gcb.14358 |pmid=29920854 |bibcode=2018GCBio..24.5281S }}</ref> The eButterfly dataset was used as it was determined to be of high quality because of the expert vetting process used on the site, and there existed a historic dataset covering the same geographic area consisting of specimen data, much of it institutional.  The authors note that, in this case, CS data provides both novel and complementary information to the specimen data. Five new species were reported from the CS data, and geographic distribution information was improved for over 80% of species in the combined dataset when CS data was included.\n\n====Law====\n{{main|Wyoming Senate Files 12 and 80 2015 'Trespassing To Collect Data'}}\nIn March 2015, the state of [[Wyoming]] passed new laws (Senate Files 12 and 80) clarifying that trespassing laws applied even if the trespasser's intention was to gather data to further a U.S. government science program.<ref name=CourthouseNewsService>{{cite web|author=Emma Gannon|title=Wyoming Criminalizes Citizen Science|url=http://www.courthousenews.com/2015/05/18/wyoming-criminalizes-citizen-science.htm|publisher=Courthouse News Service|date=18 May 2015|accessdate=29 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209050810/http://www.courthousenews.com/2015/05/18/wyoming-criminalizes-citizen-science.htm|archivedate=9 February 2016}}</ref> This hampered some CS researchers who were collecting data while on other people's land.\n\n==Ethics==\n\nVarious studies have been published that explore the [[ethics]] of CS, including issues such as [[intellectual property]] and project design.(e.g.<ref name=Re&Po/><ref name=Resnik_2015>{{cite journal|title=A framework for addressing ethical issues in citizen science|author1=D. B. Resnik|author2=K. C. Elliot|author3=A. K. Miller|journal=Environmental Science & Policy|volume=54|pages=475\u2013481|date=December 2015|doi=10.1016/j.envsci.2015.05.008|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1258927}}</ref><ref name=Bowser_2015>{{cite journal|title=Privacy in Participatory Research: Advancing Policy to support Human Computation|author1=A. E. Bowser|author2=A. Wiggins|journal=Human Computation|volume=2|issue=1|date=2015|pages=19\u201344|doi=10.15346/hc.v2i1.3}}</ref><ref name=Hoffman_2014>{{cite journal|title=Citizen Science: The Law and Ethics of Public Access to Medical Big Data|author=S. Hoffman|journal=Berkeley Technology Law Journal|date=September 2014|volume=Case Legal Studies Research Paper No. 2014-21}}</ref><ref name=Scassa_2015>{{cite web|title=Managing Intellectual Property Rights in Citizen Science: A Guide for Researchers and Citizen Scientists|author1=T. Scassa|author2=Chung H.|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/managing_intellectual_property_rights_citizen_science_scassa_chung.pdf|publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|date=2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705153453/https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/managing_intellectual_property_rights_citizen_science_scassa_chung.pdf|archivedate=5 July 2017}}</ref>) The [[Citizen Science Association|Citizen Science Association (CSA)]], based at the [[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]], and the [[European Citizen Science Association| European Citizen Science Association (ECSA)]], based in the [[Museum f\u00fcr Naturkunde]] in Berlin, have working groups on ethics and principles.<ref name=CSA_1>{{cite web|title=CSA Working Group on Ethics|url=http://citizenscience.org/association/about/working-groups/ethics-working-group/|publisher=Citizen Science Association|accessdate=24 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825062443/http://citizenscience.org/association/about/working-groups/ethics-working-group/|archivedate=25 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=ECSA_2>{{cite web|title=ECSA Principles & Standards in Citizen Science: Sharing Best Practice & Building Capacity|url=http://www.ecsa.citizen-science.net/taxonomy/term/205|publisher=ECSA|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818072003/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/taxonomy/term/205|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the European Citizen Science Association (ECSA) published its ''Ten Principles of Citizen Science'', which have been developed by the \"Sharing best practice and building capacity\" working group of the ECSA, led by the [[Natural History Museum, London]] with input from many members of the association.<ref name=ECSA_10>{{cite web|author=European Citizen Science Association|title=10 Principles of Citizen Science (English)|url=http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/sites/default/files/ecsa_ten_principles_of_citizen_science.pdf|publisher=ECSA|date=September 2015|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822040236/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/sites/default/files/ecsa_ten_principles_of_citizen_science.pdf|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=ECSA_Docs>{{cite web|title=ECSA Documents|url=http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/documents|publisher=ECSA|date=September 2015|access-date=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822042534/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/documents|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n{{quote frame|\n# Citizen science projects actively involve citizens in scientific endeavour that generates new knowledge or understanding. Citizens may act as contributors, collaborators, or as project leader and have a meaningful role in the project.\n# Citizen science projects have a genuine science outcome. For example, answering a research question or informing conservation action, management decisions or environmental policy.\n# Both the professional scientists and the citizen scientists benefit from taking part. Benefits may include the publication of research outputs, learning opportunities, personal enjoyment, social benefits, satisfaction through contributing to scientific evidence e.g. to address local, national and international issues, and through that, the potential to influence policy.\n# Citizen scientists may, if they wish, participate in multiple stages of the scientific process. This may include developing the research question, designing the method, gathering and analysing data, and communicating the results.\n# Citizen scientists receive feedback from the project. For example, how their data are being used and what the research, policy or societal outcomes are.\n# Citizen science is considered a research approach like any other, with limitations and biases that should be considered and controlled for. However unlike traditional research approaches, citizen science provides opportunity for greater public engagement and democratisation of science.\n# Citizen science project data and meta-data are made publicly available and where possible, results are published in an open access format. [[Data sharing]] may occur during or after the project, unless there are security or privacy concerns that prevent this.\n# Citizen scientists are acknowledged in project results and publications.\n# Citizen science programmes are evaluated for their scientific output, data quality, participant experience and wider societal or policy impact.\n# The leaders of citizen science projects take into consideration legal and ethical issues surrounding copyright, intellectual property, data sharing agreements, confidentiality, attribution, and the environmental impact of any activities.\n}}\n\nThe medical ethics of internet crowdsourcing has been questioned by Graber & Graber in the ''[[Journal of Medical Ethics]]''.<ref name=Graber_1>{{cite journal|author1=M. A. Graber |author2=A. Graber |title=Internet-based crowdsourcing and research ethics:the case for IRB review|journal=Journal of Medical Ethics|date=30 November 2012|doi=10.1136/medethics-2012-100798|pmid=23204319 |volume=39|issue=2 |pages=115\u2013118}}</ref> In particular, they analyse the effect of games and the crowdsourcing project [[Foldit]]. They conclude: \"games can have possible adverse effects, and that they manipulate the user into participation\".\n\nIn March 2019 the online journal ''Citizen Science: Theory and Practice'' launched a collection of articles\non the theme of Ethical Issues in Citizen Science.<ref name=CSTP_2>{{cite journal| title=Ethical Issues in Citizen Science| url=https://theoryandpractice.citizenscienceassociation.org/collections/special/ethical-issues-in-citizen-science| journal=Citizen Science: Theory and Practice| publisher=[[Ubiquity Press]]| date=7 March 2019| access-date=12 March 2019}}</ref> The articles are introduced with (quoting): \"Citizen science can challenge existing ethical norms because it falls outside of customary methods of ensuring that research is conducted ethically. What ethical issues arise when engaging the public in research? How have these issues been addressed, and how should they be addressed in the future?\"<ref name=CSTP_2/>\n\nIn June 2019, ''[[East Asian Science, Technology and Society: An International Journal]]'' (EASTS) published an issue titled \"Citizen Science: Practices and Problems\" which contains 15 articles/studies on CS, including many relevant subjects of which ethics is one.<ref name=EASTS_1>{{cite web |title=East Asian Science, Technology and Society: an International Journal-Volume 13, Number 2, June 2019 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/issue/40521 |website=Project MUSE }}</ref> Quoting from the introduction Citizen, Science, and Citizen Science: \"The term citizen science has become very popular among scholars as well as the general public, and, given its growing presence in East Asia, it is perhaps not a moment too soon to have a special issue of EASTS on the topic.\"<ref name=EASTS_2>{{cite journal| title=Citizen, Science, and Citizen Science| journal=East Asian Science, Technology and Society| author1=Fa-ti Fan| author2=Shun-Ling Chen| volume=13| issue=2| pages=181\u2013193| date=1 June 2019| doi=10.1215/18752160-7542643}}</ref>\n\n===Economic worth===\n\nIn the research paper \"Can citizen science enhance public understanding of science?\" by Bonney et al. 2016,<ref name=Bonney&Phill>{{cite journal|title=Can citizen science enhance public understanding of science?|author1=R. Bonney|author2=T. B. Phillips|author3=H. L. Ballard|author4=J. W. Enck|journal=Public Understanding of Science|volume=25|issue=1|pages=2\u201316|doi=10.1177/0963662515607406|pmid=26445860|date=1 January 2016}}</ref> statistics which analyse the economic worth of citizen science are used, drawn from two papers: '''i)'''Sauermann and Franzoni 2015,<ref name=Sau&Fran>{{cite journal|title=Crowd science user contribution patterns and their implications|author1=Henry Sauermann|author2=Chiara Franzoni| journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America| volume=112|issue=3|pages=679\u2013684|doi=10.1073/pnas.1408907112|date=20 January 2015|pmid=25561529|pmc=4311847|bibcode=2015PNAS..112..679S}}</ref> and\n'''ii)'''Theobald et al. 2015.<ref name=Theo&Ett>{{cite journal|title=Global change and local solutions: Tapping the unrealized potential of citizen science for biodiversity research|author1=J. Theobald|author2=A. K. Ettinger|author3=H. K. Burgess|author4=L. B. DeBey|author5=N. R. Schmidt|author6=H. E. Froehlich|author7=C. Wagner|author8=J. HilleRisLambers|author9=J. Tewksbury|author10=M. A. Harsch|author11=J. K. Parrish|journal=Biological Conservation|volume=181|issue=2015|pages=236\u2013244|date=1 January 2015|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2014.10.021}}</ref> In \"Crowd science user contribution patterns and their implications\" by Sauermann and Franzoni (2015), seven projects from the Zooniverse web portal are used to estimate the monetary value of the CS that had taken place. The 7 projects are: Solar Stormwatch, Galaxy Zoo Supernovae, Galaxy Zoo Hubble, Moon Zoo, Old Weather, The Milky Way Project and Planet Hunters.<ref name=Sau&Fran/> Using data from 180 days in 2010, they find a total of 100,386 users participated, contributing 129,540 hours of unpaid work.<ref name=Sau&Fran/> Estimating at a rate of $12 an hour (an undergraduate research assistant's basic wage), the total contributions amount to $1,554,474, an average of $222,068 per project.<ref name=Sau&Fran/> The range over the 7 projects was from $22,717 to $654,130.<ref name=Sau&Fran/>\n\nIn \"Global change and local solutions: Tapping the unrealized potential of citizen science for biodiversity research\" by Theobald et al. 2015, the authors surveyed 388 unique biodiversity-based projects.<ref name=Theo&Ett/> Quoting: \"We estimate that between 1.36 million and 2.28 million people volunteer annually in the 388 projects we surveyed, though variation is great\" and that \"the range of in-kind contribution of the volunteerism in our 388 citizen science projects as between $667 million to $2.5 billion annually.\"<ref name=Theo&Ett/>\n\nWorldwide participation in citizen science continues to grow. A list of the top five citizen science communities compiled by [[Marc Kuchner]] and Kristen Erickson in July 2018 shows a total of 3.75 million participants, although there is likely substantial overlap between the communities.\n\n===Education===\n\nThere have been studies published which examine the place of CS within education.(e.g.<ref name=UTW_1/><ref name=CSYE>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science and Youth Education| author1=R. Bonney| author2=T.B. Phillips| author3=J. Enck| author4=J. Shirk| author5=N. Trautmann| publisher=Center for Advancement of Informal Science Education| url=http://www.informalscience.org/citizen-science-and-youth-education| date=1 January 2015| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122072021/http://www.informalscience.org/citizen-science-and-youth-education| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=EERA>{{cite web| title=School-based Citizen Science and its Contribution to Environmental Education Outcomes: a Literature Review| author=A. Ruck| publisher=European Educational Research Association| url=http://www.eera-ecer.de/ecer-programmes/print/conference/21/contribution/38023Z| date=25 August 2016| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122072026/http://www.eera-ecer.de/ecer-programmes/print/conference/21/contribution/38023Z| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref>) Teaching aids can include books and activity or lesson plans.(e.g.<ref name=Zoo_Teach>{{cite web| title=Hands-on Activity: Citizen Science with Zooniverse| author1=P. Cain| author2=Y.Glass| author3=J. Nider| author4=S. Prakash| author5=L. Rice| url=https://www.teachengineering.org/activities/view/ksu_zooniverse_activity1| date=2012| publisher=Kansas State University| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122071934/https://www.teachengineering.org/activities/view/ksu_zooniverse_activity1| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=CS_lessons>{{cite book| title=Citizen Science: 15 Lessons That Bring Biology to Life| author1=N. Trautmann| author2=J. Fee| author3=T.M. Tomasek| author4=N.L.R. Bergey| publisher=National Science Teachers Association| date=28 February 2014| isbn=9781936959082}}</ref><ref name=CAS_Toolkit>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science Toolkit| publisher=California Academy of Sciences| url=https://www.calacademy.org/educators/citizen-science-toolkit| date=2015| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122071724/https://www.calacademy.org/educators/citizen-science-toolkit| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=NASA_LP>{{cite web| title=Lesson Plans \u2013 Citizen Science| url=https://mynasadata.larc.nasa.gov/lesson-plans/lesson-plans-citizen-science| publisher=[[NASA]]| date=7 November 2017| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710192555/https://mynasadata.larc.nasa.gov/lesson-plans/lesson-plans-citizen-science/| archivedate=10 July 2017}}</ref>). Some examples of studies are:\n\nFrom the Second International Handbook of Science Education, a chapter entitled: \"Citizen Science, Ecojustice, and Science Education: Rethinking an Education from Nowhere\" by Mueller and Tippins (2011), acknowledges in the abstract that: \"There is an emerging emphasis in science education on engaging youth in citizen science.\" The authors also ask: \"whether citizen science goes further with respect to citizen development.\"<ref name=CS_Eco/> The abstract ends by stating that the \"chapter takes account of the ways educators will collaborate with members of the community to effectively guide decisions, which offers promise for sharing a responsibility for democratizing science with others.\"<ref name=CS_Eco>{{cite book| title=Citizen Science, Ecojustice, and Science Education: Rethinking an Education from Nowhere| author1=M.P. Mueller| author2=D.J. Tippins| publisher=Springer International Handbooks of Education| volume=24|date=23 November 2011| doi=10.1007/978-1-4020-9041-7_58| isbn=978-1-4020-9040-0}}</ref>\n\nFrom the journal Democracy and Education, an article entitled: \"Lessons Learned from Citizen Science in the Classroom\" by authors Gray, Nicosia and Jordan (GNJ) (2012) give a response to a study by Mueller, Tippins and Bryan (MTB) called \"The Future of Citizen Science\".<ref name=DemEdu>{{cite journal| title=Lessons Learned from Citizen Science in the Classroom| author1=S.A. Gray| author2=K. Nicosia| author3=R.C. Jordan| journal=Democracy and Education| url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/254634887| volume=20| number=2| date=August 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072120/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/254634887_Lessons_Learned_from_Citizen_Science_in_the_Classroom_A_Response_to_The_Future_of_Citizen_Science| archivedate=23 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=FCS>{{cite journal| title=The Future of Citizen Science| author1=M.P. Mueller| author2=D. Tippins| author3=L.A. Bryan| journal=Democracy and Education| volume=20| issue=1| date=2012}}</ref> GNJ begins by stating in the abstract that the study The Future of Citizen Science: \"provides an important theoretical perspective about the future of \ndemocratized science and [[K\u201312|K12]] education.\" But GRB state: \"However, the authors (MTB) fail to adequately address the existing \nbarriers and constraints to moving community-based science into the classroom.\" They end the abstract by arguing: \"that the resource constraints of scientists, teachers, and students likely pose problems to moving true democratized science into the classroom.\"<ref name=DemEdu/>\n\nIn 2014, a study was published called \"Citizen Science and Lifelong Learning\" by R. Edwards in the journal ''[[Studies in the Education of Adults]]''.<ref name=CSLL>{{cite journal |last1=Edwards |first1=Richard |title=Citizen science and lifelong learning |journal=Studies in the Education of Adults |date=21 January 2016 |volume=46 |issue=2 |pages=132\u2013144 |doi=10.1080/02660830.2014.11661662 }}</ref> Edwards begins by writing in the abstract that CS projects have expanded over recent years and engaged CSs and professionals in diverse ways. He continues: \"Yet there has been little educational exploration of such projects to date.\"<ref name=CSLL/> He describes that \"there has been limited exploration of the educational backgrounds of adult contributors to citizen science\". Edwards explains that CS contributors are referred to as volunteers, citizens or as amateurs. He ends the abstract: \"The article will explore the nature and significance of these different characterisations and also suggest possibilities for further research.\"<ref name=CSLL/>\n\nIn the journal ''[[Microbiology and Biology Education]]'' a study was published by Shah and Martinez (2015) called \"Current Approaches in Implementing Citizen Science in the Classroom\".<ref name=CurrApp>{{cite journal| title=Current Approaches in Implementing Citizen Science in the Classroom| author1=H.R. Shah| author2=L.R. Martinez| journal=Microbiology & Biology Education| date=March 2015| volume=17| issue=1| doi=10.1128/jmbe.v17i1.1032| pmid=27047583| pages=17\u201322| pmc=4798802}}</ref> They begin by writing in the abstract that CS is a partnership between inexperienced amateurs and trained scientists. The authors continue: \"With recent studies showing a weakening in scientific competency of American students, incorporating citizen science initiatives in the curriculum provides a means to address deficiencies\".<ref name=CurrApp/> They argue that combining traditional and innovative methods can help provide a practical experience of science. The abstract ends: \"Citizen science can be used to emphasize the recognition and use of systematic approaches to solve problems affecting the community.\"<ref name=CurrApp/>\n\nIn November 2017, authors Mitchell, Triska and Liberatore published a study in ''[[PLOS ONE]]'' titled \"Benefits and Challenges of Incorporating Citizen Science into University Education\".<ref name=Bene&Chall>{{cite journal| title=Benefits and Challenges of Incorporating Citizen Science into University Education| author1=N. Mitchell| author2=M. Triska| author3=A. Liberatore| author4=L. Ashcroft| author5=R. Weatherill| author6=N. Longnecker| journal= PLOS ONE| date=1 November 2017| doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0186285| pmid=29091933| volume=12| issue=11| page=e0186285| bibcode=2017PLoSO..1286285M| pmc=5665417}}</ref> The authors begin by stating in the abstract that CSs contribute data with the expectation that it will be used. It reports that CS has been used for first year university students as a means to experience research. They continue: \"Surveys of more than 1500 students showed that their environmental engagement increased significantly after participating in data collection and data analysis.\"<ref name=Bene&Chall/> However, only a third of students agreed that data collected by CSs was reliable. A positive outcome of this was that the students were more careful of their own research. The abstract ends: \"If true for citizen scientists in general, enabling participants as well as scientists to analyse data could enhance data quality, and so address a key constraint of broad-scale citizen science programs.\"<ref name=Bene&Chall/>\n\n== History ==\n\n\"Citizen science\" is a fairly new term but an old practice. Prior to the 20th century, science was often the pursuit of [[gentleman scientist]]s, amateur or self-funded researchers such as Sir [[Isaac Newton]], [[Benjamin Franklin]], and [[Charles Darwin]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Silvertown |first1=Jonathan |title=A new dawn for citizen science |journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution |date=September 2009 |volume=24 |issue=9 |pages=467\u2013471 |doi=10.1016/j.tree.2009.03.017 |pmid=19586682 }}</ref> By the mid-20th century, however, science was dominated by researchers employed by universities and government research laboratories. By the 1970s, this transformation was being called into question. Philosopher [[Paul Feyerabend]] called for a \"democratization of science\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Paul Feyerabend |author-link=Paul Feyerabend |title=Science in a free society |publisher=[[New Left Books]]|location=London |year=1982 |isbn=978-0-86091-753-3 }}{{pn|date=November 2019}}</ref> Biochemist [[Erwin Chargaff]] advocated a return to science by nature-loving amateurs in the tradition of [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes|Descartes]], Newton, [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz|Leibniz]], [[Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon|Buffon]], and [[Charles Darwin|Darwin]]\u2014science dominated by \"amateurship instead of money-biased technical bureaucrats\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Erwin Chargaff |author-link=Erwin Chargaff |title=Heraclitean fire: sketches from a life before nature |publisher=[[Rockefeller University Press]] |location=New York |year=1978 |isbn=978-0-87470-029-9 }}{{pn|date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\nA study from 2016 indicates that the largest impact of citizen science is in research on biology, conservation and ecology, and is utilized mainly as a methodology of collecting and classifying data.<ref name=kullberg>{{cite journal |last1=Kullenberg |first1=Christopher |last2=Kasperowski |first2=Dick |last3=Dorta-Gonz\u00e1lez |first3=Pablo |title=What Is Citizen Science? \u2013 A Scientometric Meta-Analysis |journal=PLOS ONE |date=14 January 2016 |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=e0147152 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147152 |pmid=26766577 |pmc=4713078 |bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147152K }}</ref>\n\n===Amateur astronomy===\n{{main|Amateur astronomy}}\n[[File:Telescope trailer 22.jpg|right|thumb|250px|upright|Amateur astronomers can build their own equipment and can hold star parties and gatherings, such as [[Stellafane]].]]\n\n[[Astronomy]] has long been a field where amateurs have contributed throughout time, all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mims III |first=Forrest M. |authorlink=Forrest Mims |title=Amateur Science\u2014Strong Tradition, Bright Future |journal=Science |year=1999 |volume=284 |issue=5411 |pages=55\u201356 |doi=10.1126/science.284.5411.55 |quote=Astronomy has traditionally been among the most fertile fields for serious amateurs [...] |bibcode = 1999Sci...284...55M}}</ref>\n\nCollectively, amateur astronomers observe a variety of celestial objects and phenomena sometimes with [[Amateur telescope making|equipment that they build themselves]]. Common targets of amateur astronomers include the Moon, planets, stars, comets, meteor showers, and a variety of [[deep-sky object]]s such as star clusters, galaxies, and nebulae. Observations of comets and stars are also used to measure the local level of [[skyglow|artificial skyglow]].<ref name=\"GaN\">{{cite journal |last1=Kyba |first1=Christopher C. M. |last2=Wagner |first2=Janna M. |last3=Kuechly |first3=Helga U. |last4=Walker |first4=Constance E. |last5=Elvidge |first5=Christopher D. |last6=Falchi |first6=Fabio |last7=Ruhtz |first7=Thomas |last8=Fischer |first8=J\u00fcrgen |last9=H\u00f6lker |first9=Franz |title=Citizen Science Provides Valuable Data for Monitoring Global Night Sky Luminance |journal=Scientific Reports |date=16 May 2013 |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=1835 |doi=10.1038/srep01835 |pmid=23677222 |bibcode=2013NatSR...3E1835K |pmc=3655480 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=\u015aci\u0119\u017cor |first1=T. |title=A new astronomical method for determining the brightness of the night sky and its application to study long-term changes in the level of light pollution |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |date=11 October 2013 |volume=435 |issue=1 |pages=303\u2013310 |doi=10.1093/mnras/stt1297 |bibcode=2013MNRAS.435..303S }}</ref> One branch of amateur astronomy, amateur [[astrophotography]], involves the taking of photos of the night sky. Many amateurs like to specialize in the observation of particular objects, types of objects, or types of events that interest them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amsmeteors.org/|title = The Americal Meteor Society|accessdate =24 August 2006|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060822135040/http://www.amsmeteors.org/|archivedate= 22 August 2006 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jerry|last=Lodriguss|url=http://www.astropix.com/|title = Catching the Light: Astrophotography|accessdate =24 August 2006|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060901185541/http://www.astropix.com/|archivedate= 1 September 2006 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Association of Variable Star Observers]] has gathered data on variable stars for educational and professional analysis since 1911 and promotes participation beyond its membership on its Citizen Sky website.<ref name=CSP>{{cite web |title=The Origins and Future of the Citizen Sky Project |url=https://www.aavso.org/apps/jaavso/article/2864/ |website=AAVSO }}</ref>\n\n===Butterfly counts===\n{{main|Butterfly count}}\nButterfly counts have a long tradition of involving individuals in the study of butterflies' range and their relative abundance. Two long-running programs are the UK Butterfly Monitoring Scheme (started in 1976) and the [[North American Butterfly Association]]'s Butterfly Count Program (started in 1975).<ref name=UKBMS>{{cite web|title=The UK Butterfly Monitoring Scheme (UKBMS)|url=http://www.ukbms.org|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230125155/http://www.ukbms.org/|archivedate=30 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=NABA_BCD>{{cite web |first1=Leslie |last1=Ries |title=Analyzing the NABA Butterfly Count Data|url=http://www.naba.org/pubs/ab141/ab141count_column.pdf|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223114316/http://www.naba.org/pubs/ab141/ab141count_column.pdf|archivedate=23 December 2016}}</ref> There are various protocols for monitoring butterflies and different organizations support one or more of transects, counts and/or opportunistic sightings.<ref name=NA_Goal>{{cite web|title=Goal 1: Track all North American butterfly monitoring|url=http://www.nab-net.org/goal-1|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230133120/http://www.nab-net.org/goal-1|archivedate=30 December 2014}}</ref> [[eButterfly]] is an example of a program designed to capture any of the three types of counts for observers in North America.  Species-specific programs also exist, with monarchs the prominent example.<ref name=E_ButtHP>{{cite web|title=eButterfly Homepage|url=http://www.e-butterfly.org|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140408031027/http://www.e-butterfly.org/|archivedate=8 April 2014}}</ref> Two examples of this involve the counting of monarch butterflies during the fall [[Monarch butterfly migration|migration]] to overwintering sites in Mexico: (1) Monarch Watch is a continent-wide project, while (2) the Cape May Monarch Monitoring Project is an example of a local project.<ref name=MW_HP>{{cite web|title=Monarch Watch Homepage|url=http://www.monarchwatch.org|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=CS_MonarchButterfly>{{cite web|title=The Cape May Monarch Monitoring Project|publisher=New Jersey Audubon Research Department, and the Cape May Bird Observatory|url=http://www.monarchmonitoringproject.com/index.html|accessdate=4 October 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006123918/http://www.monarchmonitoringproject.com/index.html|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> The Austrian project [http://viel-falter.at Viel-Falter] investigated if and how trained and supervised pupils are able to systematically collect data about the occurrence of diurnal butterflies, and how this data could contribute to a permanent butterfly monitoring system. Despite substantial identification uncertainties for some species or species groups, the data collected by pupils was successfully used to predict the general habitat quality for butterflies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=R\u00fcdisser |first1=Johannes |last2=Tasser |first2=Erich |last3=Walde |first3=Janette |last4=Huemer |first4=Peter |last5=Lechner |first5=Kurt |last6=Ortner |first6=Alois |last7=Tappeiner |first7=Ulrike |title=Simplified and still meaningful: assessing butterfly habitat quality in grasslands with data collected by pupils |journal=Journal of Insect Conservation |date=10 July 2017 |volume=21 |issue=4 |pages=677\u2013688 |doi=10.1007/s10841-017-0010-3 }}</ref>\n\n===Ornithology===\n{{main|Birdwatching}}\nCitizen science projects have become increasingly focused on providing benefits to scientific research.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Rick |last1=Bonney |first2=Melinda S. |last2=LaBranche |date=May 1, 2004 |title=Citizen Science: Involving the Public in Research |website=Informal Science |url=https://www.informalscience.org/citizen-science-involving-public-research }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Barreto |first1=Claudia |last2=Fastovsky |first2=David E. |last3=Sheehan |first3=Peter M. |title=A Model for Integrating the Public into Scientific Research |journal=Journal of Geoscience Education |date=31 January 2018 |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=71\u201375 |doi=10.5408/1089-9995-51.1.71 |url=https://digitalcommons.uri.edu/geo_facpubs/2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first1=Rachel E. |last1=McCaffrey |date=December 2005 |title=Urban Habitats -- Using Citizen Science in Urban Bird Studies |journal=Urban Habitats |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=70\u201386 |url=http://www.urbanhabitats.org/v03n01/citizenscience_full.html }}</ref> The [[North American Bird Phenology Program]] (historically called the Bird Migration and Distribution records) may have been the earliest collective effort of citizens collecting ornithological information in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwrc.usgs.gov/bpp/|title=North American Phenology Program|accessdate=30 July 2016|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729190651/http://www.pwrc.usgs.gov/bpp/|archivedate=29 July 2016}}</ref> The program, dating back to 1883, was started by Wells Woodbridge Cooke. Cooke established a network of observers around North America to collect bird migration records. The [[National Audubon Society|Audubon Society]]'s [[Christmas Bird Count]], which began in 1900, is another example of a long-standing tradition of citizen science which has persisted to the present day.  Citizen scientists help gather data that will be analyzed by professional researchers, and can be used to produce bird population and biodiversity indicators.\n\nRaptor migration research relies on the data collected by the [[hawkwatching]] community. This mostly volunteer group counts migrating accipiters, buteos, falcons, harriers, kites, eagles, osprey, vultures and other raptors at hawk sites throughout North America during the spring and fall seasons.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Bird!\": An Exploration of Hawkwatching|last=Wargo|first=Brian M.|publisher=BMW Endeavors, LLC|year=2016|isbn=978-1-945226-00-7|location=McKees Rocks}}</ref> The daily data is uploaded to hawkcount.org where it can be viewed by professional scientists and the public.\n\nSuch indices can be useful tools to inform management, resource allocation, policy and planning.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Devictor | first1 = V. | last2 = Whittaker | first2 = R. J. | last3 = Bel trame | first3 = C. | year = 2010 | title = Beyond scarcity: citizen science programmes as useful tools for conservation biogeography | journal = Diversity and Distributions | volume = 16 | issue = 3| pages = 354\u2013362 | doi=10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00615.x}}</ref> For example, European breeding bird survey data provide input for the [[Farmland Bird Index]], adopted by the European Union as a structural indicator of sustainable development.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jiguet |first1=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric |last2=Devictor |first2=Vincent |last3=Julliard |first3=Romain |last4=Couvet |first4=Denis |title=French citizens monitoring ordinary birds provide tools for conservation and ecological sciences |journal=Acta Oecologica |date=October 2012 |volume=44 |pages=58\u201366 |doi=10.1016/j.actao.2011.05.003 |bibcode=2012AcO....44...58J |url=https://zenodo.org/record/3414128 }}</ref> This provides a cost-effective alternative to government monitoring.\n\nSimilarly, data collected by citizen scientists as part of BirdLife Australia's has been analysed to produce the first-ever Australian Terrestrial Bird Indices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian birdlife|url=http://birdlife.org.au/state-of-birds|accessdate=30 December 2015|date=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Citizen oceanography ===\nThe concept of citizen science has been extended to the ocean environment for characterizing ocean dynamics and tracking [[marine debris]]. For example, the mobile app Marine Debris Tracker is a joint partnership of [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] and the [[University of Georgia]].<ref name=MDT>{{cite web| title=Marine Debris Tracker| publisher=Marine Debris Tracker| url=http://www.marinedebris.engr.uga.edu| access-date=19 March 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227041320/http://www.marinedebris.engr.uga.edu/| archivedate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Long term sampling efforts such as the [[Continuous Plankton Recorder|continuous plankton recorder]] has been fitted on ships of opportunity since 1931. Plankton collection by sailors and subsequent genetic analysis was pioneered in 2013 by Indigo V Expeditions as a way to better understand marine microbial structure and function.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Common Oceanographer: Crowdsourcing the Collection of Oceanographic Data|journal = PLoS Biol|date = 9 September 2014|pmc = 4159111|pmid = 25203659|pages = e1001947|volume = 12|issue = 9|doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1001947|first = Federico M.|last = Lauro|first2 = Svend Jacob|last2 = Senstius|first3 = Jay|last3 = Cullen|first4 = Russell|last4 = Neches|first5 = Rachelle M.|last5 = Jensen|first6 = Mark V.|last6 = Brown|first7 = Aaron E.|last7 = Darling|first8 = Michael|last8 = Givskov|first9 = Diane|last9 = McDougald}}</ref>\n\n=== Coral reefs ===\nCitizen science in [[Coral reef]] studies developed in the 21st century.\n\n[[Underwater photography]] has become more popular since the early 2000s, resulting on millions of pictures posted every year on various websites and social media. This mass of documentation has great scientific potential, as millions of tourists possess a much superior coverage power than professional scientists, who cannot spend so much time in the field.\n\nAs a consequence, several participative sciences programs have been developed, supported by [[geotagging]] and identification web sites (such as [https://www.inaturalist.org/ iNaturalist.org]).  The ''Monitoring through many eyes'' project collates thousands of underwater images of the [[Great Barrier Reef]] and provides an interface for elicitation of reef health indicators.<ref name=MTME>{{cite web|title=Monitoring through many eyes project homepage\n |url=https://www.virtualreef.org.au\n |publisher=Queensland Government, Queensland University of Technology, CRCSI\n |accessdate=10 May 2017|url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301205255/https://www.virtualreef.org.au/|archivedate=1 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA) also offers opportunities for volunteer participation.  By taking measurements in [[United States National Marine Sanctuary|The United States' National Marine Sanctuaries]], citizens contribute data to [[marine biology]] projects.  In 2016, NOAA benefited from 137,000 hours of research.<ref name=MTME_2>{{cite web| title=Volunteers help to ensure national marine sanctuaries remain America's underwater treasures for future generations\n | url=https://sanctuaries.noaa.gov/involved/volunteer_future.html\n | publisher=National Ocean Servi, NOAA, Department of Commerce| accessdate=5 September 2017| url-status=live\n | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906034716/https://sanctuaries.noaa.gov/involved/volunteer_future.html| archivedate=6 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere also exist protocols for auto-organization and self-teaching aimed at biodiversity-interested snorkelers, in order for them to turn their observations into sound scientific data, available for research. This kind of approach has been successfully used in [[R\u00e9union island]], allowing for tens of new records and even new species.<ref name=\"CBM2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Bourjon |first1=Philippe |last2=Ducarme |first2=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric |last3=Quod |first3=Jean-Pascal |last4=Sweet |first4=Michael |year=2018 |title=Involving recreational snorkelers in inventory improvement or creation: a case study in the Indian Ocean |journal=Cahiers de Biologie Marine |volume=59 |pages=451\u2013460 |doi=10.21411/CBM.A.B05FC714 }}</ref>\n\n=== Agriculture ===\n\nFarmer participation in experiments has a long tradition in [[Agricultural science]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Gosset|first1= William S.|date=1936 |title= Co-Operation in Large-Scale Experiments|journal= Supplement to the Journal of the Royal Statistical Society|volume= 3|issue= 2|pages=115\u2013136|doi= 10.2307/2983667|access-date= |jstor= 2983667}}</ref> There are many opportunities for citizen engagement in different parts of food systems.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Ryan|first1= S.F|last2= Adamson|first2= N.L.|last3=Aktipis|first3=A.|last4=Andersen|first4=L.K.|last5=Austin|first5=R.|last6= Barnes|first6=L.|last7=Beasley|first7=M.R.|last8=Bedell|first8=K.D.|last9= Briggs|first9= S.|last10= Chapman|first10= B.|date=2018 |title= The role of citizen science in addressing grand challenges in food and agriculture research|journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society B|volume= 285|issue= 1891|pages= 20181977|doi= 10.1098/rspb.2018.1977|pmid= 30464064|access-date= |pmc= 6253361}}</ref> Citizen science is actively used for crop variety selection for climate adaptation, involving thousands of farmers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= van Etten|first1= Jacob|last2= de Sousa|first2= Kau\u00ea|last3=Aguilar|first3=Am\u00edlcar |last4=Barrios|first4=Mirna |last5=Coto|first5=Allan |last6= Dell\u2019Acqua|first6=Matteo |last7=Fadda|first7=Carlo |last8=Gebrehawaryat|first8=Yosef |last9= van de Gevel|first9= Jeske |last10=Gupta  |first10=Arnab|last11=Kiros|first11=Afewerki Y. |last12=Madriz|first12=Brandon |last13=Mathur|first13=Prem |last14=Mengistu|first14=Dejene K.|last15=Mercado|first15=Leida |last16=Nurhisen Mohammed|first16=Jemal |last17=Paliwal|first17=Ambica |last18=P\u00e8|first18=Mario Enrico |last19=Quir\u00f3s|first19=Carlos F. |last20=Rosas|first20=Juan Carlos |last21=Sharma|first21=Neeraj |last22=Singh|first22=S.S.|last23=Solanki|first23=Iswhar S.| last24=Steinke|first24=Jonathan |date=2019 |title= Crop variety management for climate adaptation supported by citizen science|journal= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume= 285|issue= 1891|pages= 4194\u20134199|doi= 10.1073/pnas.1813720116|pmid= 30782795|pmc= 6410884|access-date= }}</ref>\n\n=== Art history ===\nCitizen science has a long tradition in [[Natural science]]. But nowadays, citizen science projects can also be found in various fields of science like [[Art history]]. For example, the [[Zooniverse (citizen science project)|Zooniverse]] project AnnoTate is a transcription tool developed to enable volunteers to read and transcribe the personal papers of British-born and \u00e9migr\u00e9 artists.<ref name=AnnoTate>{{cite web|title=AnnoTate homepage|url=https://anno.tate.org.uk|publisher=Zooniverse|accessdate=2 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507142819/https://anno.tate.org.uk/|archivedate=7 May 2016}}</ref> The papers are drawn from the [[Tate Britain|Tate Archive]]. Another example of citizen science in art history is [[Human-based computation game#Artigo|ARTigo]].<ref name=Artigo>{{cite web|title=ARTigo homepage|url=http://www.artigo.org|publisher=ARTigo|accessdate=2 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601154649/http://www.artigo.org/|archivedate=1 June 2016}}</ref> ARTigo collects [[Semantics|semantic]] data on artworks from the footprints left by players of games featuring artwork images. From these footprints, ARTigo automatically builds a [[semantic search]] engine for artworks.\n\n== Modern technology ==\nNewer technologies have increased the options for citizen science.<ref name=BBC_NewEra>{{cite web|author=Dan Drollette|title=Citizen science enters a new era|url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120329-citizen-science-enters-a-new-era?selectorSection=technology\n |publisher=BBC|date=29 March 2012|accessdate=4 October 2014|url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018015022/http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120329-citizen-science-enters-a-new-era?selectorSection=technology|archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref> Citizen scientists can build and operate their own instruments to gather data for their own experiments or as part of a larger project. Examples include [[amateur radio]], [[amateur astronomy]], Six Sigma Projects, and [[Maker culture|Maker]] activities.  Scientist [[Joshua Pearce]] has advocated for the creation of [[open-source hardware]] based scientific equipment that both citizen scientists and professional scientists, which can be replicated by [[digital manufacturing]] techniques such as [[3D printing]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pearce |first1=J. M. |title=Building Research Equipment with Free, Open-Source Hardware |journal=Science |date=13 September 2012 |volume=337 |issue=6100 |pages=1303\u20131304 |doi=10.1126/science.1228183 |pmid=22984059 |bibcode=2012Sci...337.1303P }}</ref> Multiple studies have shown this approach radically reduces scientific equipment costs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pearce |first1=J. M. |title=Return on investment for open source scientific hardware development |journal=Science and Public Policy |date=April 2016 |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages=192\u2013195 |doi=10.1093/scipol/scv034 |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02119548/file/Return_on_Investment_for_Open_Source_Har.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |last1=Baden |first1=Tom |last2=Chagas |first2=Andre Maia |last3=Gage |first3=Greg |last4=Marzullo |first4=Timothy |last5=Prieto-Godino |first5=Lucia L. |last6=Euler |first6=Thomas |title=Open Labware: 3-D Printing Your Own Lab Equipment |journal=PLOS Biology |date=20 March 2015 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=e1002086 |doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.1002086 |pmid=25794301 |pmc=4368627 }}</ref> Examples of this approach include water testing, nitrate and other environmental testing, basic biology and optics.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url = https://publiclab.org/\n |title = Public Lab: a DIY environmental science community|last = Contributors|first = Public Lab\n |website = publiclab.org|access-date = 2016-02-27|url-status = live\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160226073149/https://publiclab.org/|archivedate = 26 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Damase |first1=Tulsi R. |last2=Stephens |first2=Daniel |last3=Spencer |first3=Adam |last4=Allen |first4=Peter B. |title=Open source and DIY hardware for DNA nanotechnology labs |journal=Journal of Biological Methods |date=31 August 2015 |volume=2 |issue=3 |pages=24 |doi=10.14440/jbm.2015.72 |pmid=26457320 |pmc=4598940 }}</ref><ref name=Zhang_1>{{cite journal |last1=Zhang |first1=Chenlong |last2=Anzalone |first2=Nicholas C. |last3=Faria |first3=Rodrigo P. |last4=Pearce |first4=Joshua M. |last5=de Brevern |first5=Alexandre G. |title=Open-Source 3D-Printable Optics Equipment |journal=PLoS ONE |date=27 March 2013 |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=e59840 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0059840 |pmid=23544104 |pmc=3609802 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...859840Z }}</ref> Groups such as [[Public Lab]], which is a community where citizen scientists can learn how to investigate environmental concerns using inexpensive [[Do it yourself|DIY]] techniques, embody this approach.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\n[[File:Citizen Science Center NCMNS.jpg|thumb|300px|Citizen Science Center exhibit in the Nature Research Center wing of the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]]]]\n\nVideo technology is much used in scientific research.   The Citizen Science Center in the [[Nature Research Center#First floor 2|Nature Research Center]] wing of the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]] has exhibits on how to get involved in scientific research and become a citizen scientist.  For example, visitors can observe birdfeeders at the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences#Prairie Ridge Ecostation|Prairie Ridge Ecostation]] satellite facility via live video feed and record which species they see.\n\nSince 2005, the [[Genographic Project]] has used the latest genetic technology to expand our knowledge of the human story, and its pioneering use of DNA testing to engage and involve the public in the research effort has helped to create a new breed of \"citizen scientist\". Geno 2.0 expands the scope for citizen science, harnessing the power of the [[Crowdsourcing|crowd]] to discover new details of human population history.<ref name=Wells>{{cite web|last = Wells|first = Spencer|title = The Genographic Project and the Rise of Citizen Science|publisher = Southern California Genealogical Society (SCGS)|year = 2013|url = http://www.scgsgenealogy.com/Jamboree/2013/DNAday.htm|accessdate = 10 July 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130710014353/http://www.scgsgenealogy.com/Jamboree/2013/DNAday.htm|archivedate = 10 July 2013}}</ref> This includes supporting, organization and dissemination of [[Genealogical DNA test|personal DNA (genetic) testing.]] Like [[Amateur astronomy]], citizen scientists encouraged by volunteer organizations like the [[International Society of Genetic Genealogy]] have provided valuable information and research to the professional scientific community.<ref name=KingJobling>{{cite journal|last1=King|doi=10.1016/j.tig.2009.06.003|quote=The International Society of Genetic Genealogy <http://www.isogg.org> advocates the use of genetics as a tool for genealogical research, and provides a support network for genetic genealogists. It hosts the ISOGG Y-haplogroup tree, which has the virtue of being regularly updated.|title=What's in a name? Y chromosomes, surnames and the genetic genealogy revolution|year=2009|first1=Turi E.|last2=Jobling|first2=Mark A.|journal=Trends in Genetics|volume=25|issue=8|pages=351\u201360|pmid=19665817|url=https://lra.le.ac.uk/bitstream/2381/8106/1/KingJoblingRevisedWeb.pdf|hdl=2381/8106}}</ref><ref name=AJHG>{{cite journal |last1=Mendez |first1=Fernando&nbsp;L. |last2=Krahn |first2=Thomas |last3=Schrack |first3=Bonnie |last4=Krahn |first4=Astrid-Maria |last5=Veeramah |first5=Krishna&nbsp;R. |last6=Woerner |first6=August&nbsp;E. |last7=Fomine |first7=Forka&nbsp;Leypey&nbsp;Mathew |last8=Bradman |first8=Neil |last9=Thomas |first9=Mark&nbsp;G. |last10=Karafet |first10=Tatiana&nbsp;M. |last11=Hammer |first11=Michael&nbsp;F. |title=An African American Paternal Lineage Adds an Extremely Ancient Root to the Human Y Chromosome Phylogenetic Tree |journal=The American Journal of Human Genetics |date=March 2013 |volume=92 |issue=3 |pages=454\u2013459 |doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2013.02.002 |pmid=23453668 |pmc=3591855 }}</ref>\n\nWith [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s, further citizen science is enabled. One example is the [[European Space Agency|ESA's]] AstroDrone smartphone app for gathering robotic data with the [[Parrot AR.Drone]].<ref name=AsDr>{{cite web| title=Astro Drone - A Crowdsourcing Game to Improve Visual Algorithms| url=http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/ai/projects/astrodrone.html| publisher=[[European Space Agency]]| access-date=17 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111042331/http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/ai/projects/astrodrone.html| archivedate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCitizens in Space (CIS), a project of the United States Rocket Academy, seeks to combine citizen science with citizen space exploration.<ref name=Citizens_In_Space>{{cite web|title=Citizens in Space|url=http://www.citizensinspace.org|publisher=Citizensinspace|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827233150/http://www.citizensinspace.org/|archivedate=27 August 2014}}</ref> CIS is training citizen astronauts to fly as payload operators on suborbital reusable spacecraft that are now in development. CIS will also be developing, and encouraging others to develop, citizen-science payloads to fly on suborbital vehicles. CIS has already acquired a contract for 10 flights on the Lynx suborbital vehicle, being developed by [[XCOR Aerospace]], and plans to acquire additional flights on [[XCOR Lynx]] and other suborbital vehicles in the future.<ref name=Citizens_In_Space/>\n\nCIS believes that \"The development of low-cost reusable suborbital spacecraft will be the next great enabler, allowing citizens to participate in space exploration and space science.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citizensinspace.org/2012/02/teachers-in-space-becomes-citizens-in-space-2/ |title=\"Teachers in Space\" becomes \"Citizens in Space\" |publisher=Citizensinspace.org |accessdate=6 November 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026131929/http://www.citizensinspace.org/2012/02/teachers-in-space-becomes-citizens-in-space-2/ |archivedate=26 October 2012 |date=February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Internet===\n\n[[File:SAH stopmo 1.webm|thumb|How your gameplay helps [[ScienceAtHome]] build a quantum computer]]\n\nThe Internet has been a boon to citizen science, particularly through [[gamification]].<ref name=BBC_NewEra/> One of the first Internet-based citizen science experiments was [[NASA]]'s [[Clickworkers]], which enabled the general public to assist in the classification of images, greatly reducing the time to analyze large data sets. Another was the Citizen Science Toolbox, launched in 2003, of the Australian Coastal Collaborative Research Centre.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://research.usc.edu.au/vital/access/manager/Repository/usc:1413 |title=The Citizen Science Toolbox : Citizen Science: Linking communities, scientists and decision-makers |first1=J. |last1=Fien |first2=T. F. |last2=Smith |last3=Lazarow |first3=N. S. |last4=Pembleton |first4=J. |last5=Rosenthal |first5=K |last6=Alcock |first6=D. |last7=Thomsen |first7=D. C. |last8=Hudson |first8=K. |last9=Gleeson |first9=J. |last10=Oliver |first10=P. |last11=Gooch |first11=M. |last12=White |first12=C. |last13=Powell |first13=B. |last14=Whelan |first14=J. |last15=Rickson |first15=R. |last16=Eisner |first16=R. |last17=Dwyer |first17=D. |last18=Malawkin |first18=H. |last19=Tilden |first19=J. |date=2003 }}</ref> Mozak is a game in which players create 3D reconstructions from images of actual human and mouse neurons, helping to advance understanding of the brain. One of the largest citizen science games is [[Eyewire]], a brain-mapping puzzle game developed at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] that now has over 200,000 players.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1145/2908131.2908151 |chapter=Because science is awesome |title=Proceedings of the 8th ACM Conference on Web Science - Web ''Sci'' '16 |pages=45\u201354 |year=2016 |last1=Tinati |first1=Ramine |last2=Luczak-Roesch |first2=Markus |last3=Simperl |first3=Elena |last4=Hall |first4=Wendy |isbn=9781450342087 |chapter-url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/390326/1/2016___WebSci___EyeWire_Motivations.pdf }}</ref> Another example is [[Quantum Moves]], a game developed by the Center for Driven Community Research at [[Aarhus University]], which uses online community efforts to solve quantum physics problems.<ref name=SCAH>{{cite web| title=Science at Home - About Us| url=https://www.scienceathome.org/about-us| publisher=Science at Home| access-date=17 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518221342/https://www.scienceathome.org/about-us/| archivedate=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://phys.au.dk/en/research/research-areas/coder/|title=CODER - AU Ideas Center for Community Driven Research|work=au.dk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911161608/http://phys.au.dk/en/research/research-areas/coder/|archivedate=11 September 2017}}</ref> The solutions found by players can then be used in the lab to feed computational algorithms used in building a scalable [[Quantum computing|quantum computer]].\n\nMore generally, Amazon's [[Amazon Mechanical Turk|Mechanical Turk]] is frequently used in the creation, collection, and processing of data by paid citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/inside-amazons-hidden-science-factory/|title=The Internet's hidden science factory|work=PBS NewsHour|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911114807/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/inside-amazons-hidden-science-factory/|archivedate=11 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bohannon |first1=J. |title=Mechanical Turk upends social sciences |journal=Science |date=9 June 2016 |volume=352 |issue=6291 |pages=1263\u20131264 |doi=10.1126/science.352.6291.1263 |pmid=27284175 |bibcode=2016Sci...352.1263B }}</ref> There is controversy as to whether or not the data collected through such services is reliable, as it is subject to participants' desire for compensation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guilty-planet/httpblogsscientificamericancomguilty-planet20110707the-pros-cons-of-amazon-mechanical-turk-for-scientific-surveys/|title=The pros & cons of Amazon Mechanical Turk for scientific surveys|last=Jacquet|first=Jennifer|work=Scientific American Blog Network|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911163048/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guilty-planet/httpblogsscientificamericancomguilty-planet20110707the-pros-cons-of-amazon-mechanical-turk-for-scientific-surveys/|archivedate=11 September 2017}}</ref> However, use of [[Amazon Mechanical Turk|Mechanical Turk]] tends to quickly produce more diverse participant backgrounds, as well as comparably accurate data when compared to traditional collection methods.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Michael Buhrmester, Tracy Kwang, and Samuel D. Gosling|date=2011|title=Amazon's Mechanical Turk: A New Source of Inexpensive, Yet High-Quality, Data?|url=https://www.pomona.edu/sites/default/files/buhrmester_-crowdsourcing-amazon-mturk.pdf|journal=Perspectives on Psychological Science|volume=6|issue=1|pages=3\u20135|via=SAGE|doi=10.1177/1745691610393980|pmid=26162106|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729100125/https://www.pomona.edu/sites/default/files/buhrmester_-crowdsourcing-amazon-mturk.pdf|archivedate=29 July 2016|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref>\n\nThe internet has also enabled citizen scientists to gather data to be analyzed by professional researchers.  Citizen science networks are often involved in the observation of cyclic events of nature ([[phenology]]), such as effects of global warming on plant and animal life in different geographic areas,<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0410/p14s01-sten.html \"Citizen scientists\" watch for signs of climate change] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411230403/http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0410/p14s01-sten.html |date=11 April 2008 }}, ''The Christian Science Monitor'', 10 April 2008.</ref> and in monitoring programs for natural-resource management.<ref>Ballard, H., Pilz, D., Jones, E.T., and Getz, C. (2005). Training Curriculum for Scientists and Managers: Broadening Participation in Biological Monitoring. Corvallis, OR: Institute for Culture and Ecology.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Cooper | first1 = C. B. | last2 = Dickinson | first2 = J. | last3 = Phillips | first3 = T. | last4 = Bonney | first4 = R. | year = 2007 | title = Citizen Science as a Tool for Conservation in Residential Ecosystems | journal = Ecology and Society | volume = 12 | issue = 2 | doi=10.5751/es-02197-120211}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Firehock |first1 = K. |last2 = West |first2 = J. |title = A Brief History of Volunteer Biological Water Monitoring Using Macroinvertebrates |journal = Journal of the North American Benthological Society |volume = 14 |issue = 1 |pages = 197\u2013202 |doi = 10.2307/1467734 |year = 1995 |jstor = 1467734 }}</ref> On [[BugGuide]].Net, an online community of naturalists who share observations of [[arthropod]], amateurs and professional researchers contribute to the analysis. By October 2014, BugGuide has over 808,718 images submitted by more than 27,846 contributors.<ref name=BG_Stats>{{cite web|title=BugGuide System Statistics |url=http://bugguide.net/node/view/11181 |publisher=BugGuide.net |date=6 October 2014 |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425102840/http://bugguide.net/node/view/11181 |archivedate=25 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bubbles Within Bubbles.jpg|thumb|An NASA/JPL image from the Zooniverse's [[The Milky Way Project]] showing a hierarchical bubble structure]]\n\nNot counting [[iNaturalist]] and [[eBird]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/inaturalist.org|title=Alexa.com}}</ref> the [[Zooniverse (citizen science project)|Zooniverse]] is home to the internet's largest, most popular and most successful citizen science projects.<ref name=ESERO>{{cite web|title=New Zooniverse projects \u2013 Bat Detective and Click to Cure|url=http://www.esero.org.uk/news/new-zooniverse-projects-bat-detective-and-click-to-cure|publisher=European Space Education Resource Office|date=30 October 2012|accessdate=8 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014070524/http://www.esero.org.uk/news/new-zooniverse-projects-bat-detective-and-click-to-cure|archivedate=14 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1145/2702123.2702420 |chapter=Designing for Citizen Data Analysis |title=Proceedings of the 33rd Annual ACM Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems - CHI '15 |pages=4069\u20134078 |year=2015 |last1=Tinati |first1=Ramine |last2=Van Kleek |first2=Max |last3=Simperl |first3=Elena |last4=Luczak-R\u00f6sch |first4=Markus |last5=Simpson |first5=Robert |last6=Shadbolt |first6=Nigel |isbn=9781450331456 }}</ref> The Zooniverse and the suite of projects it contains is produced, maintained and developed by the Citizen Science Alliance (CSA).<ref name=CSA>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science Alliance website|url=http://www.citizensciencealliance.org|accessdate=28 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812000639/http://www.citizensciencealliance.org/|archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref> The member institutions of the CSA work with many academic and other partners around the world to produce projects that use the efforts and ability of volunteers to help scientists and researchers deal with the flood of data that confronts them. On 29 June 2015, the Zooniverse released a new software version with a project-building tool allowing any registered user to create a project.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lintott|first1=Chris|title=A Whole New Zooniverse|url=https://blog.zooniverse.org/2015/06/29/a-whole-new-zooniverse/|website=Zooniverse Blog|accessdate=15 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617133346/https://blog.zooniverse.org/2015/06/29/a-whole-new-zooniverse/|archivedate=17 June 2016|date=29 June 2015}}</ref> Project owners may optionally complete an approval process to have their projects listed on the Zooniverse site and promoted to the Zooniverse community.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zooniverse Project Builder Policies, or So You Want To Launch a Project?|url=https://www.zooniverse.org/lab-policies|website=Zooniverse|accessdate=15 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617144633/https://www.zooniverse.org/lab-policies|archivedate=17 June 2016}}</ref> A NASA/JPL picture to the right gives an example from one of Zooniverse's projects [[The Milky Way Project]].\n\nThe website [[CosmoQuest]] has as its goal \"To create a community of people bent on together advancing our understanding of the universe; a community of people who are participating in doing science, who can explain why what they do matters, and what questions they are helping to answer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cosmoquest.org/x/about/|title=About Us|work=cosmoquest.org|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803003859/http://cosmoquest.org/x/about/|archivedate=3 August 2016|date=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nCrowdCrafting enables its participants to create and run projects where volunteers help with image classification, transcription, geocoding and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crowdcrafting.org/about|title=crowdcrafting|author=Scifabric|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102215736/https://crowdcrafting.org/about|archivedate=2 November 2017|access-date=2014-10-04}}</ref> The platform is powered by PyBossa software, a free and open-source framework for crowdsourcing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pybossa.com/|title=PyBossa|author=Shuttleworth Foundation|work=pybossa.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105154726/http://pybossa.com/|archivedate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nProject Soothe is a citizen science research project based at the University of Edinburgh. The aim of this research is to create a bank of soothing images, submitted by members of the public, which can be used to help others through psychotherapy and research in the future. Since 2015, Project Soothe has received over 600 soothing photographs from people in 23 countries. Anyone aged 12 years or over are eligible to participate in this research in two ways: (1) By submitting soothing photos that they have taken with a description of why the images make them feel soothed (2) By rating the photos that have been submitted by people worldwide for their soothability.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projectsoothe.com/participate/4593532002|author=Project Soothe|title=Participate in Project Soothe|work=projectsoothe.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119235525/http://www.projectsoothe.com/participate/4593532002|archivedate=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Smartphone ===\n\nThe bandwidth and ubiquity afforded by smartphones has vastly expanded the opportunities for citizen science.  Examples include [[iNaturalist]], the San Francisco project, the WildLab, Project Noah,<ref name=PkSc>{{cite web|title=San Francisco Parks Alliance ParkScan|url=http://www.sfparksalliance.org/our-work/policy/research/parkscan|publisher=San Francisco Parks Alliance|date=2014|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805103901/http://www.sfparksalliance.org/our-work/policy/research/parkscan|archivedate=5 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=WiLa>{{cite web|title=The Wildlab|url=http://www.thewildlab.org|publisher=The Wildlab|date=2016|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824232455/http://www.thewildlab.org/|archivedate=24 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=PrjNoah>{{cite web|url=http://www.projectnoah.org|title=Project Noah|publisher=Networked Organisms|date=2016|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812112645/http://www.projectnoah.org/|archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> and Aurorasurus. Due to their ubiquity, for example, [[Twitter]], [[Facebook]], and [[smartphone]]s have been useful for citizen scientists, having enabled them to discover and propagate a new type of aurora dubbed \"STEVE\" in 2016.<ref name=\"Twitter and Citizen science\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gi.alaska.edu/Alaska-Science-Forum/citizen-science-meets-aurora |title=Citizen science meets the aurora |last=Rozell |first=Ned |date=2 April 2015 |website=University of Alaska Fairbanks Geophysical Institute |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731234543/http://www.gi.alaska.edu/Alaska-Science-Forum/citizen-science-meets-aurora |archivedate=31 July 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThere are also [[Mobile app|apps]] for monitoring birds, marine wildlife and other organisms, and the \"Loss of the Night\".<ref name=C.Clarke_YouTube>{{cite web|title=Citizen science: Chandra Clarke at TEDxChathamKent\n |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U7XOcB6_TWw|publisher=YouTube\n |date=14 March 2014|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801223346/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U7XOcB6_TWw\n |archivedate=1 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=lotn_discovery>{{cite news|last=O'Hanlon|first=Larry\n |title=Turn Yourself into a Skyglow Meter\n |url=http://news.discovery.com/space/astronomy/turn-yourself-into-a-skyglow-meter-130501.htm|accessdate=8 May 2013\n |newspaper=Discovery News|date=1 May 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503003739/http://news.discovery.com/space/astronomy/turn-yourself-into-a-skyglow-meter-130501.htm|archivedate=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Android (operating system)|Android]] app Sapelli is a mobile data-collection and -sharing platform designed with a particular focus on non-literate and illiterate users.<ref name=Sap>{{cite web|title=Sapelli\n |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/excites/software/sapelli|publisher=University College London\n |date=2016|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817000416/https://www.ucl.ac.uk/excites/software/sapelli|archivedate=17 August 2016}}</ref> The SPOTTERON app creates synergy effects for projects by sharing a common feature set.<ref>{{Cite book|date=6 November 2018 |publisher=Frontiers Media SA|pages=66\u201369\n |doi=10.3389/978-2-88945-587-4 |isbn=9782889455874|chapter=Austrian Citizen Science Conference 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"The Crowd and the Cloud\" is a four-part series broadcast during April 2017, which examines citizen science.<ref name=Crowd&Cloud>{{cite web| title=The Crowd and the Cloud| url=http://crowdandcloud.org| website=The Crowd and the Cloud| accessdate=24 April 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425030405/http://crowdandcloud.org/| archivedate=25 April 2017}}</ref> It shows how smartphones, computers and mobile technology enable regular citizens to become part of a 21st-century way of doing science.<ref name=Crowd&Cloud/> The programs also demonstrate how CSs help professional scientists to advance knowledge, which helps speed up new discoveries and innovations. The Crowd & The Cloud is based upon work supported by the [[National Science Foundation]].<ref name=Crowd&Cloud/>\n\n===Seismology===\n\nSince 1975, in order to improve earthquake detection and collect useful information, the [[European-Mediterranean Seismological Centre]] monitors the visits of earthquake eyewitnesses to its website and relies on Facebook and Twitter.<ref name=EMSC>{{cite web| title=EMSC History| url=https://www.emsc-csem.org/about| publisher=The European-Mediterranean Seismological Centre| access-date=16 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908143401/https://www.emsc-csem.org/about/| archivedate=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hydrology===\n\nCitizen science has been used to provide valuable data in [[hydrology]] (catchment science), notably flood risk, [[water quality]] and [[water resource management]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Starkey|first1=Eleanor|last2=Parkin|first2=Geoff|last3=Birkinshaw|first3=Steve|last4=Large|first4=Andy|last5=Quinn|first5=Paul|last6=Gibson|first6=Ceri|title=Demonstrating the value of community-based ('citizen science') observations for catchment modelling and characterisation|journal=Journal of Hydrology|volume=548|pages=801\u2013817|date=2017|doi=10.1016/j.jhydrol.2017.03.019|bibcode=2017JHyd..548..801S}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Community Involvement in UK Catchment Management|url=http://www.fwr.org/Catchment/frr0021.pdf|publisher=Foundation for Water Research|accessdate=27 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428053522/http://www.fwr.org/Catchment/frr0021.pdf|archivedate=28 April 2017}}</ref> A growth in internet use and smartphone ownership has allowed users to collect and share real-time flood-risk information using, for example, social media and web-based forms. Although traditional data collection methods are well-established, citizen science is being used to fill the data gaps on a local level, and is therefore meaningful to individual communities. It has been demonstrated that citizen science is particularly advantageous during a [[flash flood]] because the public are more likely to witness these rarer hydrological events than scientists.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newcastle University|title=Communities can fill the gaps on flooding|url=http://www.ncl.ac.uk/press/news/2017/04/communityfloodmonitoring/|accessdate=27 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428051503/http://www.ncl.ac.uk/press/news/2017/04/communityfloodmonitoring/|archivedate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Plastics and pollution===\n{{Further| Plastic pollution}}\n[[File:Pollution plastique 2.jpg|thumb|right|Plastic Pollution in [[Madagascar]]]]\nCitizen science includes projects that help monitor [[plastic]]s and their associated [[pollution]].<ref name=ES_PP1>{{cite news| title=How citizen scientists, technology and people power can help clean up our seas| author=Anna Turns| url=https://www.standard.co.uk/futurelondon/theplasticfreeproject/how-citizen-scientists-technology-and-people-power-can-help-clean-up-our-seas-a4261831.html| work=[[Evening Standard]]| date=15 October 2019| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=TMO_1>{{cite web| title=Finding Solutions to Plastic Pollution (How You Can Help)| url=https://treadingmyownpath.com/2016/11/10/solutions-to-plastic-pollution| publisher=Lindsay Miles| date=10 November 2016| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=ScS_1>{{cite web| title=SciStarter| url=https://scistarter.org| publisher=SciStarter.org| date=2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=CSP_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science Projects on Plastic Pollution| url=https://www.arocha.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/citizen-science-projects.pdf| publisher=A Rocha International| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref> These include [[The Ocean Cleanup]], #OneLess, The Big Microplastic Survey, EXXpedition and Alliance to End Plastic Waste.<ref name=OL_1>{{cite web| title=#OneLess| url=https://www.onelessbottle.org| publisher=OneLess 2017| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=BMS_1>{{cite web| title=The Big Microplastic Survey| url=https://microplasticsurvey.org| publisher=The Big Microplastic Survey 2018| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=EXX_1>{{cite web| title=eXXpedition| url=https://exxpedition.com| publisher=eXXpedition 2019| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=AEP_1>{{cite web| title=Alliance To End Plastic Waste| url=https://endplasticwaste.org| publisher=Alliance to End Plastic Waste| date=2019| access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref> Ellipsis seeks to map the distribution of litter using aerial data mapping by [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s and [[machine learning]] software.<ref name=EE_1>{{cite web| title=Ellipsis| url=https://ellipsis-environmental.com| publisher=Ellipsis Environmental| date=2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> A Zooniverse project called The Plastic Tide (now finished) helped train an [[algorithm]] used by Ellipsis.<ref name=TPT_1>{{cite web| title=The Plastic Tide| url=https://www.zooniverse.org/projects/theplastictide/the-plastic-tide| publisher=Zooniverse| date=2017| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nProjects that use [[Mobile app|apps]] include:<ref name=AWN_1>{{cite web| title=Mobile Apps and Marine Debris| url=https://africanwastenetwork.org.za/news/mobile-apps-marine-debris| publisher=Sustainable Seas Trust| date=29 August 2017| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[European Environment Agency]] launched an initiative called \"Marine Litter Watch\" in June 2018. This uses mobile phones to: (quote) \"help individuals and communities come together to clean up Europe\u2019s beaches.\"<ref name=EEA_1>{{cite web| title=Citizens collect plastic and data to protect Europe's marine environment| url=https://www.eea.europa.eu/themes/water/europes-seas-and-coasts/assessments/marine-litterwatch/briefing| publisher=European Environment Agency| date=8 June 2018| access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref> \n* PlasticPatrol seeks to log and record plastic pollution: (quote) \"The Plastic Patrol app is a real world tool that combines citizen science and scientific analysis to help us gather crucial insight into plastic pollution.\"<ref name=PP_1>{{cite web| title=Plastic Patrol| url=https://plasticpatrol.co.uk| publisher=Plastic Patrol CIC| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Literati's mission is to eradicate [[litter]]: (quote) \"When millions of people come together, the impossible becomes reality, and change happens.\"<ref name=Lit_1>{{cite web| title=Litterati| url=https://www.litterati.org| publisher=Litterati| date=2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Anecdata helps anyone and any organisation to create a project: (quote) \"Anecdata helps individuals and organizations collect, manage, and share their citizen science data, providing both web-based and mobile solutions for gathering and accessing observations.\"<ref name=Anec_1>{{cite web| title=Anecdata| url=https://www.anecdata.org| publisher=MDI Biological Laboratory| date=2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=MDI_1>{{cite web| title=MDI Biological Laboratory develops Anecdata citizen science mobile app| url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-01/mdib-mbl011718.php| publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science| date=January 2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* In the [[United Kingdom|UK]] #2minutebeachclean seeks to purge plastics in coastal environments.<ref name=BC_1>{{cite web| title=#2minutebeachclean| url=https://beachclean.net| publisher=2 Minute Beach Clean| access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref> They offer an app and a beachclean board, which can be displayed on beaches: (quote) \"We believe that every piece of litter removed from the beach matters. So it doesn\u2019t matter if you do 2 minutes or 30.\"<ref name=BC_1/>\n\nExamples of relevant articles (by date):\n\n* Citizen Science Promotes Environmental Engagement: (quote) \"Citizen science projects are rapidly gaining popularity among the public, in which volunteers help gather data on [[species]] that can be used by scientists in research. And it\u2019s not just adults who are involved in these projects \u2013 even kids have collected high-quality data in the US.\"<ref name=SC_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science Promotes Environmental Engagement| author=Neha Jain| url=https://magazine.scienceconnected.org/2018/01/citizen-science-environmental-engagement| publisher=Science Connected, Inc.| date=4 January 2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Tackling [[Microplastics]] on Our Own: (quote) \"Plastics, ranging from the circles of soda can rings to [[microbeads]] the size of pinheads, are starting to replace images of sewage for a leading cause of pollution \u2013 especially in the ocean\". Further, \"With recent backing from the Crowdsourcing and Citizen Science Act, citizen science is increasingly embraced as a tool by US Federal agencies.\"<ref name=TM_1>{{cite web| title=Tackling Microplastics on Our Own| author1=Alex Long| author2=Anne Bowser| url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/article/tackling-microplastics-our-own| publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars| date=6 February 2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Citizen Scientists Are Tracking Plastic Pollution Worldwide: (quote) \"Scientists who are monitoring the spread of tiny pieces of plastic throughout the environment are getting help from a small army of citizen volunteers \u2013 and they\u2019re finding bits of [[polymer]] in some of the most remote parts of North America.\"<ref name=Seek_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Scientists Are Tracking Plastic Pollution Worldwide| author=Matt Smith| url=https://www.seeker.com/conservation/citizen-scientists-are-tracking-plastic-pollution-worldwide| publisher=Group Nine Media| date=12 March 2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Artificial intelligence]] and citizen scientists: Powering the clean-up of Asia Pacific's beaches:(quote) \"The main objective is to support citizen scientists cleaning up [[New Zealand]] beaches and get a better understanding of why litter is turning up, so preventive and proactive action can be taken.\"<ref name=MAI_1>{{cite web| title=Artificial intelligence and citizen scientists: Powering the clean-up of Asia Pacific's beaches| author=Mike Chan| url=https://news.microsoft.com/apac/2019/04/29/artificial-intelligence-and-citizen-scientists-powering-the-clean-up-of-asia-pacifics-beaches| publisher=[[Microsoft]]| date=29 April 2019| access-date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n* Citizen science could help address [[Canada]]'s plastic pollution problem: (quote) \"But citizen engagement and participation in science goes beyond beach cleanups, and can be used as a tool to bridge gaps between communities and scientists. These partnerships between scientists and citizen scientists have produced real world data that have influenced policy changes.\"<ref name=Conv_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen science could help address Canada's plastic pollution problem| author=Tony Walker| url=https://theconversation.com/citizen-science-could-help-address-canadas-plastic-pollution-problem-121787| publisher=The Conversation Trust(UK) Ltd.| date=12 September 2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nExamples of relevant scientific studies or books include (by date):\n\n* ''Distribution and abundance of small plastic debris on beaches in the SE Pacific ([[Chile]]): a study supported by a citizen science project'': (quote) \"The citizen science project \"National Sampling of Small Plastic Debris\" was supported by schoolchildren from all over Chile who documented the distribution and abundance of small plastic debris on Chilean beaches. Thirty-nine schools and nearly 1000 students from continental Chile and [[Easter Island]] participated in the activity.\"<ref name=VHR_1>{{cite journal| title=Distribution and abundance of small plastic debris on beaches in theSE Pacific (Chile): A study supported by a citizen science project| author1=V. Hidalgo-Ruz| author2=M. Thiel| journal=Marine Environmental Research| date=26 February 2013| volume=87\u201388| pages=12\u201318| doi=10.1016/j.marenvres.2013.02.015| pmid=23541391}}</ref>\n* ''Incorporating citizen science to study plastics in the environment'': (quote) \"Taking advantage of public interest in the impact of plastic on the marine environment, successful Citizen Science (CS) programs incorporate members of the public to provide repeated sampling for time series as well as [[wikt:synoptic|synoptic]] collections over wide geographic regions.\"<ref name=ICS_2>{{cite journal| title=Incorporating citizen science to study plastics in the environment| author1=E.R. Zettler| author2=H. Takada| author3=B. Monteleone| author4=N. Mallos| author5=M. Eriksen| author6=L.A. Amaral-Zettler| journal=Analytical Methods| volume=9| date=14 November 2016| issue=9| pages=1392\u20131403| doi=10.1039/C6AY02716D| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/22cbd784a2c5ca88edef0c474b543d88b8a4c678}}</ref>\n* ''Marine [[Human impact on the environment| anthropogenic]] litter on British beaches: A 10-year nationwide assessment using citizen science data'': (quote) \"Citizen science projects, whereby members of the public gather information, offer a low-cost method of collecting large volumes of data with considerable temporal and spatial coverage. Furthermore, such projects raise awareness of environmental issues and can lead to positive changes in behaviours and attitudes.\"<ref name=MAL_1>{{cite journal| title=Marine anthropogenic litter on British beaches: A 10-year nationwide assessment using citizen science data| author1=S.E. Nelms| author2=C. Coombes| author3=L.C. Foster| author4=T.S. Galloway| author5=B.J. Godley| author6=P.K. Lindeque| author7=M.J. Witt| journal=Science of the Total Environment| date=1 February 2017| volume=579| pages=1399\u20131409| doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2016.11.137| pmid=27913017| bibcode=2017ScTEn.579.1399N}}</ref>\n* ''Determining Global Distribution of Microplastics by Combining Citizen Science and In-Depth Case Studies'': (quote) \"Our first project involves the general public through citizen science. Participants collect sand samples from beaches using a basic [[Protocol (science)| protocol]], and we subsequently extract and quantify microplastics in a central laboratory using the standard operating procedure.\"<ref name=GBD_1>{{cite journal| title=Determining Global Distribution of Microplastics by Combining Citizen Science and In-Depth Case Studies| author1=T. Bosker| author2=P. Behrens| author3=M.G. Vijver| journal=Integrated Environmental Assessment and Management| volume=13| issue=3| pages=536\u2013541| date=9 February 2017| doi=10.1002/ieam.1908| pmid=28440934}}</ref>\n* ''[[Risk perception| Risk Perception]] of Plastic Pollution: Importance of Stakeholder Involvement and Citizen Science'': (quote) \"The chapter finally discusses how risk perception can be improved by greater stakeholder involvement and utilization of citizen science and thereby improve the foundation for timely and efficient societal measures.\"<ref name=RP_1>{{cite book| title=Risk Perception of Plastic Pollution: Importance of Stakeholder Involvement and Citizen Science| author1=K. Syberg| author2=S.F. Hansen| author3=T.B. Christensen| author4=F.R Khan| work=Freshwater Microplastics| publisher=Springer, Cham| date=2018| volume=58| pages=203\u2013221| doi=10.1007/978-3-319-61615-5_10| isbn=978-3-319-61615-5}}</ref>\n* ''Assessing the citizen science approach as tool to increase awareness on the marine litter problem'':(quote) \"This paper provides a quantitative assessment of students' attitude and behaviors towards marine litter before and after their participation to SEACleaner, an educational and citizen science project devoted to monitor macro- and micro-litter in an Area belonging to [[Ligurian Sea Cetacean Sanctuary|Pelagos Sanctuary]].\"<ref name=ACS_1>{{cite journal| title=Assessing the citizen science approach as tool to increase awareness on the marine litter problem| author1=M.Locritania| author2=S.Merlinob| author3=M.Abbate| journal=Marine Pollution Bulletin| date=March 2019| volume=140| pages=0320\u2013329| doi=10.1016/j.marpolbul.2019.01.023| pmid=30803651}}</ref>\n* ''Spatial trends and drivers of marine debris accumulation on shorelines in [[South Eleuthera]], [[The Bahamas]] using citizen science'': (quote) \"This study measured spatial distribution of marine debris stranded on beaches in South Eleuthera, The Bahamas. Citizen science, fetch modeling, relative exposure index and predictive mapping were used to determine marine debris source and abundance.\"<ref name=ST_1>{{cite journal |last1=Ambrose |first1=Kristal K. |last2=Box |first2=Carolynn |last3=Boxall |first3=James |last4=Brooks |first4=Annabelle |last5=Eriksen |first5=Marcus |last6=Fabres |first6=Joan |last7=Fylakis |first7=Georgios |last8=Walker |first8=Tony R. |title=Spatial trends and drivers of marine debris accumulation on shorelines in South Eleuthera, The Bahamas using citizen science |journal=Marine Pollution Bulletin |date=May 2019 |volume=142 |pages=145\u2013154 |doi=10.1016/j.marpolbul.2019.03.036 |pmid=31232287 }}</ref><ref name=ST_2>{{cite web| title=Spatial trends and drivers of marine debris accumulation on shorelines in South Eleuthera, The Bahamas using citizen science| last1=Ambrose |first1=Kristal K. |last2=Box |first2=Carolynn |last3=Boxall |first3=James |last4=Brooks |first4=Annabelle |last5=Eriksen |first5=Marcus |last6=Fabres |first6=Joan |last7=Fylakis |first7=Georgios |last8=Walker |first8=Tony R. | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/331839548| publisher=ResearchGate| date=May 2019| access-date=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n* ''Making citizen science count: Best practices and challenges of citizen science projects on plastics in [[Aquatic ecosystem| aquatic environments]]'':(quote) \"Citizen science is a [[Cost-effectiveness analysis|cost-effective]] way to gather data over a large geographical range while simultaneously raising public awareness on the problem\".<ref name=MCS_1>{{cite journal| title=Making citizen science count: Best practices and challenges of citizen science projects on plastics in aquatic environments| author1=L. Rambonnet| author2=S.C.Vink| author3=A.M.Land-Zandstra| author4=T. Bosker| journal=Marine Pollution Bulletin| date=August 2019| volume=145| pages=271\u2013277|doi=10.1016/j.marpolbul.2019.05.056| pmid=31590787}}</ref><ref name=UL_1>{{cite web| title=How do you make citizen science successful?| url=https://www.universiteitleiden.nl/en/news/2019/06/how-do-you-make-citizen-science-successful| \npublisher=Universiteit Leiden| date=14 June 2019| access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n* ''White and wonderful? Microplastics prevail in snow from the [[Alps]] to the [[Arctic]]'': (quote) \"\"In March 2018, five samples were taken at different locations on [[Svalbard]] (Fig. 1A and Table 1) by citizen scientists embarking on a land expedition by [[ski-doo]] (Aemalire project). The citizens were instructed on contamination prevention and equipped with protocol forms, prerinsed 2-liter stainless steel containers (Ecotanca), a porcelain mug, a steel spoon, and a soup ladle for sampling.\"<ref name=WaW_1>{{cite journal| title=White and wonderful? Microplastics prevail in snow from the Alps to the Arctic| author1=M. Bergmann| author2=S. M\u00fctzel| author3=S. Primpke| author4=M.B. Tekman| author5=J. Trachsel| author6=G. Gerdts| journal=[[Science Advances]]| date=14 August 2019| volume=5| issue=8| doi=10.1126/sciadv.aax1157| pmid=31453336| pmc=6693909| page=eaax1157}}</ref>\n\n===Citizen sensing===\n\nCitizen sensing can be a form of Citizen science: (quote) \"The work of citizen sensing, as a form of citizen science, then further transforms [[Isabelle Stengers| Stengers]]\u2019s notion of the work of science by moving the experimental facts and collectives where scientific work is undertaken out of the laboratory of experts and into the world of citizens.\"<ref name=FCS_1>{{cite journal|title=From Citizen Sensing to Collective Monitoring:Working through the Perceptive and Affective Problematics of Environmental Pollution|author1=H. Pritchard|author2=J. Gabrys|journal=GeoHumanities|date=16 November 2016|volume=2|issue=2|pages=354\u2013371|doi=10.1080/2373566X.2016.1234355}}</ref> Similar sensing activities include [[Crowdsensing]] and [[Participatory monitoring]]. While the idea of using mobile technology to aid this sensing is not new, creating devices and systems that can be used to aid regulation has not been straightforward.<ref name=FCS_1/> Some examples of projects that include citizen sensing are:\n* Citizen Sense (2013-2018): (quote) \"Practices of monitoring and sensing environments have migrated to everyday participatory applications, where users of smart phones and networked devices are able to engage with modes of environmental observation and data collection.\"<ref name=CitSen_1>{{cite web|title=Citizen Sense|url=https://citizensense.net|publisher=Citizen Sense| date=2017| access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=CSEP_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Sensing and Environmental Practice: Assessing Participatory Engagements with Environments through Sensor Technologies|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/rcn/106442/factsheet/en|publisher=EU Publications Office|date=2 August 2019|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Breathe Project: (quote) \"We use the best available science and technology to better understand the quality of the air we breathe and provide opportunities for citizens to engage and take action.\"<ref name=BPr_1>{{cite web|title=Breathe Project|url=https://breatheproject.org|publisher=Breathe Project|date=2019|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* The Bristol Approach to Citizen Sensing: (quote) \"Citizen Sensing is about empowering people and places to understand and use smart tech and data from sensors to tackle the issues they care about, connect with other people who can help, and take positive, practical action.\"<ref name=BrAp_1>{{cite web|title=The Bristol Approach|url=https://www.bristolapproach.org|publisher=The Bristol Approach|date=2018|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=URB_1>{{cite web|title=Citizen sensing - where people act as sensors|url=https://urbact.eu/citizen-sensing-where-people-act-sensors|publisher=URBACT|date=2017|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Luftdaten.info: (quote) \"You and thousands of others around the world install self-built sensors on the outside their home. Luftdaten.info generates a continuously updated particular matter map from the transmitted data.\"<ref name=LDI_1>{{cite web|title=Luftdaten.info|url=https://luftdaten.info|publisher=OK Lab Stuttgart|date=6 October 2016|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* CitiSense: (quote) \"CitiSense aims to co-develop a participatory risk management system (PRMS) with citizens, local authorities and organizations which enables them to contribute to advanced climate services and enhanced urban climate resilience as well as receive recommendations that support their security.\"<ref name=CsSe_1>{{cite web|title=Citizen Sensing \u2013 Urban Climate Resilience through Participatory Risk Management Systems|url=https://citta.fe.up.pt/projects/1-48-citizen-sensing-2013-urban-climate-resilience-through-participatory-risk-management-systems|publisher=CITTA|date=September 2017|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus (COVID19) pandemic===\n{{also| Wikipedia:WikiProject COVID-19| Portal:Coronavirus disease 2019| COVID-19 apps}}\n\nResources for CS and scientific [[Crowdsourcing#Health-care_crowdsourcing| Crowdsourcing]] projects concerning the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID19) can be found on the internet or as apps.<ref name=CSR1>{{cite web | title=Citizen science resources related to the COVID19 pandemic| url=https://www.citizenscience.org/covid-19| author=CSA team| publisher=Citizen Science Association| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=COIE_1>{{cite web| title=COVID-19 Open Innovation Efforts| url=https://my.usgs.gov/confluence/display/cdi/COVID-19+Open+Innovation+Efforts| publisher=[[University of California, San Francisco]]| date=24 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=HHMI_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Scientists Are Helping Researchers Design New Drugs to Combat COVID-19| url=https://www.hhmi.org/news/citizen-scientists-are-helping-researchers-design-new-drugs-to-combat-covid-19| publisher=[[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]]| date=26 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> These include:\n\n* The Eterna OpenVaccine project enables video game players to \"design an mRNA encoding a potential vaccine against the novel coronavirus.\"<ref name=\"EOV_1\">{{cite web| title=Eterna OpenVaccine| author=Do Soon & the Eterna Developer Team| url=https://eternagame.org/web/news/9818657/| publisher=Eterna| date=23 March 2020| access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* EU-Citizen.Science has (quote): \"A selection of resources related to the current COVID19 pandemic. It contains links to citizen science and crowdsourcing projects\"<ref name=EUCS_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen science resources related to the COVID19 pandemic| author=Lucie Steigleder| url=http://eu-citizen.science/citizen-science-resources-related-to-the-covid19-pandemic| publisher=EU-Citizen.Science| date=24 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* COVID-19 Citizen Science is (quote): \"A new initiative by [[University of California, San Francisco]] physician-scientists\" that \"will allow anyone in the world age 18 or over to become a citizen scientist advancing understanding of the disease.\"<ref name=UCSF_1>{{cite web| title=New COVID-19 \u2018Citizen Science\u2019 Initiative Lets Any Adult with a Smartphone Help to Fight Coronavirus| author=Jeff Norris| url=https://www.ucsf.edu/news/2020/03/417026/new-covid-19-citizen-science-initiative-lets-any-adult-smartphone-help-fight|  publisher=The Regents of The University of California| date=30 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* CoronaReport is (quote): \"A citizen science project which democratizes the reporting on the Coronavirus, and makes these reports accessible to other citizens.\"<ref name=CR_1>{{cite web| title=CoronaReport| url=https://www.coronareport.eu| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CR_2>{{cite web| title=Corona Report App (social media)| url=https://www.facebook.com/coronareportapp| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* COVID Symptom Tracker is a crowdsourced study (quote): \"By using this app you're contributing to advance vital research on COVID-19. The app will be used to study the symptoms of the virus and track how it spreads.\" It has had two million downloads by April 2020.<ref name=CST_1>{{cite web| title=COVID Symptom Tracker| url=https://covid.joinzoe.com| publisher=[[King's College London]]| date=March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=COCO_1>{{cite web| title=New COVID-19 symptom tracker app helps researchers better understand coronavirus| url=https://www.clickorlando.com/health/2020/04/01/new-covid-19-symptom-tracker-app-helps-researchers-better-understand-coronavirus| author=Gwen Baumgardner| publisher=ClickOrlando.com| date=1 April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Covid Near You (quote): \"Uses crowdsourced data to visualize maps to help citizens and public health agencies identify current and potential hotspots for the recent pandemic coronavirus, COVID-19.\"<ref name=CNY_1>{{cite web| title=Covid Near You| author=CNY team| url=https://www.covidnearyou.org/#!/who-we-are| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor Coronavirus studies and information that can help enable CS, many online resources are available through [[Open access]] and [[Open science]] websites.(e.g.<ref name=CUP_1>{{cite web| title=Coronavirus Free Access Collection| url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/browse-subjects/medicine/coronavirus-free-access-collection| publisher=Cambridge University Press| date=2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=SPARC_1>{{cite web| title=The Coronavirus and Open Science: Our reads and Open use cases| url=https://sparceurope.org/coronaopensciencereadsandusecases| publisher=SPARC| date=March 2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=TL_1>{{cite web| title=The Lancet COVID-19 Resource Centre| url=https://www.thelancet.com/coronavirus| publisher=2020 Elsevier Inc.| date=April 2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Wil_1>{{cite web| title=Covid-19: Novel Coronavirus Outbreak| url=https://novel-coronavirus.onlinelibrary.wiley.com| publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc.| date=March 2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Spri_1>{{cite web| title=SARS-CoV-2 and COVID-19| url=https://www.springernature.com/gp/researchers/campaigns/coronavirus| publisher=Springer Nature| date=2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>)\n\n==Around the world ==\n{{also|List of citizen science projects|Citizen science#National and regional portals}} \n===Africa ===\n\n*In [[South Africa]] (SA), CS projects include: the Stream Assessment Scoring System (miniSASS) which \"encourages enhanced catchment management for water security in a climate stressed society.\"<ref name=SASS>{{cite web|title=Healthy Rivers \u2013 Healthy people: Citizen Science for sustainable water management in a climate stressed society|url=http://www.wessa.org.za/what-we-do/water-programme/healthy-rivers-healthy-people.htm|publisher=The Wildlife and Environment Society of South Africa|date=2014|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817021400/http://www.wessa.org.za/what-we-do/water-programme/healthy-rivers-healthy-people.htm|archivedate=17 August 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Snapshot serengeti.jpg|thumb|right|Snapshot Serengeti classifies animals at the [[Serengeti National Park]] in [[Tanzania]]]]\n*Also in SA, \"Members of the public, or 'citizen scientists' are helping researchers from the University of Pretoria to identify Phytophthora species present in the fynbos.\"<ref name=CS_Fynbos>{{cite web|title=Citizen engagement in research to protect fynbos \u2013 and forests|author=Joey Hulbert|url=http://saforestryonline.co.za/articles/citizen-engagement-research-protect-fynbos-forests|publisher=SA Forestry Online|date=10 February 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802102813/http://saforestryonline.co.za/articles/citizen-engagement-research-protect-fynbos-forests/|archivedate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n*In June 2016, citizen science experts from across East Africa gathered in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]] for a symposium organised by the Tropical Biology Association (TBA) in partnership with the Centre for Ecology & Hydrology (CEH). The aim was \"to harness the growing interest and expertise in East Africa to stimulate new ideas and collaborations in citizen science.\" Rosie Trevelyan of the TBA said: \"We need to enhance our knowledge about the status of Africa's species and the threats facing them.  And scientists can't do it all on their own. At the same time, citizen science is an extremely effective way of connecting people more closely to nature and enrolling more people in conservation action\".<ref name=TBA_CEH>{{cite web|title=Citizen science takes a leap forward in East Africa|url=http://www.tropical-biology.org/citizen-science-takes-a-leap-forward-in-east-africa|publisher=Tropical Biology Association|date=June 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712090949/http://www.tropical-biology.org/citizen-science-takes-a-leap-forward-in-east-africa/|archivedate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n*The website [[Zooniverse]] hosts several African CS projects, including: Snapshot Serengeti, Wildcam Gorongosa and Jungle Rhythms.<ref name=Zoo_CS>{{cite web|title=Zooniverse Projects|url=https://www.zooniverse.org/projectspublisher=Zooniverse|publisher=[[Zooniverse]]|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807015915/https://www.zooniverse.org/projectspublisher=Zooniverse|archivedate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Nigeria]] has the Ibadan Bird Club whose to aim is to \"exchange ideas and share knowledge about birds, and get actively involved in the conservation of birds and biodiversity.\"<ref name=IBC>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science and Bird Conservation in Nigeria|url=https://www.africanbirdclub.org/sites/default/files/2013_Bird_Identification_Workshop_Nigeria.pdf|publisher=Nigerian Conservation Foundation|date=March 2014|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017002631/https://www.africanbirdclub.org/sites/default/files/2013_Bird_Identification_Workshop_Nigeria.pdf|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n*In [[Namibia]], Giraffe Spotter.org is \"project that will provide people with an online citizen science platform for giraffes\".<ref name=GS>{{cite web|title=Citizen science project will benefit Africa's giraffes|author=Megan Hamilton|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/environment/citizen-science-project-will-benefit-africa-s-giraffes/article/403071|work=Digital Journal|date=15 September 2014|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822191901/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/environment/citizen-science-project-will-benefit-africa-s-giraffes/article/403071|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n*Within the [[Republic of the Congo]], the territories of an indigenous people have been mapped so that \"the Mbendjele tribe can protect treasured trees from being cut down by logging companies\". An Android open-source app called Sapelli was used by the Mbendjele which helped them map \"their tribal lands and highlighted trees that were important to them, usually for medicinal reasons or religious significance. Congolaise Industrielle des Bois then verified the trees that the tribe documented as valuable and removed them from its cutting schedule. The tribe also documented illegal logging and poaching activities.\"<ref name=Mb_Sapelli>{{cite web|title=Mapping Indigenous Territories in Africa|url=http://www.esri.com/esri-news/arcnews/winter16articles/mapping-indigenous-territories-in-africa|publisher=Esri|date=2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801073639/http://www.esri.com/esri-news/arcnews/winter16articles/mapping-indigenous-territories-in-africa|archivedate=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n*In [[West Africa]], the eradication of the recent outbreak of [[Ebola virus disease]] was partly helped by CS. \"Communities learnt how to assess the risks posed by the disease independently of prior cultural assumptions, and local empiricism allowed cultural rules to be reviewed, suspended or changed as epidemiological facts emerged.\" \"Citizen science is alive and well in all three Ebola-affected countries. And if only a fraction of the international aid directed at rebuilding health systems were to be redirected towards support for citizen science, that might be a fitting memorial to those who died in the epidemic.\"<ref name=WA_Ebola>{{cite web|title=How black bin bags and common sense helped end an epidemic, and what we can learn from it|author=Paul Richards|url=http://africanarguments.org/2016/05/19/how-black-bin-bags-and-common-sense-helped-end-ebola-and-what-we-can-learn-from-it|publisher=African Arguments|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630015128/http://africanarguments.org/2016/05/19/how-black-bin-bags-and-common-sense-helped-end-ebola-and-what-we-can-learn-from-it/|archivedate=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n* The [[Hong Kong Bird Watching Society|Hong Kong Birdwatching Society]] was established in 1957, and is the only local civil society aiming at appreciating and conserving Hong Kong birds and their natural environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hkbws.org.hk/web/eng/index_eng.htm|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u89c0\u9ce5\u6703 Hong Kong Bird Watching Society|website=www.hkbws.org.hk|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> Their bird surveys go back to 1958, and they carry out a number of Citizen Science events such as their yearly sparrow census.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sparrow795.wixsite.com/hkbws-sparrow|title=hkbws-sparrow|website=hkbws-sparrow|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n* The Bird Count India partnership consists of a large number of organizations and groups involved in birdwatching and bird surveys. They coordinate a number of Citizen Science projects such as the Kerala Bird Atlas and Mysore city Bird Atlas that map the distribution and abundance of birds of entire Indian states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birdcount.in/|title=Bird Count India|website=Bird Count India|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n* The Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network, founded in 2011 and consists of more than 16,000 members as of 2019, is a Citizen Science project where [[roadkill]] across Taiwan is photographed and sent to the Endemic Species Research Institute for study. Its primary goal has been to set up an eco-friendly path to mitigate roadkill challenges and popularize national discourse on environmental issues and civil participation in scientific research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://roadkill.tw/|title=\u53f0\u7063\u52d5\u7269\u8def\u6b7b\u89c0\u5bdf\u7db2 Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network {{!}} \u6539\u5584\u8def\u6b7b\u3001\u74b0\u5883\u6559\u80b2\u3001\u5168\u6c11\u79d1\u5b78\u3001\u73cd\u60dc\u751f\u547d|website=roadkill.tw|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> The members of the Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network volunteer to observe the animals\u2019 corpses caused by roadkill or other reasons in Taiwan, and upload pictures and geographic locations of the roadkill to an internet database or send the corpses to the Endemic Species Research for making specimen. Because the members come from different areas of the island, the collection of data could serve as an animal distribution map of the island. According to the geographical data and pictures of dead animals collected by the members, the community itself and the sponsor the Endemic Species Center could find out the hotspots and the reasons of animals\u2019 death. One of the most renowned case is that the community successfully detected rabies cases due to the massively collected data and the corpse of Melogale moschata have been accumulated for years and alarmed the government authority to take actions to prevent the prevalence of rabies in Taiwan immediately. Another case in 2014 that some citizen scientists discovered birds that died from unknown causes near an agricultural area, then Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network cooperated with National Pingtung University of Science and Technology and engaged citizen scientists to collect bird carcass. The volunteers collected 250 bird corpses for laboratory tests, which con\ufb01rmed that the bird deaths were attributable to the pesticides used on crops. This prompted the Taiwanese government to restrict pesticides, and the Bill of Pesticide Management amendment, establishing a pesticide control system, was passed after the third reading in the Legislative Yuan. The results indicated that Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network developed a set of shared working methods and jointly completed certain actions. Furthermore, the community of Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network have made real changes on road resign to avoid roadkill, improved the management of usage of pesticide, epidemic prevention, and so on.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hsu|first=Chia-Hsuan|last2=Lin|first2=Te-En|last3=Fang|first3=Wei-Ta|last4=Liu|first4=Chi-Chang|date=2018-10-10|title=Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network: An Example of a Community of Practice Contributing to Taiwanese Environmental Literacy for Sustainability|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/328208270|journal=Sustainability|volume=10|issue=10|pages=3610|doi=10.3390/su10103610}}</ref>\n*The AirBox Project was launched in Taiwan to create a participatory ecosystem with a focus on PM2.5 monitoring with AirBox devices. At the end of 2014, the public paid more attention to the PM2.5 level because the air pollution problem became worse, especially in central and southern Taiwan. High PM2.5 level is harmful to our health, such as respiratory problems, so it aroused public concerns and led to an intensive debate about air pollution sources. Some experts indicated that the air quality was affected by pollutants from Mainland China, while some environmentalists believed that it is the result of industrialization such as exhaust fumes from local power plants or factories; however, no one knew the answer because of insufficient data. Dr. Ling-Jyh Chen, a researcher of the Institute of Information Science, Academia Sinica, launched The AirBox Project. His original idea is inspired by a popular Taiwanese slogan Save Your Environment by Yourself. As an expert in Participatory Sensing System, he decided to take this bottom-up approach to collect PM2.5 level data, and through open data and data analysis to have a better understanding of the possible air pollution source. In this ecosystem, massive data was collected from the AirBox device. Data was instantly revealed online to inform people of PM2.5 level so that they take proper action, such as wearing a mask or staying at home, to prevent themselves from directly exploring to polluted environment. Data could be also analyzed to understand the possible sources of pollution and provide recommendations for improving the situation. To be precise, there are four main steps in this project. '''I)''' Develop the AirBox device. Developing a device that could correctly collect the data of the PM2.5 level was time-consuming. It took more than three years to develop AirBox that can be easily used, but with both high accuracy and low cost. '''II)''' Broad installation of AirBox. In the beginning, very few people were willing to install it at their homes because of their concerns about the possible harm to their health, power-consuming problem and maintenances of it, so that AirBoxs were only installed in a relatively small area. Thanks to the help from Taiwan's LASS (Location Aware Sensing System) community, AirBox appeared in all parts of Taiwan. As of February 2017, there are more than 1,600 Air Boxes installed in more than 27 countries. '''III)''' Open Source and Data Analysis. All measurement results were released and visualized in real-time to the public through different media, such as [https://pm25.lass-net.org/ their website] and [https://www.facebook.com/groups/pm25opendata/ Facebook page]. Data can be analyzed to trace pollution sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://research.sinica.edu.tw/pm25-air-box/|title=\u7a7a\u6c23\u76d2\u5b50\u63a8\u624b\uff1a\u7a7a\u6c23\u8b8a\u9ad2\u4e86\uff0c\u96e3\u9053\u6c92\u6709\u8fa6\u6cd5\u55ce\uff1f\u2502\u7814\u4e4b\u6709\u7269 - \u4e2d\u592e\u7814\u7a76\u9662\u8cc7\u6599\u79d1\u5b78\u7814\u7a76|date=2017-02-16|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n*Japan has a long history of citizen science involvement, the 1,200-year-old tradition of collecting records on [[cherry blossom]] flowering probably being the world's longest-running citizen science project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technology.org/2015/03/25/cherry-blossom-season-emperors-sake-and-citizen-science/|title=Cherry blossom season, Emperor's sake and Citizen Science|date=25 March 2015|website=Technology Org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref> One of the most influential citizen science projects has also come out of Japan: [[Safecast (organization)|Safecast]]. Dedicated to open citizen science for the environment, Safecast was established in the wake of the [[Fukushima nuclear disaster]], and produces open hardware sensors for radiation and air-pollution mapping. Presenting this data via a global open data network and maps<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.safecast.org/|title=Safecast|website=Safecast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\n===South America ===\n[[File:Ashaninca children in school.jpg|thumb|right|Ash\u00e1ninka children in school]]\n*In 2015 the [[Ash\u00e1ninka people]] from Apiwtxa, which crosses the border between [[Brazil]] and [[Peru]], began using the Android app Sapelli to monitor their land. The Ashaninka have \"faced historical pressures of disease, exploitation and displacement, and today still face the illegal invasion of their lands by loggers and hunters. This monitoring project shows how the Apiwtxa Ashaninka from the Kampa do Rio Am\u00f4nia Indigenous Territory, Brazil, are beginning to use smartphones and technological tools to monitor these illegal activities more effectively.\"<ref name=Ash_Api>{{cite web|title=Ashaninka Land Monitoring Initiative|url=http://forestcompass.org/case-studies/ashaninka-land-monitoring-initiative|publisher=Global Canopy Programme|date=April 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423075020/http://forestcompass.org/case-studies/ashaninka-land-monitoring-initiative|archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref>\n*In [[Argentina]], two smartphone [[Android (operating system)|Android]] applications are available for CS. '''i)''' AppEAR has been developed at the Institute of [[Limnology]] and was launched in May 2016.<ref name=AppEAR>{{cite web|title=AppEAR: una aplicaci\u00f3n para estudiar ambientes acu\u00e1ticos con colaboraci\u00f3n ciudadana|author=Marcelo Gisande|url=http://www.conicet.gov.ar/appear-una-aplicacion-para-estudiar-ambientes-acuaticos-con-colaboracion-ciudadana|publisher=CONICET|date=7 June 2016|accessdate=1 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812041610/http://www.conicet.gov.ar/appear-una-aplicacion-para-estudiar-ambientes-acuaticos-con-colaboracion-ciudadana/|archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> Joaqu\u00edn Coachman is a researcher who developed an \"application that appeals to the collaboration of users of mobile devices in collecting data that allow the study of aquatic ecosystems\" (translation).<ref name=AppEAR/> Coachman stated: \"Not much of citizen science in Argentina, just a few more oriented to astronomy specific cases.  As ours is the first.  And I have volunteers from different parts of the country that are interested in joining together to centralize data.  That's great because these types of things require many people participate actively and voluntarily\" (translation).<ref name=AppEAR/> '''ii)''' eBird was launched in 2013, and has so far identified 965 species of birds.<ref name=Arg_ebird>{{cite web|title=Ciencia ciudadana: la cultura de la colaboraci\u00f3n|author=Federico Kukso|url=http://fkukso.com/post/86028119770/ciencia-ciudadana-la-cultura-de-la-colaboraci%C3%B3n|date=2016|accessdate=1 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829065141/http://fkukso.com/post/86028119770/ciencia-ciudadana-la-cultura-de-la-colaboraci%C3%B3n|archivedate=29 August 2016}}</ref> eBird in Argentina is \"developed and managed by the Cornell Lab of Ornithology at [[Cornell University]], one of the most important ornithological institutions in the world, and locally presented recently with the support of the Ministry of Science, Technology and Productive Innovation of the Nation (MINCyT)\" (translation).<ref name=Arg_ebird/>\n*Projects in [[Brazil]] include: '''i)''' Platform and mobile app 'Missions' has been developed by [[IBM]] in their [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] research lab with Brazil's Ministry for Environment and Innovation (BMEI).<ref name=Mission>{{cite news|title=IBM and SAP open up big data platforms for citizen science|author=Kristine A. Wong|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/tech-giants-ibm-sap-citizen-science-big-data|date=27 January 2014|accessdate=2 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826070641/https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/tech-giants-ibm-sap-citizen-science-big-data|archivedate=26 August 2016}}</ref> Sergio Borger, an IBM team lead in S\u00e3o Paulo, devised the crowdsourced approach when BMEI approached the company in 2010. They were looking for a way to create a central repository for the rainforest data.<ref name=Mission/> Users can upload photos of a plant species and its components, enter its characteristics (such as color and size), compare it against a catalog photo and classify it. The classification results are juried by crowdsourced ratings.<ref name=Mission/> '''ii)''' Exoss Citizen Science is a member of Astronomers Without Borders and seeks to explore the southern sky for new meteors and radiants.<ref name=Exoss>{{cite web|title=Exoss Citizen Science|url=http://astronomerswithoutborders.org/my-awb/our-current-affiliates/network.html?id=510|publisher=Astronomy Without Borders|date=July 2015|accessdate=2 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818054051/http://astronomerswithoutborders.org/my-awb/our-current-affiliates/network.html?id=510|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> Users can report meteor fireballs through uploading pictures on to a webpage or by linking to [[YouTube]].<ref name=Exoss/> [[File:Jaguar in Pantanal Brazil 2.jpg|thumb|right|A jaguar in [[Pantanal]]; an example of Brazilian [[biodiversity]].]] '''iii)''' The Information System on Brazilian Biodiversity (SiBBr) was launched in 2014 \"aiming to encourage and facilitate the publication, integration, access and use of information about the biodiversity of the country.\"<ref name=SiBBr>{{cite web|title=SiBBr completes one year with six million records on biodiversity|url=https://www.rnp.br/en/noticias/sibbr-completa-ano-seis-milhoes-registros|publisher=RNP|date=26 November 2015|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920002851/https://www.rnp.br/en/noticias/sibbr-completa-ano-seis-milhoes-registros|archivedate=20 September 2016}}</ref> Their initial goal \"was to gather 2.5 million occurrence records of species from biological collections in Brazil and abroad up to the end of 2016. It is now expected that SiBBr will reach nine million records in 2016.\" Andrea Portela said: \"In 2016, we will begin with the citizen science. They are tools that enable anyone, without any technical knowledge, to participate. With this we will achieve greater engagement with society. People will be able to have more interaction with the platform, contribute and comment on what Brazil has.<ref name=SiBBr/> '''iv)''' The Brazilian Marine Megafauna Project (Iniciativa Pro Mar) is working with the European CSA towards its main goal, which is the \"sensibilization of society for marine life issues\" and concerns about pollution and the over-exploitation of natural resources.<ref name=IPM>{{cite web|title=Brasil Megafauna Marinha|url=http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/profile-supporter_profile/490|publisher=ECSA|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818122208/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/profile-supporter_profile/490|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> Having started as a project monitoring [[manta ray]], it now extends to [[whale shark]] and educating schools and divers within the Santos area.<ref name=IPM/> Its social media activities include a live streaming of a CS course to help divers identify marine megafauna.<ref name=IPM/> '''v)''' A smartphone app called Plantix has been developed by the [[Leibniz Centre for Agricultural Landscape Research]] (ZALF) which helps Brazilian farmers discover crop diseases quicker and helps fight them more efficiently.<ref name=Zalf>{{cite web|title=Crop protection via smart phone: ZALF and PEAT start new Citizen Science project|url=http://www.zalf.de/en/aktuelles/meldungen_alle/Pages/LSA/Plantix.aspx|publisher=Leibniz-Zentrum f\u00fcr Agrarlandschaftsforschung|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818020517/http://www.zalf.de/en/aktuelles/meldungen_alle/Pages/LSA/Plantix.aspx|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> Brazil is a very large agricultural exporter, but between 10-30% of crops fail because of disease.<ref name=Zalf/> \"The database currently includes 175 frequently occurring crop diseases and pests as well as 40,000 photos. The identification [[algorithm]] of the app improves with every image which records a success rate of over 90 per cent as of approximately 500 photos per crop disease.\"<ref name=Zalf/> '''vi)''' In an [[Atlantic Ocean]] forest region in Brazil, an effort to map the genetic riches of soil is under way.<ref name=DFD>{{cite web|title=Citizen scientists sift soil for new antibiotics|author=Penny Sarchet|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn26825-citizen-scientists-sift-soil-for-new-antibiotics|publisher=RBI|date=20 January 2015|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413024228/https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn26825-citizen-scientists-sift-soil-for-new-antibiotics/|archivedate=13 April 2016}}</ref> The Drugs From Dirt initiative, based at the [[Rockefeller University]], seeks to turn up [[bacteria]] that yield new types of antibiotics- the Brazilian region being particularly rich in potentially useful bacterial genes.<ref name=DFD/> Approximately a quarter of the 185 soil samples have been taken by Citizen Scientists without which the project could not run.<ref name=DFD/>\n*In [[Chile]] CS projects include (some websites in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]): '''i)''' Testing new cancer therapies with scientists from the Science Foundation for Life.<ref name=Ch_CS>{{cite web|title=Chilecientifico Ciencia Ciudadana|publisher=Chilecient\u00edfico|url=http://chilecientifico.cl/participar.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628075551/http://chilecientifico.cl/participar.html|archivedate=28 June 2016}}</ref> '''ii)''' Monitoring the population of the Chilean [[bumblebee]].<ref name=BB_FB>{{cite web|title=Saving Chile's bumblebee from extinction|publisher=Bee Safe|url=http://www.bee-safe.eu/save-chiles-bumblebee-from-extinction|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916060258/http://www.bee-safe.eu/save-chiles-bumblebee-from-extinction/|archivedate=16 September 2016}}</ref> '''iii)''' Monitoring the invasive [[Coccinellidae|ladybird]] Chinita arlequ\u00edn.<ref name=Ch_Ar>{{cite web|title=Chinita arlequin: Harmonia axryidis en Chile|author1=A.A. Grez|author2=T. Zaviezo|url=http://www.chinita-arlequin.uchile.cl|publisher=Chinita Arlequ\u00edn en Chile|date=2015|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802030754/http://www.chinita-arlequin.uchile.cl/|archivedate=2 August 2016}}</ref> '''iv)''' Collecting rain water data.<ref name=Ch_RW>{{cite web|title=Pluvi\u00f3metros Ciudadanos|url=http://milluvia.dga.cl/index.php|publisher=Direcci\u00f3n General de Aguas: Ministerio de Obras P\u00fablicas|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820124029/http://milluvia.dga.cl/index.php|archivedate=20 August 2016}}</ref> '''v)''' Monitoring various pollinating [[fly]] populations.<ref name=MFC>{{cite web|title=Moscas Floricholas de Chile|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/774986852548819|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122141323/https://www.facebook.com/groups/774986852548819|archivedate=22 January 2017}}</ref> '''vi)''' Providing information and field data on the abundance and distribution of various species of [[Sebastidae|rockfish]].<ref name=Ch_RFish>{{cite web|title=Lanzamiento Programa Primera Red de Buzos Deportivos para la Conservaci\u00f3n de Peces de Roca|url=http://www.costahumboldt.org/2015/01/27/lanzamiento-programa-primera-red-de-buzos-deportivos-para-la-conservacion-de-peces-de-roca|publisher=Costa Humboldt|date=27 January 2015|accessdate=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008002133/http://www.costahumboldt.org/2015/01/27/lanzamiento-programa-primera-red-de-buzos-deportivos-para-la-conservacion-de-peces-de-roca/|archive-date=8 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:\u00c1rboles en Bogot\u00e1 - Humedal de C\u00f3rdoba Vegetaci\u00f3n.JPG|thumb|right|[[C\u00f3rdoba (wetland)|C\u00f3rdoba wetland]]]]\n*Projects in [[Colombia]] include (some websites in Spanish): '''i)''' The Communications Project of the Humboldt Institute along with the Organization for Education and Environmental Protection initiated projects in the [[Bogot\u00e1]] [[wetlands]] of [[C\u00f3rdoba (wetland)|Cordoba]] and [[El Burro]], which have a lot of [[biodiversity]].<ref name=HI_Wet>{{cite web| title=Concluy\u00f3 proyecto piloto de ciencia ciudadana en humedales de Bogot\u00e1| url=http://www.humboldt.org.co/es/noticias/notas/item/243-concluyo-proyecto-piloto-de-ciencia-ciudadana-en-humedales-de-bogota| publisher=Humboldt Institute| date=2014| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816145953/http://www.humboldt.org.co/es/noticias/notas/item/243-concluyo-proyecto-piloto-de-ciencia-ciudadana-en-humedales-de-bogota| archivedate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=OpEPA>{{cite web| title=Organizaci\u00f3n para la Educaci\u00f3n y Protecci\u00f3n Ambiental| url=http://www.opepa.org| publisher=OpEPA| date=2016| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810092951/http://opepa.org/| archivedate=10 August 2016}}</ref> '''ii)''' In the Model Forest of Risaralda, the Colombia {{lang|es|'proyecto de Ciencia Abierta y Colaborativa'}} promotes citizen participation in research related to how the local environment is adapting to climate change. The first meeting took place in the Flora and Fauna Sanctuary Ot\u00fan Quimbaya.<ref name=PCA>{{cite web| title=Ciencia ciudadana en el Bosque Modelo Risaralda, Colombia| author=Comunicaci\u00f3n RIABM editor| url=http://www.bosquesmodelo.net/ciencia-ciudadana-en-el-bosque-modelo-risaralda-colombia| publisher=Red Iberoamericana de Bosques Modelo| date=4 August 2015| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017063902/http://www.bosquesmodelo.net/ciencia-ciudadana-en-el-bosque-modelo-risaralda-colombia/| archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref> '''iii''') The Citizen Network Environmental Monitoring (CLUSTER), based in the city of [[Bucaramanga]], seeks to engage younger students in [[data science]], who are trained in building weather stations with open repositories based on free software and open hardware data.<ref name=Cluster>{{cite web| title=Red Ambiental Ciudadana de Monitoreo (RACIMO)| url=http://halley.uis.edu.co/tierra/?page_id=143| publisher=Racimo| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809220831/http://halley.uis.edu.co/tierra/?page_id=143| archivedate=9 August 2016}}</ref> '''iv)''' The Symposium on Biodiversity has adapted the CS tool iNaturalist for use in Colombia.<ref name=SIB>{{cite web| title=SIB Report No.2| url=http://www.sibcolombia.net/web/sib/2013-2| publisher=Sistema de informaci\u00f3n sobre Biodiversidad de Colombia| date=2013| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818085623/http://www.sibcolombia.net/web/sib/2013-2| archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> '''v)''' The [[Sinchi Amazonic Institute of Scientific Research]] seeks to encourage the development and diffusion of knowledge, values and technologies on the management of natural resources for ethnic groups in the Amazon. This research should further the use of participatory action research schemes and promoting participation communities.<ref name=Si_Inst>{{cite web| title=Funciones del Instituto| url=http://www.sinchi.org.co/index.php/funciones| publisher=The Sinchi Institute| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820091926/http://www.sinchi.org.co/index.php/funciones| archivedate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n*Since 2010, the Pacific Biodiversity Institute (PBI) seeks \"volunteers to help identify, describe and protect wildland complexes and roadless areas in South America\". The PBI \"are engaged in an ambitious project with our Latin American conservation partners to map all the wildlands in South America, to evaluate their contribution to global biodiversity and to share and disseminate this information.\"<ref name=PBI>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science Volunteers needed for mapping South American Wetlands|url=http://www.pacificbio.org/helpout/volunteer-south-america.html|publisher=Pacific Biodiversity Institute|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827190519/http://www.pacificbio.org/helpout/volunteer-south-america.html|archivedate=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Conferences==\n\nThe first Conference on Public Participation in Scientific Research was held in Portland, Oregon in August 2012.<ref name=\"Rosner2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Rosner |first1=Hillary |title=Data on Wings |journal=Scientific American |date=14 January 2013 |volume=308 |issue=2 |pages=68\u201373 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0213-68 |pmid=23367787 |bibcode=2013SciAm.308b..68R }}</ref> Citizen science is now often a theme at large conferences, such as the annual meeting of the [[American Geophysical Union]].<ref name=AGU_Meeting>{{cite web|title=ED51A. Era of Citizen Science: Intersection of Outreach, Scientific Research and Big Data I Posters|url=http://fallmeeting.agu.org/2013/scientific-program-2/session-search/sessions/ed51a-era-of-citizen-science-intersection-of-outreach-scientific-research-and-big-data-i-posters|publisher=American Geophysical Union|date=13 December 2013|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409001310/http://fallmeeting.agu.org/2013/scientific-program-2/session-search/sessions/ed51a-era-of-citizen-science-intersection-of-outreach-scientific-research-and-big-data-i-posters/|archivedate=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, 2012 and 2014 there were three Citizen Cybersience summits, organised by the [[Citizen Cyberscience Centre]] in [[Geneva]] and [[University College London]].<ref name=CitCyb>{{cite web| title=Citizen Cyberscience Summit (2014 - 2012 - 2010)| url=http://www.citizencyberlab.org/events.html#one| publisher=CERN, unitar, Universite de Geneve| access-date=17 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604171916/http://citizencyberlab.org/events.html#one| archivedate=4 June 2016}}</ref> The 2014 summit was hosted in [[London]] and attracted over 300 participants.<ref name=CitCyb/>\n\nIn January 2015, the [[ETH Z\u00fcrich]] and [[University of Z\u00fcrich]] hosted an international meeting on the \"Challenges and Opportunities in Citizen Science\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsb.ethz.ch/news-and-events/events/citizenscienceworkshop/Program.html|title=Program|work=ethz.ch|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103001056/http://www.imsb.ethz.ch/news-and-events/events/citizenscienceworkshop/Program.html|archivedate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first citizen science conference hosted by the Citizen Science Association was in San Jose, California, in February 2015 in partnership with the AAAS conference.<ref name=CSA_Feb2015>{{cite web|title=Conference 11\u201312 February, San Jose, California, USA|url=http://citizenscienceassociation.org/conference|publisher=Citizen Science Association|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915231307/http://citizenscienceassociation.org/conference/|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The Citizen Science Association conference, CitSci 2017, was held in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], [[Minnesota]], United States, between 17 and 20 May 2017. The conference had more than 600 attendees.<ref name=Conf_2>{{cite web| title=2017 CSA Top Ten Year in Review| url=http://citizenscience.org/2017/12/28/2017-csa-top-ten-year-in-review| publisher=The Citizen Science Association| date=2017| accessdate=16 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229010851/http://citizenscience.org/2017/12/28/2017-csa-top-ten-year-in-review/| archivedate=29 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=CSA_Conf>{{cite web|title=CitSci2017: May 17\u201320th in Saint Paul, Minnesota|url=http://citizenscience.org/2016/07/13/citsci2017-may-17-20th-in-saint-paul-minnesota|publisher=Citizen Science Association|date=13 July 2016|accessdate=1 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017063905/http://citizenscience.org/2016/07/13/citsci2017-may-17-20th-in-saint-paul-minnesota/|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref> The next CitSci is in March 2019 in [[Raleigh]], USA.<ref name=Conf_2/>\n\nThe platform \"\u00d6sterreich forscht\" hosts the annual [[Austria]]n citizen science conference since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizen-science.at/eventarchiv|title=Eventarchiv|website=Citizen Science Platform \"\u00d6sterreich forscht\"|access-date=31 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017004036/http://www.citizen-science.at/eventarchiv|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Columns-list|\n* {{annotated link|Genealogy}}\n* {{annotated link|Independent scientist}}\n* {{annotated link|Independent scholar}}\n* {{annotated link|List of citizen science projects}}\n* {{annotated link|List of distributed computing projects}}\n* {{annotated link|Open science}}\n* {{annotated link|Open-source intelligence}}\n* {{annotated link|Open-Source Lab (book)}}\n* {{annotated link|Outsider art}} (produced by artists that are non-institutionalized, in the same way as citizen scientists)\n* {{annotated link|Public participation (decision making)}}\n* {{annotated link|Reinventing Discovery}}\n* {{annotated link|Popular science}}\n* {{annotated link|Public participation}}\n* {{annotated link|Scientific instrument}}\n* {{annotated link|Virtual volunteering}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite web|website=The Conversation|url=https://theconversation.com/as-heat-strikes-heres-one-way-to-help-fight-disease-carrying-and-nuisance-mosquitoes-128466|title=As heat strikes, here's one way to help fight disease-carrying and nuisance mosquitoes|first1=Cameron|last1=Web|first2=Craig|last2=Williams|first3=Larissa Braz|last3=Sousa|first4=Seamus|last4= Doherty|first5=Stephen Robert|last5=Fricker|date=11 December 2019}} \"The Mozzie Monitors program marks the first time formal mosquito trapping has been combined with citizen science.\" (Australian project)\n*{{cite journal |last1=Franzoni |first1=Chiara |last2=Sauermann |first2=Henry |title=Crowd science: The organization of scientific research in open collaborative projects |journal=Research Policy |date=February 2014 |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201320 |doi=10.1016/j.respol.2013.07.005 |ssrn=2167538 }}\n*Dick Kasperowsik (interviewed by Ulrich Herb): [http://www.heise.de/tp/artikel/49/49243/1.html ''Citizen Science as democratization of science?''] In: telepolis, 2016, 27 August\n*Ridley, Matt. (2012, February 8) [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204369404577206990249077050 \"Following the Crowd to Citizen Science\"].  ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n*Young, Jeffrey R. (2010, May 28). [http://chronicle.com/article/The-Rise-of-Crowd-Science/65707/ \"Crowd Science Reaches New Heights\"], ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]''\n*{{cite journal |last1=Sauermann |first1=Henry |last2=Franzoni |first2=Chiara |title=Crowd science user contribution patterns and their implications |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=20 January 2015 |volume=112 |issue=3 |pages=679\u2013684 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1408907112 |pmid=25561529 |pmc=4311847 |ssrn=2545945 |bibcode=2015PNAS..112..679S }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Bourjon |first1=Philippe |last2=Ducarme |first2=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric |last3=Quod |first3=Jean-Pascal |last4=Sweet |first4=Michael |year=2018 |title=Involving recreational snorkelers in inventory improvement or creation: a case study in the Indian Ocean |journal=Cahiers de Biologie Marine |volume=59 |pages=451\u2013460 |doi=10.21411/CBM.A.B05FC714 }}\n\n== External links ==\n\n===National and regional portals===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!'''Nation or region'''\n!'''Portal'''\n|-\n| Asia\n|[https://citizenscienceasia.mobilize.io/network-groups CitizenScience.Asia], [http://www.citizenscience.asia See Also]\n|-\n| Australia\n| [https://citizenscience.org.au/ Australian Citizen Science Association]\n|-\n| Australia\n| [https://biocollect.ala.org.au/ Australian Citizen Science Project Finder]\n|-\n| Austria\n| [https://www.citizen-science.at/ \u00d6sterreich Forscht]\n|-\n| Belgium (Flanders)\n| [https://www.scivil.be/ Citizen Science Vlaanderen]\n|-\n| Canada\n| [http://science.gc.ca/eic/site/063.nsf/eng/h_97169.html/ Citizen science portal]\n|- \n| Denmark\n| [http://www.citizenscience.dk/ Citizen Science Portalen]\n|-\n| France\n| [http://www.open-sciences-participatives.org/ Open]\n|-\n| Germany\n| [https://www.buergerschaffenwissen.de/en/ B\u00fcrger schaffen Wissen]\n|-\n| Global\n| [https://scistarter.com/ SciStarter] [[SciStarter]]\n|-\n| Global\n| [https://www.zooniverse.org/ Zooniverse: People-powered research] \n|-\n| Ireland\n| [http://www.epa.ie/irelandsenvironment/getinvolved/citizenscience/ Environmental  Protection Agency]\n|-\n| Netherlands and Flanders \n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20190430022015/https://www.iedereenwetenschapper.be/ EOS Wetenschap ]\n|-\n| Scotland\n| [http://www.tcv.org.uk/scotland/discover/citizen-science/ Citizen Science with TCV].\n|-\n| Spain \n| [https://ciencia-ciudadana.es/listado-de-proyectos/ Observatorio De La Ciencia Ciudadana]\n|-\n| Sweden\n| [https://medborgarforskning.se/ Arenas for co-operation through citizen science]\n|-\n| Switzerland\n| [https://www.schweiz-forscht.ch/ Schweiz Forscht]\n|-\n| United Kingdom\n| [https://catalogue.ukeof.org.uk/ UK Environment Observation Framework]\n|-\n| United States\n| [https://www.citizenscience.gov/ USA Government Official Website]\n|}\n\n===Other===\n*[http://med.stanford.edu/ourvoice.html/ Stanford Our Voice Initiative: Citizen Science for Health Equity]\n*[https://www.nasa.gov/solve/index.html NASA Solve: Citizen Science, Challenges and Prizes at NASA.]\n*[http://www.citizensciencecenter.com/ Citizen Science Center]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181223023620/http://geotagx.org/ GeoTag-X] run by [http://www.unitar.org/unosat/ UNITAR-UNOSAT]\n*[http://www.ibercivis.com/ Ibercivis Foundation]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304191919/http://www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/sar_cse-sar_esc/ Search and Rescue Citizen Science Experiment] by [http://www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/index.html National Research Council Canada]\n*[http://birdlife.org.au/projects/atlas-and-birdata/ Atlas]. [[Australia]]'s voice for birds since 1901.\n*[http://www.indigovexpeditions.org/ Indigo V Expeditions]. Dedicated to the advancement of citizen oceanography.\n\n{{Open navbox}}\n{{Science and technology studies|state=collapsed}}\n{{Science and the public|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Citizen Science}}\n[[Category:Citizen science| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Crowdsourcing]]\n[[Category:Human-based computation]]\n[[Category:Open science]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scientific research conducted, in whole or in part, by amateur or nonprofessional scientists}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n'''Citizen science''' ('''CS'''; also known as '''community science''', '''crowd science''', '''crowd-sourced science''', '''civic science''', '''volunteer monitoring''', or '''online citizen science''') is [[scientific research]] conducted, in whole or in part, by [[amateur]] (or nonprofessional) [[scientist]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Gura, Trisha|title=Citizen science: amateur experts|journal=Nature|volume=496|issue=7444|year=2013|pages=259\u2013261|doi=10.1038/nj7444-259a|pmid=23586092}}</ref> Citizen science is sometimes described as \"[[public participation]] in scientific research,\" [[participatory monitoring]], and [[participatory action research]] whose outcomes are often advancements in scientific research, as well as an increase in the public's understanding of science.<ref name=Hand_1>{{Cite journal |last1 = Hand |first1 = E. |title = Citizen science: People power |doi = 10.1038/466685a |journal = Nature |volume = 466 |issue = 7307 |pages = 685\u2013687 |year = 2010 |pmid = 20686547}}</ref><ref name=UTW_1>{{Cite book| title=Using the Web for Science in the Classroom: Online Citizen Science Participation in Teaching and Learning| author1=C. Doyle| author2=R. David| author3=Y.Li| author4=M. Luczak-Roesch| author5=D. Anderson| author6=C.M Pearson| url=https://osf.io/n953p| date=30 June 2019| access-date=30 July 2019| doi=10.1145/3292522.3326022| isbn=978-1-4503-6202-3}}</ref> Based on Alexa rankings<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com|title=Alexa.com}}</ref> [[iNaturalist]] is currently the most popular citizen science website<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/inaturalist.org|title=Alexa.com: inaturalist.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic}}</ref> followed by [[eBird]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/ebird.org|title=Alexa.com: ebird.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic}}</ref> and then [[Zooniverse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/zooniverse.org|title=Alexa.com: zooniverse.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic}}</ref> in second and third place respectively.{{Update-inline|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Scanning the cliffs near Logan Pass for mountain goats (Citizen Science) (4427399123).jpg|thumb|right|Scanning the cliffs near [[Logan Pass]] for mountain goats as part of the [[Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Glacier National Park]] Citizen Science Program]]\n\n== Definition ==\n\nThe term CS has multiple origins, as well as differing concepts.<ref name=\"Re&Po\">{{cite journal|title=Citizen science as seen by scientists: Methodological, epistemological and ethical dimensions|author1=H. Riesch|author2=C. Potter|date=2014|pages=107\u2013120|doi=10.1177/0963662513497324|pmid=23982281|journal=Public Understanding of Science|volume=23|issue=1|url=http://bura.brunel.ac.uk/handle/2438/10337}}</ref> It was first defined independently in the mid-1990s by [[Rick Bonney]] in the United States and [[Alan Irwin (academic)|Alan Irwin]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name=Re&Po/><ref name=\"A.I.\">{{cite book|title=Citizen Science: A Study of People, Expertise and Sustainable Development|last=Irwin|first=Alan|date=1995|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415130103|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=R.Bonney>{{cite report |first1=Rick |last1=Bonney |first2=Heidi |last2=Ballard |first3=Rebecca |last3=Jordan |first4=Ellen |last4=McCallie |first5=Tina |last5=Phillips |first6=Jennifer |last6=Shirk |first7=Candie C. |last7=Wilderman |date=July 2009 |title=Public Participation in Scientific Research: Defining the Field and Assessing Its Potential for Informal Science Education |publisher=Center for Advancement of Informal Science Education |url=http://www.birds.cornell.edu/citscitoolkit/publications/CAISE-PPSR-report-2009.pdf/view }}</ref> Alan Irwin, a British sociologist, defines CS as \"developing concepts of scientific citizenship which foregrounds the necessity of opening up science and science policy processes to the public\".<ref name=Re&Po/> Irwin sought to reclaim two dimensions of the relationship between citizens and science: 1) that science should be responsive to citizens' concerns and needs; and 2) that citizens themselves could produce reliable scientific knowledge.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=The Rightful Place of Science: Citizen Science|last=Cavalier|first=Darlene|last2=Kennedy|first2=Eric|publisher=Consortium for Science, Policy & Outcomes|year=2016|isbn=9780692694831|location=Tempe, AZ|page=54|via=}}</ref> The American ornithologist Rick Bonney, unaware of Irwin's work, defined CS as projects in which nonscientists, such as amateur birdwatchers, voluntarily contributed scientific data. This describes a more limited role for citizens in scientific research than Irwin's conception of the term.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe terms ''citizen science'' and ''citizen scientists'' entered the [[Oxford English Dictionary]] (''OED'') in June 2014.<ref>{{cite dictionary|title=New words list June 2014|url=http://public.oed.com/the-oed-today/recent-updates-to-the-oed/previous%20updates/june-2014-update/new-words-list-june-2014|dictionary=Oxford English Dictionary|accessdate=3 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509083230/http://public.oed.com/the-oed-today/recent-updates-to-the-oed/previous%20updates/june-2014-update/new-words-list-june-2014|archivedate=9 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Zoo_OED>{{cite web|title='Citizen science' added to Oxford English Dictionary|url=https://daily.zooniverse.org/2014/09/16/citizen-science-in-dictionary|publisher=The Daily Zooniverse|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=3 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616165001/https://daily.zooniverse.org/2014/09/16/citizen-science-in-dictionary/|archivedate=16 June 2016}}</ref> \"Citizen science\" is defined as \"scientific work undertaken by members of the general public, often in collaboration with or under the direction of professional scientists and scientific institutions\".<ref name=Zoo_OED/> \"Citizen scientist\" is defined as: (a) \"a scientist whose work is characterized by a sense of responsibility to serve the best interests of the wider community (now rare)\"; or (b) \"a member of the general public who engages in scientific work, often in collaboration with or under the direction of professional scientists and scientific institutions; an amateur scientist\".<ref name=Zoo_OED/> The first use of the term \"citizen scientist\" can be found in the magazine ''[[New Scientist]]'' in an article about [[ufology]] from October 1979.<ref name=Oberg>{{cite magazine|title=The Failure of the 'Science' of Ufology|author=James Oberg|journal=New Scientist|date=11 October 1979|volume=84|issue=1176|pages=102\u2013105}}</ref>\n\nMuki Haklay cites, from a policy report for the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|Wilson Center]] entitled \"Citizen Science and Policy: A European Perspective\", an alternate first use of the term \"citizen science\" by R. Kerson in the magazine ''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' from January 1989.<ref name=1stUse>{{cite web|author=Muki Haklay|title=Citizen Science and Policy: A European Perspective|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/Citizen_Science_Policy_European_Perspective_Haklay.pdf|publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|page=11|date=2015|accessdate=3 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018170921/https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/Citizen_Science_Policy_European_Perspective_Haklay.pdf|archivedate=18 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=Kerson>{{cite magazine|author=R. Kerson|title=Lab for the Environment|journal=MIT Technology Review|date=1989|volume=92|issue=1|pages=11\u201312}}</ref> Quoting from the Wilson Center report: \"The new form of engagement in science received the name 'citizen science'. The first recorded example of the use of the term is from 1989, describing how 225 volunteers across the US collected rain samples to assist the [[National Audubon Society|Audubon Society]] in an acid-rain awareness raising campaign.\"<ref name=1stUse/><ref name=Kerson/>\n\nA ''\"Green Paper on Citizen Science\"'' was published in 2013 by the [[European Commission]]'s Digital Science Unit and Socientize.eu, which included a definition for CS, referring to \"the general public engagement in scientific research activities when citizens actively contribute to science either with their intellectual effort or surrounding knowledge or with their tools and resources. Participants provide experimental data and facilities for researchers, raise new questions and co-create a new scientific culture.\"<ref name=GP_CS_EU>{{cite web|title=Green paper on Citizen Science for Europe: Towards a society of empowered citizens and enhanced research|url=https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/news/green-paper-citizen-science-europe-towards-society-empowered-citizens-and-enhanced-research|publisher=European Commission|date=21 January 2014|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017015723/https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/news/green-paper-citizen-science-europe-towards-society-empowered-citizens-and-enhanced-research|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=EU_GrPa>{{cite web|title=Green paper on Citizen Science|url=http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/dae/document.cfm?doc_id=4122|publisher=Socientize.eu|page=6|date=2013|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226063915/http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/dae/document.cfm?doc_id=4122|archivedate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nCitizen science may be performed by individuals, teams, or networks of volunteers. Citizen scientists often partner with professional scientists to achieve common goals. Large volunteer networks often allow scientists to accomplish tasks that would be too expensive or time-consuming to accomplish through other means.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Silvertown|first=Jonathan|title=A new dawn for citizen science|journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution|volume=24|issue=9|pages=467\u2013471|doi=10.1016/j.tree.2009.03.017|pmid=19586682|year=2009}}</ref>\n\nMany citizen-science projects serve education and outreach goals.<ref>{{Cite book |last1 = Osborn |first1 = D. A. |doi = 10.1061/40761(175)57 |chapter = Monitoring Rocky Intertidal Shorelines: A Role for the Public in Resource Management |title = California and the World Ocean 02 |volume = 175 |page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780784407615/page/57 57] |year = 2002 |isbn = 978-0-7844-0761-5 |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780784407615/page/57 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Brossard |first1 = D. |last2 = Lewenstein |first2 = B. |last3 = Bonney |first3 = R. |doi = 10.1080/09500690500069483 |title = Scientific knowledge and attitude change: The impact of a citizen science project |journal = International Journal of Science Education |volume = 27 |issue = 9 |pages = 1099\u20131121 |year = 2005 |bibcode = 2005IJSEd..27.1099B|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6ef660acdad8b5faf8b5be387292eb45a9a3afc9 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Bauer |first1 = M. W. |last2 = Petkova |first2 = K. |last3 = Boyadjieva |first3 = P. |title = Public Knowledge of and Attitudes to Science: Alternative Measures That May End the \"Science War\" |doi = 10.1177/016224390002500102 |journal = Science, Technology & Human Values |volume = 25 |pages = 30\u201351 |year = 2000 }}</ref> These projects may be designed for a formal classroom environment or an informal education environment such as museums.\n\nCitizen science has evolved over the past four decades. Recent projects place more emphasis on scientifically sound practices and measurable goals for public education.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Bonney |first1 = R. |last2 = Cooper |first2 = C. B. |last3 = Dickinson |first3 = J. |last4 = Kelling |first4 = S. |last5 = Phillips |first5 = T. |last6 = Rosenberg |first6 = K. V. |last7 = Shirk |first7 = J. |doi = 10.1525/bio.2009.59.11.9 |title = Citizen Science: A Developing Tool for Expanding Science Knowledge and Scientific Literacy |journal = BioScience |volume = 59 |issue = 11 |pages = 977\u2013984 |year = 2009 }}</ref> Modern citizen science differs from its historical forms primarily in the access for, and subsequent scale of, public participation; technology is credited as one of the main drivers of the recent explosion of citizen science activity.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Silvertown |first1 = J. |title = A new dawn for citizen science |doi = 10.1016/j.tree.2009.03.017 |journal = Trends in Ecology & Evolution |volume = 24 |issue = 9 |pages = 467\u2013471|year = 2009 |pmid =  19586682}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, the [[Office of Science and Technology Policy]] published a factsheet entitled \"Empowering Students and Others through Citizen Science and Crowdsourcing\".<ref name=OSTP_2015>{{cite web|title=Fact Sheet: Empowering Students and Others through Citizen Science and Crowdsourcing|author=OSTP|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/citizen_science_backgrounder_03-23-15.pdf|publisher=The White House|date=23 March 2015|accessdate=24 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322013634/https://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/citizen_science_backgrounder_march-23.pdf|archivedate=22 March 2016}}</ref> Quoting: \"Citizen science and crowdsourcing projects are powerful tools for providing students with skills needed to excel in science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM). Volunteers in citizen science, for example, gain hands-on experience doing real science, and in many cases take that learning outside of the traditional classroom setting\".<ref name=OSTP_2015/>\n\n[[File:Cascades Butterfly Project Team (8273990532).jpg|thumb|right|Members of the [[Cascade Range|Cascades]] Butterfly Citizen Science Team pictured on Sauk mountain]]\nIn May 2016, a new [[open-access journal]] was started by the [[Citizen Science Association]] along with [[Ubiquity Press]] called ''Citizen Science: Theory and Practice'' (CS:T&P).<ref name=CS:T&P_Web>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science: Theory and Practice|url=http://theoryandpractice.citizenscienceassociation.org|publisher=The Citizen Science Association and Ubiquity Press|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=22 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524120333/http://theoryandpractice.citizenscienceassociation.org/|archivedate=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=CS_T&P>{{cite journal|author1=R. Bonney|author2=C. Cooper|author3=H. Ballard|title=The Theory and Practice of Citizen Science: Launching a New Journal|date=20 May 2016|journal=Citizen Science: Theory and Practice|volume=1|issue=1|page=1|doi=10.5334/cstp.65}}</ref> Quoting from the editorial article titled \"The Theory and Practice of Citizen Science: Launching a New Journal\", \"CS:T&P provides the space to enhance the quality and impact of citizen science efforts by deeply exploring the citizen science concept in all its forms and across disciplines. By examining, critiquing, and sharing findings across a variety of citizen science endeavors, we can dig into the underpinnings and assumptions of citizen science and critically analyze its practice and outcomes.\"<ref name=CS_T&P/>\n\n===Alternative definitions===\n\nOther definitions for citizen science have also been proposed. For example, Bruce Lewenstein of [[Cornell University]]'s [[Communication studies|Communication]] and [[Science and technology studies|S&TS]] departments describes 3 possible definitions:<ref name=\"Lewenstein_2004\">{{cite journal|last=Lewenstein|first=B.|date=8 June 2004|title=What does citizen science accomplish?|url=http://ecommons.library.cornell.edu/handle/1813/37362|url-status=live|journal=|publisher=Cornell University|volume=|pages=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009065556/http://ecommons.library.cornell.edu/handle/1813/37362|archivedate=9 October 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014|via=}}</ref>\n* The participation of nonscientists in the process of gathering data according to specific scientific protocols and in the process of using and interpreting that data.<ref name=Lewenstein_2004/>\n* The engagement of nonscientists in true decision-making about policy issues that have technical or scientific components.<ref name=Lewenstein_2004/>\n* The engagement of research scientists in the democratic and policy process.<ref name=Lewenstein_2004/>\n\nScientists and scholars who have used other definitions include [[Frank N. von Hippel]], [[Stephen Schneider]], [[Neal Francis Lane|Neal Lane]] and [[Jon Beckwith]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Von Hippel, Frank |title=Citizen scientist |publisher=[[American Institute of Physics]] |location=New York |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-88318-709-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Beckwith, Jonathan R. |authorlink=Jon Beckwith|title=Making genes, making waves: a social activist in science |url=https://archive.org/details/makinggenesmakin0000beck |url-access=registration |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-674-00928-8 }}</ref><ref>Neal Lane, \"Remarks\" at Panel Discussion on Future of Federal Funding for Science and Engineering, [[Rutgers University]], 8 April 1996. [https://www.nsf.gov/news/speeches/lane/slrtgrs.htm Steve Schneider remarks at AAAS meeting, February 1997] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929095756/https://www.nsf.gov/news/speeches/lane/slrtgrs.htm |date=29 September 2007 }}; see here {{cite web |url=http://news-service.stanford.edu/pr/97/970210schneider.html |title=Schneider offers three questions to make a citizen-scientist (2/97) |accessdate=18 August 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609092054/http://news-service.stanford.edu/pr/97/970210schneider.html |archivedate=9 June 2007 }}</ref> Other alternative terminologies proposed are \"civic science\" and \"civic scientist\".<ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Clark |first1 = F. |last2 = Illman |first2 = D. L. |doi = 10.1177/1075547001023001002 |title = Dimensions of Civic Science: Introductory Essay |journal = Science Communication |volume = 23 |pages = 5\u201327 |year = 2001 }}</ref>\n\nFurther, Muki Haklay offers an overview of the typologies of the level of citizen participation in citizen science, which range from \"crowdsourcing\" (level 1), where the citizen acts as a sensor, to \"distributed intelligence\" (level 2), where the citizen acts as a basic interpreter, to \"participatory science\", where citizens contribute to problem definition and data collection (level 3), to \"extreme citizen science\", which involves collaboration between the citizen and scientists in problem definition, collection and data analysis.<ref>Haklay, Muki (2012) in Citizen Science and Volunteered Geographic Information: Overview and Typology of Participation. Crowdsourcing Geographic Knowledge. 2013, pp. 105\u2013122.</ref>\n\nA 2014 [[Mashable]] article defines a citizen scientist as: \"Anybody who voluntarily contributes his or her time and resources toward scientific research in partnership with professional scientists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2014/05/26/citizen-science/|title=What Is Citizen Science, and How Can You Get Involved?|author=Eric Larson|date=26 May 2014|work=Mashable|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110231048/http://mashable.com/2014/05/26/citizen-science/|archivedate=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the [[Australian Citizen Science Association]] released their definition which states \"Citizen science involves public participation and collaboration in scientific research with the aim to increase scientific knowledge.\"<ref name=ACSA_1>{{cite web| title=What is Citizen Science?| url=https://citizenscience.org.au/who-we-are| publisher=Australian Citizen Science Association| access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=ACSA_2>{{cite web| title=Discover Another Side of Scientific Research| url=https://citizenscience.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Australian-Citizen-Science-Association-brochure.pdf| publisher=Australian Citizen Science Association| access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the book \"Analyzing the Role of Citizen Science in Modern Research\" defined citizen science as \"work undertaken by civic educators together with citizen communities to advance science, foster a broad scientific mentality, and/or encourage democratic engagement, which allows society to deal rationally with complex modern problems\".<ref>{{cite book| title=Analyzing the role of citizen science in modern research|author=Ceccaroni, L., & Piera, J. (Eds.)|date=2016| url=https://www.igi-global.com/book/analyzing-role-citizen-science-modern/154745| publisher=IGI Global| access-date=27 September 2018|isbn=9781522509622}}</ref>\n\n===Related fields===\n\nIn a [[Smart City]] era, Citizen Science relays on various web-based tools (eg.[[Web mapping|WebGIS)]] and becomes Cyber Citizen Science.<ref name=WebGIS_1>{{cite journal| title=Citizen science and WebGIS for outdoor advertisement visual pollution assessment| author1=S. Chmielewski| author2=M. Samulowska| author3=M. Lupa| author4=B. Zagajewski| journal=Computers Environment and Urban Systems| volume=67| pages=97\u2013109| doi=10.1016/j.compenvurbsys.2017.09.001| year=2018}}</ref> Some projects, such as [[SETI@home]], use the Internet to take advantage of [[distributed computing]]. These projects are generally passive. Computation tasks are performed by volunteers' computers and require little involvement beyond initial setup. There is disagreement as to whether these projects should be classified as citizen science.\n\nThe astrophysicist and [[Galaxy Zoo]] co-founder [[Kevin Schawinski]] stated: \"We prefer to call this [Galaxy Zoo] citizen science because it's a better description of what you're doing; you're a regular citizen but you're doing science. Crowd sourcing sounds a bit like, well, you're just a member of the crowd and you're not; you're our collaborator. You're pro-actively involved in the process of science by participating.\"<ref name=AnthonyWilliams>{{cite web|title=Crowdsourcing versus citizen science|author=A. Williams|url=http://anthonydwilliams.com/2009/02/09/crowdsourcing-versus-citizen-science|publisher=Anthony D. Williams|date=9 February 2009|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915231600/http://anthonydwilliams.com/2009/02/09/crowdsourcing-versus-citizen-science/|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nCompared to SETI@home, \"Galaxy Zoo volunteers do real work. They're not just passively running something on their computer and hoping that they'll be the first person to find aliens. They have a stake in science that comes out of it, which means that they are now interested in what we do with it, and what we find.\"<ref name=AnthonyWilliams/>\n\nCitizen policy may be another result of citizen science initiatives. Bethany Brookshire (pen name SciCurious) writes: \"If citizens are going to live with the benefits or potential consequences of science (as the vast majority of them will), it's incredibly important to make sure that they are not only well informed about changes and advances in science and technology, but that they also ... are able to ... influence the science policy decisions that could impact their lives.\"<ref name=SciCur>{{cite magazine|title=Citizen Science, Citizen Policy|author=SciCurious|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/scicurious-brain/citizen-science-citizen-policy/|magazine=Scientific American|date=7 January 2013|accessdate=23 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423064500/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/scicurious-brain/citizen-science-citizen-policy/|archivedate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits and limitations===\n\nCitizen involvement in scientific projects has become a means of encouraging curiosity and greater understanding of science whilst providing an unprecedented engagement between professional scientists and the general public.<ref name=UTW_1/> In a research report published by the [[National Park Service]] in 2008, Brett Amy Thelen and Rachel K. Thiet mention the following concerns, previously reported in the literature, about the validity of volunteer-generated data:<ref name=Cape_Cod_CS>{{cite journal |title=Cultivating connection: Incorporating meaningful citizen science into Cape Cod National Seashore's estuarine research and monitoring programs |last1=Thelen |first1=Brett Amy |last2=Thiet |first2=Rachel K. |journal=Park Science |volume=25 |issue=1 |year=2008 |citeseerx=10.1.1.692.656 }} </ref>\n* Some projects may not be suitable for volunteers, for instance, when they use complex research methods or require a lot of (often repetitive) work.<ref name=Cape_Cod_CS/>\n* If volunteers lack proper training in research and monitoring protocols, they are at risk of introducing bias into the data.<ref name=Cape_Cod_CS/>\n\nThe question of data accuracy, in particular, remains open.<ref name=\"Fr\u00edas 2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Fr\u00edas |first1=O. |last2=Bautista |first2=L. M. |last3=D\u00e9nes |first3=F. V.  |last4=Cuevas |first4=J. A. |last5= Mart\u00ednez |first5=F. |last6=Blanco |first6=G. |year=2018 |title=Influence of habitat suitability and sex-related detectability on density and population size estimates of habitat-specialist warblers |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=13 |issue=7 |page=020148 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0201482|pmid=30059562 |pmc=6066240 |bibcode=2018PLoSO..1301482F }}</ref> John Losey, who created the [[Lost Ladybug Project|Lost Ladybug]] citizen science project, has argued that the cost-effectiveness of citizen science data can outweigh data quality issues, if properly managed.<ref name=LadyBeatles>{{cite journal|author1=M. M. Gardiner |author2=L. L. Allee |author3=P. M. J. Brown |author4=J. E. Losey |author5=H. E. Roy |author6=R. Rice Smyth |title=Lessons from lady beetles: accuracy of monitoring data from US and UK citizen-science programs|journal=[[Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment]]|date=November 2012|volume=10|issue=9 |doi=10.1890/110185 |pages=471\u2013476|url=http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/id/eprint/20992/1/N020992JA.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, authors M. Kosmala, A. Wiggins, A. Swanson and B. Simmons published a study in the journal [[Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment]] called \"Assessing Data Quality in Citizen Science\".<ref name=ADQ>{{cite journal| author1=Margaret Kosmala| author2=Andrea Wiggins| author3=Alexandra Swanson| author4=Brooke Simmons| title=Assessing Data Quality in Citizen Science| journal=[[Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment]]| volume=14| issue=10| pages=551\u2013560| date=1 December 2016| doi=10.1002/fee.1436| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ee013b1477e8f81cb5c66a9a93a342281f740042}}</ref> The abstract describes how ecological and environmental CS projects have enormous potential to advance science. Also, CS projects can influence policy and guide resource management by producing [[dataset]]s that are otherwise infeasible to generate.<ref name=ADQ/> In the section \"In a Nutshell\" (pg3), four condensed conclusions are stated. They are:<ref name=ADQ/>\n\n{{quote frame|\n# Datasets produced by volunteer CSs can have reliably high quality, on par with those produced by professionals.\n# Individual volunteer accuracy varies, depending on task difficulty and volunteer experience. Multiple methods exist for boosting accuracy to required levels for a given project.\n# Most types of [[bias]] found in CS datasets are also found in professionally produced datasets and can be accommodated using existing statistical tools.\n# Reviewers of CS projects should look for iterated project design, standardization and appropriateness of volunteer protocols and data analyses, capture of [[metadata]], and accuracy assessment.\n}}\n\nThey conclude that as CS continues to grow and mature, a key metric of project success they expect to see will be a growing awareness of data quality. They also conclude that CS will emerge as a general tool helping \"to collect otherwise unobtainable high-quality data in support of policy and resource management, conservation monitoring, and basic science.\"<ref name=ADQ/>\n\nA study of Canadian lepidoptera datasets published in 2018 compared the use of a professionally curated dataset of butterfly specimen records with four years of data from a CS program, [[eButterfly]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Semeniuk |first1=Ivan |title=The butterfly effect: How Canadians and their smartphones are helping scientists map species diversity |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/technology/science/article-the-butterfly-effect-how-canadians-and-their-smartphones-are-helping/ |accessdate=13 October 2018 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=7 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013040152/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/technology/science/article-the-butterfly-effect-how-canadians-and-their-smartphones-are-helping/ |archivedate=13 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Soroye |first1=Peter |last2=Ahmed |first2=Najeeba |last3=Kerr |first3=Jeremy T. |title=Opportunistic citizen science data transform understanding of species distributions, phenology, and diversity gradients for global change research |journal=Global Change Biology |volume=24 |issue=11 |pages=5281\u20135291 |date=3 July 2018 |doi=10.1111/gcb.14358 |pmid=29920854 |bibcode=2018GCBio..24.5281S }}</ref> The eButterfly dataset was used as it was determined to be of high quality because of the expert vetting process used on the site, and there existed a historic dataset covering the same geographic area consisting of specimen data, much of it institutional.  The authors note that, in this case, CS data provides both novel and complementary information to the specimen data. Five new species were reported from the CS data, and geographic distribution information was improved for over 80% of species in the combined dataset when CS data was included.\n\n====Law====\n{{main|Wyoming Senate Files 12 and 80 2015 'Trespassing To Collect Data'}}\nIn March 2015, the state of [[Wyoming]] passed new laws (Senate Files 12 and 80) clarifying that trespassing laws applied even if the trespasser's intention was to gather data to further a U.S. government science program.<ref name=CourthouseNewsService>{{cite web|author=Emma Gannon|title=Wyoming Criminalizes Citizen Science|url=http://www.courthousenews.com/2015/05/18/wyoming-criminalizes-citizen-science.htm|publisher=Courthouse News Service|date=18 May 2015|accessdate=29 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209050810/http://www.courthousenews.com/2015/05/18/wyoming-criminalizes-citizen-science.htm|archivedate=9 February 2016}}</ref> This hampered some CS researchers who were collecting data while on other people's land.\n\n==Ethics==\n\nVarious studies have been published that explore the [[ethics]] of CS, including issues such as [[intellectual property]] and project design.(e.g.<ref name=Re&Po/><ref name=Resnik_2015>{{cite journal|title=A framework for addressing ethical issues in citizen science|author1=D. B. Resnik|author2=K. C. Elliot|author3=A. K. Miller|journal=Environmental Science & Policy|volume=54|pages=475\u2013481|date=December 2015|doi=10.1016/j.envsci.2015.05.008|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1258927}}</ref><ref name=Bowser_2015>{{cite journal|title=Privacy in Participatory Research: Advancing Policy to support Human Computation|author1=A. E. Bowser|author2=A. Wiggins|journal=Human Computation|volume=2|issue=1|date=2015|pages=19\u201344|doi=10.15346/hc.v2i1.3}}</ref><ref name=Hoffman_2014>{{cite journal|title=Citizen Science: The Law and Ethics of Public Access to Medical Big Data|author=S. Hoffman|journal=Berkeley Technology Law Journal|date=September 2014|volume=Case Legal Studies Research Paper No. 2014-21}}</ref><ref name=Scassa_2015>{{cite web|title=Managing Intellectual Property Rights in Citizen Science: A Guide for Researchers and Citizen Scientists|author1=T. Scassa|author2=Chung H.|url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/managing_intellectual_property_rights_citizen_science_scassa_chung.pdf|publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars|date=2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705153453/https://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/managing_intellectual_property_rights_citizen_science_scassa_chung.pdf|archivedate=5 July 2017}}</ref>) The [[Citizen Science Association|Citizen Science Association (CSA)]], based at the [[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]], and the [[European Citizen Science Association| European Citizen Science Association (ECSA)]], based in the [[Museum f\u00fcr Naturkunde]] in Berlin, have working groups on ethics and principles.<ref name=CSA_1>{{cite web|title=CSA Working Group on Ethics|url=http://citizenscience.org/association/about/working-groups/ethics-working-group/|publisher=Citizen Science Association|accessdate=24 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825062443/http://citizenscience.org/association/about/working-groups/ethics-working-group/|archivedate=25 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=ECSA_2>{{cite web|title=ECSA Principles & Standards in Citizen Science: Sharing Best Practice & Building Capacity|url=http://www.ecsa.citizen-science.net/taxonomy/term/205|publisher=ECSA|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818072003/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/taxonomy/term/205|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the European Citizen Science Association (ECSA) published its ''Ten Principles of Citizen Science'', which have been developed by the \"Sharing best practice and building capacity\" working group of the ECSA, led by the [[Natural History Museum, London]] with input from many members of the association.<ref name=ECSA_10>{{cite web|author=European Citizen Science Association|title=10 Principles of Citizen Science (English)|url=http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/sites/default/files/ecsa_ten_principles_of_citizen_science.pdf|publisher=ECSA|date=September 2015|accessdate=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822040236/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/sites/default/files/ecsa_ten_principles_of_citizen_science.pdf|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=ECSA_Docs>{{cite web|title=ECSA Documents|url=http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/documents|publisher=ECSA|date=September 2015|access-date=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822042534/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/documents|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n{{quote frame|\n# Citizen science projects actively involve citizens in scientific endeavour that generates new knowledge or understanding. Citizens may act as contributors, collaborators, or as project leader and have a meaningful role in the project.\n# Citizen science projects have a genuine science outcome. For example, answering a research question or informing conservation action, management decisions or environmental policy.\n# Both the professional scientists and the citizen scientists benefit from taking part. Benefits may include the publication of research outputs, learning opportunities, personal enjoyment, social benefits, satisfaction through contributing to scientific evidence e.g. to address local, national and international issues, and through that, the potential to influence policy.\n# Citizen scientists may, if they wish, participate in multiple stages of the scientific process. This may include developing the research question, designing the method, gathering and analysing data, and communicating the results.\n# Citizen scientists receive feedback from the project. For example, how their data are being used and what the research, policy or societal outcomes are.\n# Citizen science is considered a research approach like any other, with limitations and biases that should be considered and controlled for. However unlike traditional research approaches, citizen science provides opportunity for greater public engagement and democratisation of science.\n# Citizen science project data and meta-data are made publicly available and where possible, results are published in an open access format. [[Data sharing]] may occur during or after the project, unless there are security or privacy concerns that prevent this.\n# Citizen scientists are acknowledged in project results and publications.\n# Citizen science programmes are evaluated for their scientific output, data quality, participant experience and wider societal or policy impact.\n# The leaders of citizen science projects take into consideration legal and ethical issues surrounding copyright, intellectual property, data sharing agreements, confidentiality, attribution, and the environmental impact of any activities.\n}}\n\nThe medical ethics of internet crowdsourcing has been questioned by Graber & Graber in the ''[[Journal of Medical Ethics]]''.<ref name=Graber_1>{{cite journal|author1=M. A. Graber |author2=A. Graber |title=Internet-based crowdsourcing and research ethics:the case for IRB review|journal=Journal of Medical Ethics|date=30 November 2012|doi=10.1136/medethics-2012-100798|pmid=23204319 |volume=39|issue=2 |pages=115\u2013118}}</ref> In particular, they analyse the effect of games and the crowdsourcing project [[Foldit]]. They conclude: \"games can have possible adverse effects, and that they manipulate the user into participation\".\n\nIn March 2019 the online journal ''Citizen Science: Theory and Practice'' launched a collection of articles\non the theme of Ethical Issues in Citizen Science.<ref name=CSTP_2>{{cite journal| title=Ethical Issues in Citizen Science| url=https://theoryandpractice.citizenscienceassociation.org/collections/special/ethical-issues-in-citizen-science| journal=Citizen Science: Theory and Practice| publisher=[[Ubiquity Press]]| date=7 March 2019| access-date=12 March 2019}}</ref> The articles are introduced with (quoting): \"Citizen science can challenge existing ethical norms because it falls outside of customary methods of ensuring that research is conducted ethically. What ethical issues arise when engaging the public in research? How have these issues been addressed, and how should they be addressed in the future?\"<ref name=CSTP_2/>\n\nIn June 2019, ''[[East Asian Science, Technology and Society: An International Journal]]'' (EASTS) published an issue titled \"Citizen Science: Practices and Problems\" which contains 15 articles/studies on CS, including many relevant subjects of which ethics is one.<ref name=EASTS_1>{{cite web |title=East Asian Science, Technology and Society: an International Journal-Volume 13, Number 2, June 2019 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/issue/40521 |website=Project MUSE }}</ref> Quoting from the introduction Citizen, Science, and Citizen Science: \"The term citizen science has become very popular among scholars as well as the general public, and, given its growing presence in East Asia, it is perhaps not a moment too soon to have a special issue of EASTS on the topic.\"<ref name=EASTS_2>{{cite journal| title=Citizen, Science, and Citizen Science| journal=East Asian Science, Technology and Society| author1=Fa-ti Fan| author2=Shun-Ling Chen| volume=13| issue=2| pages=181\u2013193| date=1 June 2019| doi=10.1215/18752160-7542643}}</ref>\n\n===Economic worth===\n\nIn the research paper \"Can citizen science enhance public understanding of science?\" by Bonney et al. 2016,<ref name=Bonney&Phill>{{cite journal|title=Can citizen science enhance public understanding of science?|author1=R. Bonney|author2=T. B. Phillips|author3=H. L. Ballard|author4=J. W. Enck|journal=Public Understanding of Science|volume=25|issue=1|pages=2\u201316|doi=10.1177/0963662515607406|pmid=26445860|date=1 January 2016}}</ref> statistics which analyse the economic worth of citizen science are used, drawn from two papers: '''i)'''Sauermann and Franzoni 2015,<ref name=Sau&Fran>{{cite journal|title=Crowd science user contribution patterns and their implications|author1=Henry Sauermann|author2=Chiara Franzoni| journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America| volume=112|issue=3|pages=679\u2013684|doi=10.1073/pnas.1408907112|date=20 January 2015|pmid=25561529|pmc=4311847|bibcode=2015PNAS..112..679S}}</ref> and\n'''ii)'''Theobald et al. 2015.<ref name=Theo&Ett>{{cite journal|title=Global change and local solutions: Tapping the unrealized potential of citizen science for biodiversity research|author1=J. Theobald|author2=A. K. Ettinger|author3=H. K. Burgess|author4=L. B. DeBey|author5=N. R. Schmidt|author6=H. E. Froehlich|author7=C. Wagner|author8=J. HilleRisLambers|author9=J. Tewksbury|author10=M. A. Harsch|author11=J. K. Parrish|journal=Biological Conservation|volume=181|issue=2015|pages=236\u2013244|date=1 January 2015|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2014.10.021}}</ref> In \"Crowd science user contribution patterns and their implications\" by Sauermann and Franzoni (2015), seven projects from the Zooniverse web portal are used to estimate the monetary value of the CS that had taken place. The 7 projects are: Solar Stormwatch, Galaxy Zoo Supernovae, Galaxy Zoo Hubble, Moon Zoo, Old Weather, The Milky Way Project and Planet Hunters.<ref name=Sau&Fran/> Using data from 180 days in 2010, they find a total of 100,386 users participated, contributing 129,540 hours of unpaid work.<ref name=Sau&Fran/> Estimating at a rate of $12 an hour (an undergraduate research assistant's basic wage), the total contributions amount to $1,554,474, an average of $222,068 per project.<ref name=Sau&Fran/> The range over the 7 projects was from $22,717 to $654,130.<ref name=Sau&Fran/>\n\nIn \"Global change and local solutions: Tapping the unrealized potential of citizen science for biodiversity research\" by Theobald et al. 2015, the authors surveyed 388 unique biodiversity-based projects.<ref name=Theo&Ett/> Quoting: \"We estimate that between 1.36 million and 2.28 million people volunteer annually in the 388 projects we surveyed, though variation is great\" and that \"the range of in-kind contribution of the volunteerism in our 388 citizen science projects as between $667 million to $2.5 billion annually.\"<ref name=Theo&Ett/>\n\nWorldwide participation in citizen science continues to grow. A list of the top five citizen science communities compiled by [[Marc Kuchner]] and Kristen Erickson in July 2018 shows a total of 3.75 million participants, although there is likely substantial overlap between the communities.\n\n===Education===\n\nThere have been studies published which examine the place of CS within education.(e.g.<ref name=UTW_1/><ref name=CSYE>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science and Youth Education| author1=R. Bonney| author2=T.B. Phillips| author3=J. Enck| author4=J. Shirk| author5=N. Trautmann| publisher=Center for Advancement of Informal Science Education| url=http://www.informalscience.org/citizen-science-and-youth-education| date=1 January 2015| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122072021/http://www.informalscience.org/citizen-science-and-youth-education| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=EERA>{{cite web| title=School-based Citizen Science and its Contribution to Environmental Education Outcomes: a Literature Review| author=A. Ruck| publisher=European Educational Research Association| url=http://www.eera-ecer.de/ecer-programmes/print/conference/21/contribution/38023Z| date=25 August 2016| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122072026/http://www.eera-ecer.de/ecer-programmes/print/conference/21/contribution/38023Z| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref>) Teaching aids can include books and activity or lesson plans.(e.g.<ref name=Zoo_Teach>{{cite web| title=Hands-on Activity: Citizen Science with Zooniverse| author1=P. Cain| author2=Y.Glass| author3=J. Nider| author4=S. Prakash| author5=L. Rice| url=https://www.teachengineering.org/activities/view/ksu_zooniverse_activity1| date=2012| publisher=Kansas State University| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122071934/https://www.teachengineering.org/activities/view/ksu_zooniverse_activity1| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=CS_lessons>{{cite book| title=Citizen Science: 15 Lessons That Bring Biology to Life| author1=N. Trautmann| author2=J. Fee| author3=T.M. Tomasek| author4=N.L.R. Bergey| publisher=National Science Teachers Association| date=28 February 2014| isbn=9781936959082}}</ref><ref name=CAS_Toolkit>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science Toolkit| publisher=California Academy of Sciences| url=https://www.calacademy.org/educators/citizen-science-toolkit| date=2015| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122071724/https://www.calacademy.org/educators/citizen-science-toolkit| archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=NASA_LP>{{cite web| title=Lesson Plans \u2013 Citizen Science| url=https://mynasadata.larc.nasa.gov/lesson-plans/lesson-plans-citizen-science| publisher=[[NASA]]| date=7 November 2017| access-date=21 January 2018| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710192555/https://mynasadata.larc.nasa.gov/lesson-plans/lesson-plans-citizen-science/| archivedate=10 July 2017}}</ref>). Some examples of studies are:\n\nFrom the Second International Handbook of Science Education, a chapter entitled: \"Citizen Science, Ecojustice, and Science Education: Rethinking an Education from Nowhere\" by Mueller and Tippins (2011), acknowledges in the abstract that: \"There is an emerging emphasis in science education on engaging youth in citizen science.\" The authors also ask: \"whether citizen science goes further with respect to citizen development.\"<ref name=CS_Eco/> The abstract ends by stating that the \"chapter takes account of the ways educators will collaborate with members of the community to effectively guide decisions, which offers promise for sharing a responsibility for democratizing science with others.\"<ref name=CS_Eco>{{cite book| title=Citizen Science, Ecojustice, and Science Education: Rethinking an Education from Nowhere| author1=M.P. Mueller| author2=D.J. Tippins| publisher=Springer International Handbooks of Education| volume=24|date=23 November 2011| doi=10.1007/978-1-4020-9041-7_58| isbn=978-1-4020-9040-0}}</ref>\n\nFrom the journal Democracy and Education, an article entitled: \"Lessons Learned from Citizen Science in the Classroom\" by authors Gray, Nicosia and Jordan (GNJ) (2012) give a response to a study by Mueller, Tippins and Bryan (MTB) called \"The Future of Citizen Science\".<ref name=DemEdu>{{cite journal| title=Lessons Learned from Citizen Science in the Classroom| author1=S.A. Gray| author2=K. Nicosia| author3=R.C. Jordan| journal=Democracy and Education| url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/254634887| volume=20| number=2| date=August 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072120/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/254634887_Lessons_Learned_from_Citizen_Science_in_the_Classroom_A_Response_to_The_Future_of_Citizen_Science| archivedate=23 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=FCS>{{cite journal| title=The Future of Citizen Science| author1=M.P. Mueller| author2=D. Tippins| author3=L.A. Bryan| journal=Democracy and Education| volume=20| issue=1| date=2012}}</ref> GNJ begins by stating in the abstract that the study The Future of Citizen Science: \"provides an important theoretical perspective about the future of \ndemocratized science and [[K\u201312|K12]] education.\" But GRB state: \"However, the authors (MTB) fail to adequately address the existing \nbarriers and constraints to moving community-based science into the classroom.\" They end the abstract by arguing: \"that the resource constraints of scientists, teachers, and students likely pose problems to moving true democratized science into the classroom.\"<ref name=DemEdu/>\n\nIn 2014, a study was published called \"Citizen Science and Lifelong Learning\" by R. Edwards in the journal ''[[Studies in the Education of Adults]]''.<ref name=CSLL>{{cite journal |last1=Edwards |first1=Richard |title=Citizen science and lifelong learning |journal=Studies in the Education of Adults |date=21 January 2016 |volume=46 |issue=2 |pages=132\u2013144 |doi=10.1080/02660830.2014.11661662 }}</ref> Edwards begins by writing in the abstract that CS projects have expanded over recent years and engaged CSs and professionals in diverse ways. He continues: \"Yet there has been little educational exploration of such projects to date.\"<ref name=CSLL/> He describes that \"there has been limited exploration of the educational backgrounds of adult contributors to citizen science\". Edwards explains that CS contributors are referred to as volunteers, citizens or as amateurs. He ends the abstract: \"The article will explore the nature and significance of these different characterisations and also suggest possibilities for further research.\"<ref name=CSLL/>\n\nIn the journal ''[[Microbiology and Biology Education]]'' a study was published by Shah and Martinez (2015) called \"Current Approaches in Implementing Citizen Science in the Classroom\".<ref name=CurrApp>{{cite journal| title=Current Approaches in Implementing Citizen Science in the Classroom| author1=H.R. Shah| author2=L.R. Martinez| journal=Microbiology & Biology Education| date=March 2015| volume=17| issue=1| doi=10.1128/jmbe.v17i1.1032| pmid=27047583| pages=17\u201322| pmc=4798802}}</ref> They begin by writing in the abstract that CS is a partnership between inexperienced amateurs and trained scientists. The authors continue: \"With recent studies showing a weakening in scientific competency of American students, incorporating citizen science initiatives in the curriculum provides a means to address deficiencies\".<ref name=CurrApp/> They argue that combining traditional and innovative methods can help provide a practical experience of science. The abstract ends: \"Citizen science can be used to emphasize the recognition and use of systematic approaches to solve problems affecting the community.\"<ref name=CurrApp/>\n\nIn November 2017, authors Mitchell, Triska and Liberatore published a study in ''[[PLOS ONE]]'' titled \"Benefits and Challenges of Incorporating Citizen Science into University Education\".<ref name=Bene&Chall>{{cite journal| title=Benefits and Challenges of Incorporating Citizen Science into University Education| author1=N. Mitchell| author2=M. Triska| author3=A. Liberatore| author4=L. Ashcroft| author5=R. Weatherill| author6=N. Longnecker| journal= PLOS ONE| date=1 November 2017| doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0186285| pmid=29091933| volume=12| issue=11| page=e0186285| bibcode=2017PLoSO..1286285M| pmc=5665417}}</ref> The authors begin by stating in the abstract that CSs contribute data with the expectation that it will be used. It reports that CS has been used for first year university students as a means to experience research. They continue: \"Surveys of more than 1500 students showed that their environmental engagement increased significantly after participating in data collection and data analysis.\"<ref name=Bene&Chall/> However, only a third of students agreed that data collected by CSs was reliable. A positive outcome of this was that the students were more careful of their own research. The abstract ends: \"If true for citizen scientists in general, enabling participants as well as scientists to analyse data could enhance data quality, and so address a key constraint of broad-scale citizen science programs.\"<ref name=Bene&Chall/>\n\n== History ==\n\n\"Citizen science\" is a fairly new term but an old practice. Prior to the 20th century, science was often the pursuit of [[gentleman scientist]]s, amateur or self-funded researchers such as Sir [[Isaac Newton]], [[Benjamin Franklin]], and [[Charles Darwin]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Silvertown |first1=Jonathan |title=A new dawn for citizen science |journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution |date=September 2009 |volume=24 |issue=9 |pages=467\u2013471 |doi=10.1016/j.tree.2009.03.017 |pmid=19586682 }}</ref> By the mid-20th century, however, science was dominated by researchers employed by universities and government research laboratories. By the 1970s, this transformation was being called into question. Philosopher [[Paul Feyerabend]] called for a \"democratization of science\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Paul Feyerabend |author-link=Paul Feyerabend |title=Science in a free society |publisher=[[New Left Books]]|location=London |year=1982 |isbn=978-0-86091-753-3 }}{{pn|date=November 2019}}</ref> Biochemist [[Erwin Chargaff]] advocated a return to science by nature-loving amateurs in the tradition of [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes|Descartes]], Newton, [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz|Leibniz]], [[Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon|Buffon]], and [[Charles Darwin|Darwin]]\u2014science dominated by \"amateurship instead of money-biased technical bureaucrats\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Erwin Chargaff |author-link=Erwin Chargaff |title=Heraclitean fire: sketches from a life before nature |publisher=[[Rockefeller University Press]] |location=New York |year=1978 |isbn=978-0-87470-029-9 }}{{pn|date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\nA study from 2016 indicates that the largest impact of citizen science is in research on biology, conservation and ecology, and is utilized mainly as a methodology of collecting and classifying data.<ref name=kullberg>{{cite journal |last1=Kullenberg |first1=Christopher |last2=Kasperowski |first2=Dick |last3=Dorta-Gonz\u00e1lez |first3=Pablo |title=What Is Citizen Science? \u2013 A Scientometric Meta-Analysis |journal=PLOS ONE |date=14 January 2016 |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=e0147152 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147152 |pmid=26766577 |pmc=4713078 |bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147152K }}</ref>\n\n===Amateur astronomy===\n{{main|Amateur astronomy}}\n[[File:Telescope trailer 22.jpg|right|thumb|250px|upright|Amateur astronomers can build their own equipment and can hold star parties and gatherings, such as [[Stellafane]].]]\n\n[[Astronomy]] has long been a field where amateurs have contributed throughout time, all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mims III |first=Forrest M. |authorlink=Forrest Mims |title=Amateur Science\u2014Strong Tradition, Bright Future |journal=Science |year=1999 |volume=284 |issue=5411 |pages=55\u201356 |doi=10.1126/science.284.5411.55 |quote=Astronomy has traditionally been among the most fertile fields for serious amateurs [...] |bibcode = 1999Sci...284...55M}}</ref>\n\nCollectively, amateur astronomers observe a variety of celestial objects and phenomena sometimes with [[Amateur telescope making|equipment that they build themselves]]. Common targets of amateur astronomers include the Moon, planets, stars, comets, meteor showers, and a variety of [[deep-sky object]]s such as star clusters, galaxies, and nebulae. Observations of comets and stars are also used to measure the local level of [[skyglow|artificial skyglow]].<ref name=\"GaN\">{{cite journal |last1=Kyba |first1=Christopher C. M. |last2=Wagner |first2=Janna M. |last3=Kuechly |first3=Helga U. |last4=Walker |first4=Constance E. |last5=Elvidge |first5=Christopher D. |last6=Falchi |first6=Fabio |last7=Ruhtz |first7=Thomas |last8=Fischer |first8=J\u00fcrgen |last9=H\u00f6lker |first9=Franz |title=Citizen Science Provides Valuable Data for Monitoring Global Night Sky Luminance |journal=Scientific Reports |date=16 May 2013 |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=1835 |doi=10.1038/srep01835 |pmid=23677222 |bibcode=2013NatSR...3E1835K |pmc=3655480 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=\u015aci\u0119\u017cor |first1=T. |title=A new astronomical method for determining the brightness of the night sky and its application to study long-term changes in the level of light pollution |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |date=11 October 2013 |volume=435 |issue=1 |pages=303\u2013310 |doi=10.1093/mnras/stt1297 |bibcode=2013MNRAS.435..303S }}</ref> One branch of amateur astronomy, amateur [[astrophotography]], involves the taking of photos of the night sky. Many amateurs like to specialize in the observation of particular objects, types of objects, or types of events that interest them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amsmeteors.org/|title = The Americal Meteor Society|accessdate =24 August 2006|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060822135040/http://www.amsmeteors.org/|archivedate= 22 August 2006 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jerry|last=Lodriguss|url=http://www.astropix.com/|title = Catching the Light: Astrophotography|accessdate =24 August 2006|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060901185541/http://www.astropix.com/|archivedate= 1 September 2006 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Association of Variable Star Observers]] has gathered data on variable stars for educational and professional analysis since 1911 and promotes participation beyond its membership on its Citizen Sky website.<ref name=CSP>{{cite web |title=The Origins and Future of the Citizen Sky Project |url=https://www.aavso.org/apps/jaavso/article/2864/ |website=AAVSO }}</ref>\n\n===Butterfly counts===\n{{main|Butterfly count}}\nButterfly counts have a long tradition of involving individuals in the study of butterflies' range and their relative abundance. Two long-running programs are the UK Butterfly Monitoring Scheme (started in 1976) and the [[North American Butterfly Association]]'s Butterfly Count Program (started in 1975).<ref name=UKBMS>{{cite web|title=The UK Butterfly Monitoring Scheme (UKBMS)|url=http://www.ukbms.org|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230125155/http://www.ukbms.org/|archivedate=30 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=NABA_BCD>{{cite web |first1=Leslie |last1=Ries |title=Analyzing the NABA Butterfly Count Data|url=http://www.naba.org/pubs/ab141/ab141count_column.pdf|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223114316/http://www.naba.org/pubs/ab141/ab141count_column.pdf|archivedate=23 December 2016}}</ref> There are various protocols for monitoring butterflies and different organizations support one or more of transects, counts and/or opportunistic sightings.<ref name=NA_Goal>{{cite web|title=Goal 1: Track all North American butterfly monitoring|url=http://www.nab-net.org/goal-1|accessdate=29 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230133120/http://www.nab-net.org/goal-1|archivedate=30 December 2014}}</ref> [[eButterfly]] is an example of a program designed to capture any of the three types of counts for observers in North America.  Species-specific programs also exist, with monarchs the prominent example.<ref name=E_ButtHP>{{cite web|title=eButterfly Homepage|url=http://www.e-butterfly.org|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140408031027/http://www.e-butterfly.org/|archivedate=8 April 2014}}</ref> Two examples of this involve the counting of monarch butterflies during the fall [[Monarch butterfly migration|migration]] to overwintering sites in Mexico: (1) Monarch Watch is a continent-wide project, while (2) the Cape May Monarch Monitoring Project is an example of a local project.<ref name=MW_HP>{{cite web|title=Monarch Watch Homepage|url=http://www.monarchwatch.org|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=CS_MonarchButterfly>{{cite web|title=The Cape May Monarch Monitoring Project|publisher=New Jersey Audubon Research Department, and the Cape May Bird Observatory|url=http://www.monarchmonitoringproject.com/index.html|accessdate=4 October 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006123918/http://www.monarchmonitoringproject.com/index.html|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> The Austrian project [http://viel-falter.at Viel-Falter] investigated if and how trained and supervised pupils are able to systematically collect data about the occurrence of diurnal butterflies, and how this data could contribute to a permanent butterfly monitoring system. Despite substantial identification uncertainties for some species or species groups, the data collected by pupils was successfully used to predict the general habitat quality for butterflies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=R\u00fcdisser |first1=Johannes |last2=Tasser |first2=Erich |last3=Walde |first3=Janette |last4=Huemer |first4=Peter |last5=Lechner |first5=Kurt |last6=Ortner |first6=Alois |last7=Tappeiner |first7=Ulrike |title=Simplified and still meaningful: assessing butterfly habitat quality in grasslands with data collected by pupils |journal=Journal of Insect Conservation |date=10 July 2017 |volume=21 |issue=4 |pages=677\u2013688 |doi=10.1007/s10841-017-0010-3 }}</ref>\n\n===Ornithology===\n{{main|Birdwatching}}\nCitizen science projects have become increasingly focused on providing benefits to scientific research.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Rick |last1=Bonney |first2=Melinda S. |last2=LaBranche |date=May 1, 2004 |title=Citizen Science: Involving the Public in Research |website=Informal Science |url=https://www.informalscience.org/citizen-science-involving-public-research }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Barreto |first1=Claudia |last2=Fastovsky |first2=David E. |last3=Sheehan |first3=Peter M. |title=A Model for Integrating the Public into Scientific Research |journal=Journal of Geoscience Education |date=31 January 2018 |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=71\u201375 |doi=10.5408/1089-9995-51.1.71 |url=https://digitalcommons.uri.edu/geo_facpubs/2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first1=Rachel E. |last1=McCaffrey |date=December 2005 |title=Urban Habitats -- Using Citizen Science in Urban Bird Studies |journal=Urban Habitats |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=70\u201386 |url=http://www.urbanhabitats.org/v03n01/citizenscience_full.html }}</ref> The [[North American Bird Phenology Program]] (historically called the Bird Migration and Distribution records) may have been the earliest collective effort of citizens collecting ornithological information in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwrc.usgs.gov/bpp/|title=North American Phenology Program|accessdate=30 July 2016|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729190651/http://www.pwrc.usgs.gov/bpp/|archivedate=29 July 2016}}</ref> The program, dating back to 1883, was started by Wells Woodbridge Cooke. Cooke established a network of observers around North America to collect bird migration records. The [[National Audubon Society|Audubon Society]]'s [[Christmas Bird Count]], which began in 1900, is another example of a long-standing tradition of citizen science which has persisted to the present day.  Citizen scientists help gather data that will be analyzed by professional researchers, and can be used to produce bird population and biodiversity indicators.\n\nRaptor migration research relies on the data collected by the [[hawkwatching]] community. This mostly volunteer group counts migrating accipiters, buteos, falcons, harriers, kites, eagles, osprey, vultures and other raptors at hawk sites throughout North America during the spring and fall seasons.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Bird!\": An Exploration of Hawkwatching|last=Wargo|first=Brian M.|publisher=BMW Endeavors, LLC|year=2016|isbn=978-1-945226-00-7|location=McKees Rocks}}</ref> The daily data is uploaded to hawkcount.org where it can be viewed by professional scientists and the public.\n\nSuch indices can be useful tools to inform management, resource allocation, policy and planning.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Devictor | first1 = V. | last2 = Whittaker | first2 = R. J. | last3 = Bel trame | first3 = C. | year = 2010 | title = Beyond scarcity: citizen science programmes as useful tools for conservation biogeography | journal = Diversity and Distributions | volume = 16 | issue = 3| pages = 354\u2013362 | doi=10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00615.x}}</ref> For example, European breeding bird survey data provide input for the [[Farmland Bird Index]], adopted by the European Union as a structural indicator of sustainable development.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jiguet |first1=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric |last2=Devictor |first2=Vincent |last3=Julliard |first3=Romain |last4=Couvet |first4=Denis |title=French citizens monitoring ordinary birds provide tools for conservation and ecological sciences |journal=Acta Oecologica |date=October 2012 |volume=44 |pages=58\u201366 |doi=10.1016/j.actao.2011.05.003 |bibcode=2012AcO....44...58J |url=https://zenodo.org/record/3414128 }}</ref> This provides a cost-effective alternative to government monitoring.\n\nSimilarly, data collected by citizen scientists as part of BirdLife Australia's has been analysed to produce the first-ever Australian Terrestrial Bird Indices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian birdlife|url=http://birdlife.org.au/state-of-birds|accessdate=30 December 2015|date=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Citizen oceanography ===\nThe concept of citizen science has been extended to the ocean environment for characterizing ocean dynamics and tracking [[marine debris]]. For example, the mobile app Marine Debris Tracker is a joint partnership of [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] and the [[University of Georgia]].<ref name=MDT>{{cite web| title=Marine Debris Tracker| publisher=Marine Debris Tracker| url=http://www.marinedebris.engr.uga.edu| access-date=19 March 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227041320/http://www.marinedebris.engr.uga.edu/| archivedate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Long term sampling efforts such as the [[Continuous Plankton Recorder|continuous plankton recorder]] has been fitted on ships of opportunity since 1931. Plankton collection by sailors and subsequent genetic analysis was pioneered in 2013 by Indigo V Expeditions as a way to better understand marine microbial structure and function.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Common Oceanographer: Crowdsourcing the Collection of Oceanographic Data|journal = PLoS Biol|date = 9 September 2014|pmc = 4159111|pmid = 25203659|pages = e1001947|volume = 12|issue = 9|doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1001947|first = Federico M.|last = Lauro|first2 = Svend Jacob|last2 = Senstius|first3 = Jay|last3 = Cullen|first4 = Russell|last4 = Neches|first5 = Rachelle M.|last5 = Jensen|first6 = Mark V.|last6 = Brown|first7 = Aaron E.|last7 = Darling|first8 = Michael|last8 = Givskov|first9 = Diane|last9 = McDougald}}</ref>\n\n=== Coral reefs ===\nCitizen science in [[Coral reef]] studies developed in the 21st century.\n\n[[Underwater photography]] has become more popular since the early 2000s, resulting on millions of pictures posted every year on various websites and social media. This mass of documentation has great scientific potential, as millions of tourists possess a much superior coverage power than professional scientists, who cannot spend so much time in the field.\n\nAs a consequence, several participative sciences programs have been developed, supported by [[geotagging]] and identification web sites (such as [https://www.inaturalist.org/ iNaturalist.org]).  The ''Monitoring through many eyes'' project collates thousands of underwater images of the [[Great Barrier Reef]] and provides an interface for elicitation of reef health indicators.<ref name=MTME>{{cite web|title=Monitoring through many eyes project homepage\n |url=https://www.virtualreef.org.au\n |publisher=Queensland Government, Queensland University of Technology, CRCSI\n |accessdate=10 May 2017|url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301205255/https://www.virtualreef.org.au/|archivedate=1 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA) also offers opportunities for volunteer participation.  By taking measurements in [[United States National Marine Sanctuary|The United States' National Marine Sanctuaries]], citizens contribute data to [[marine biology]] projects.  In 2016, NOAA benefited from 137,000 hours of research.<ref name=MTME_2>{{cite web| title=Volunteers help to ensure national marine sanctuaries remain America's underwater treasures for future generations\n | url=https://sanctuaries.noaa.gov/involved/volunteer_future.html\n | publisher=National Ocean Servi, NOAA, Department of Commerce| accessdate=5 September 2017| url-status=live\n | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906034716/https://sanctuaries.noaa.gov/involved/volunteer_future.html| archivedate=6 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere also exist protocols for auto-organization and self-teaching aimed at biodiversity-interested snorkelers, in order for them to turn their observations into sound scientific data, available for research. This kind of approach has been successfully used in [[R\u00e9union island]], allowing for tens of new records and even new species.<ref name=\"CBM2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Bourjon |first1=Philippe |last2=Ducarme |first2=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric |last3=Quod |first3=Jean-Pascal |last4=Sweet |first4=Michael |year=2018 |title=Involving recreational snorkelers in inventory improvement or creation: a case study in the Indian Ocean |journal=Cahiers de Biologie Marine |volume=59 |pages=451\u2013460 |doi=10.21411/CBM.A.B05FC714 }}</ref>\n\n=== Agriculture ===\n\nFarmer participation in experiments has a long tradition in [[Agricultural science]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Gosset|first1= William S.|date=1936 |title= Co-Operation in Large-Scale Experiments|journal= Supplement to the Journal of the Royal Statistical Society|volume= 3|issue= 2|pages=115\u2013136|doi= 10.2307/2983667|access-date= |jstor= 2983667}}</ref> There are many opportunities for citizen engagement in different parts of food systems.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Ryan|first1= S.F|last2= Adamson|first2= N.L.|last3=Aktipis|first3=A.|last4=Andersen|first4=L.K.|last5=Austin|first5=R.|last6= Barnes|first6=L.|last7=Beasley|first7=M.R.|last8=Bedell|first8=K.D.|last9= Briggs|first9= S.|last10= Chapman|first10= B.|date=2018 |title= The role of citizen science in addressing grand challenges in food and agriculture research|journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society B|volume= 285|issue= 1891|pages= 20181977|doi= 10.1098/rspb.2018.1977|pmid= 30464064|access-date= |pmc= 6253361}}</ref> Citizen science is actively used for crop variety selection for climate adaptation, involving thousands of farmers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= van Etten|first1= Jacob|last2= de Sousa|first2= Kau\u00ea|last3=Aguilar|first3=Am\u00edlcar |last4=Barrios|first4=Mirna |last5=Coto|first5=Allan |last6= Dell\u2019Acqua|first6=Matteo |last7=Fadda|first7=Carlo |last8=Gebrehawaryat|first8=Yosef |last9= van de Gevel|first9= Jeske |last10=Gupta  |first10=Arnab|last11=Kiros|first11=Afewerki Y. |last12=Madriz|first12=Brandon |last13=Mathur|first13=Prem |last14=Mengistu|first14=Dejene K.|last15=Mercado|first15=Leida |last16=Nurhisen Mohammed|first16=Jemal |last17=Paliwal|first17=Ambica |last18=P\u00e8|first18=Mario Enrico |last19=Quir\u00f3s|first19=Carlos F. |last20=Rosas|first20=Juan Carlos |last21=Sharma|first21=Neeraj |last22=Singh|first22=S.S.|last23=Solanki|first23=Iswhar S.| last24=Steinke|first24=Jonathan |date=2019 |title= Crop variety management for climate adaptation supported by citizen science|journal= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume= 285|issue= 1891|pages= 4194\u20134199|doi= 10.1073/pnas.1813720116|pmid= 30782795|pmc= 6410884|access-date= }}</ref>\n\n=== Art history ===\nCitizen science has a long tradition in [[Natural science]]. But nowadays, citizen science projects can also be found in various fields of science like [[Art history]]. For example, the [[Zooniverse (citizen science project)|Zooniverse]] project AnnoTate is a transcription tool developed to enable volunteers to read and transcribe the personal papers of British-born and \u00e9migr\u00e9 artists.<ref name=AnnoTate>{{cite web|title=AnnoTate homepage|url=https://anno.tate.org.uk|publisher=Zooniverse|accessdate=2 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507142819/https://anno.tate.org.uk/|archivedate=7 May 2016}}</ref> The papers are drawn from the [[Tate Britain|Tate Archive]]. Another example of citizen science in art history is [[Human-based computation game#Artigo|ARTigo]].<ref name=Artigo>{{cite web|title=ARTigo homepage|url=http://www.artigo.org|publisher=ARTigo|accessdate=2 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601154649/http://www.artigo.org/|archivedate=1 June 2016}}</ref> ARTigo collects [[Semantics|semantic]] data on artworks from the footprints left by players of games featuring artwork images. From these footprints, ARTigo automatically builds a [[semantic search]] engine for artworks.\n\n== Modern technology ==\nNewer technologies have increased the options for citizen science.<ref name=BBC_NewEra>{{cite web|author=Dan Drollette|title=Citizen science enters a new era|url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120329-citizen-science-enters-a-new-era?selectorSection=technology\n |publisher=BBC|date=29 March 2012|accessdate=4 October 2014|url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018015022/http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120329-citizen-science-enters-a-new-era?selectorSection=technology|archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref> Citizen scientists can build and operate their own instruments to gather data for their own experiments or as part of a larger project. Examples include [[amateur radio]], [[amateur astronomy]], Six Sigma Projects, and [[Maker culture|Maker]] activities.  Scientist [[Joshua Pearce]] has advocated for the creation of [[open-source hardware]] based scientific equipment that both citizen scientists and professional scientists, which can be replicated by [[digital manufacturing]] techniques such as [[3D printing]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pearce |first1=J. M. |title=Building Research Equipment with Free, Open-Source Hardware |journal=Science |date=13 September 2012 |volume=337 |issue=6100 |pages=1303\u20131304 |doi=10.1126/science.1228183 |pmid=22984059 |bibcode=2012Sci...337.1303P }}</ref> Multiple studies have shown this approach radically reduces scientific equipment costs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pearce |first1=J. M. |title=Return on investment for open source scientific hardware development |journal=Science and Public Policy |date=April 2016 |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages=192\u2013195 |doi=10.1093/scipol/scv034 |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02119548/file/Return_on_Investment_for_Open_Source_Har.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |last1=Baden |first1=Tom |last2=Chagas |first2=Andre Maia |last3=Gage |first3=Greg |last4=Marzullo |first4=Timothy |last5=Prieto-Godino |first5=Lucia L. |last6=Euler |first6=Thomas |title=Open Labware: 3-D Printing Your Own Lab Equipment |journal=PLOS Biology |date=20 March 2015 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=e1002086 |doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.1002086 |pmid=25794301 |pmc=4368627 }}</ref> Examples of this approach include water testing, nitrate and other environmental testing, basic biology and optics.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url = https://publiclab.org/\n |title = Public Lab: a DIY environmental science community|last = Contributors|first = Public Lab\n |website = publiclab.org|access-date = 2016-02-27|url-status = live\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160226073149/https://publiclab.org/|archivedate = 26 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Damase |first1=Tulsi R. |last2=Stephens |first2=Daniel |last3=Spencer |first3=Adam |last4=Allen |first4=Peter B. |title=Open source and DIY hardware for DNA nanotechnology labs |journal=Journal of Biological Methods |date=31 August 2015 |volume=2 |issue=3 |pages=24 |doi=10.14440/jbm.2015.72 |pmid=26457320 |pmc=4598940 }}</ref><ref name=Zhang_1>{{cite journal |last1=Zhang |first1=Chenlong |last2=Anzalone |first2=Nicholas C. |last3=Faria |first3=Rodrigo P. |last4=Pearce |first4=Joshua M. |last5=de Brevern |first5=Alexandre G. |title=Open-Source 3D-Printable Optics Equipment |journal=PLoS ONE |date=27 March 2013 |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=e59840 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0059840 |pmid=23544104 |pmc=3609802 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...859840Z }}</ref> Groups such as [[Public Lab]], which is a community where citizen scientists can learn how to investigate environmental concerns using inexpensive [[Do it yourself|DIY]] techniques, embody this approach.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\n[[File:Citizen Science Center NCMNS.jpg|thumb|300px|Citizen Science Center exhibit in the Nature Research Center wing of the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]]]]\n\nVideo technology is much used in scientific research.   The Citizen Science Center in the [[Nature Research Center#First floor 2|Nature Research Center]] wing of the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences]] has exhibits on how to get involved in scientific research and become a citizen scientist.  For example, visitors can observe birdfeeders at the [[North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences#Prairie Ridge Ecostation|Prairie Ridge Ecostation]] satellite facility via live video feed and record which species they see.\n\nSince 2005, the [[Genographic Project]] has used the latest genetic technology to expand our knowledge of the human story, and its pioneering use of DNA testing to engage and involve the public in the research effort has helped to create a new breed of \"citizen scientist\". Geno 2.0 expands the scope for citizen science, harnessing the power of the [[Crowdsourcing|crowd]] to discover new details of human population history.<ref name=Wells>{{cite web|last = Wells|first = Spencer|title = The Genographic Project and the Rise of Citizen Science|publisher = Southern California Genealogical Society (SCGS)|year = 2013|url = http://www.scgsgenealogy.com/Jamboree/2013/DNAday.htm|accessdate = 10 July 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130710014353/http://www.scgsgenealogy.com/Jamboree/2013/DNAday.htm|archivedate = 10 July 2013}}</ref> This includes supporting, organization and dissemination of [[Genealogical DNA test|personal DNA (genetic) testing.]] Like [[Amateur astronomy]], citizen scientists encouraged by volunteer organizations like the [[International Society of Genetic Genealogy]] have provided valuable information and research to the professional scientific community.<ref name=KingJobling>{{cite journal|last1=King|doi=10.1016/j.tig.2009.06.003|quote=The International Society of Genetic Genealogy <http://www.isogg.org> advocates the use of genetics as a tool for genealogical research, and provides a support network for genetic genealogists. It hosts the ISOGG Y-haplogroup tree, which has the virtue of being regularly updated.|title=What's in a name? Y chromosomes, surnames and the genetic genealogy revolution|year=2009|first1=Turi E.|last2=Jobling|first2=Mark A.|journal=Trends in Genetics|volume=25|issue=8|pages=351\u201360|pmid=19665817|url=https://lra.le.ac.uk/bitstream/2381/8106/1/KingJoblingRevisedWeb.pdf|hdl=2381/8106}}</ref><ref name=AJHG>{{cite journal |last1=Mendez |first1=Fernando&nbsp;L. |last2=Krahn |first2=Thomas |last3=Schrack |first3=Bonnie |last4=Krahn |first4=Astrid-Maria |last5=Veeramah |first5=Krishna&nbsp;R. |last6=Woerner |first6=August&nbsp;E. |last7=Fomine |first7=Forka&nbsp;Leypey&nbsp;Mathew |last8=Bradman |first8=Neil |last9=Thomas |first9=Mark&nbsp;G. |last10=Karafet |first10=Tatiana&nbsp;M. |last11=Hammer |first11=Michael&nbsp;F. |title=An African American Paternal Lineage Adds an Extremely Ancient Root to the Human Y Chromosome Phylogenetic Tree |journal=The American Journal of Human Genetics |date=March 2013 |volume=92 |issue=3 |pages=454\u2013459 |doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2013.02.002 |pmid=23453668 |pmc=3591855 }}</ref>\n\nWith [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s, further citizen science is enabled. One example is the [[European Space Agency|ESA's]] AstroDrone smartphone app for gathering robotic data with the [[Parrot AR.Drone]].<ref name=AsDr>{{cite web| title=Astro Drone - A Crowdsourcing Game to Improve Visual Algorithms| url=http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/ai/projects/astrodrone.html| publisher=[[European Space Agency]]| access-date=17 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111042331/http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/ai/projects/astrodrone.html| archivedate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCitizens in Space (CIS), a project of the United States Rocket Academy, seeks to combine citizen science with citizen space exploration.<ref name=Citizens_In_Space>{{cite web|title=Citizens in Space|url=http://www.citizensinspace.org|publisher=Citizensinspace|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827233150/http://www.citizensinspace.org/|archivedate=27 August 2014}}</ref> CIS is training citizen astronauts to fly as payload operators on suborbital reusable spacecraft that are now in development. CIS will also be developing, and encouraging others to develop, citizen-science payloads to fly on suborbital vehicles. CIS has already acquired a contract for 10 flights on the Lynx suborbital vehicle, being developed by [[XCOR Aerospace]], and plans to acquire additional flights on [[XCOR Lynx]] and other suborbital vehicles in the future.<ref name=Citizens_In_Space/>\n\nCIS believes that \"The development of low-cost reusable suborbital spacecraft will be the next great enabler, allowing citizens to participate in space exploration and space science.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citizensinspace.org/2012/02/teachers-in-space-becomes-citizens-in-space-2/ |title=\"Teachers in Space\" becomes \"Citizens in Space\" |publisher=Citizensinspace.org |accessdate=6 November 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026131929/http://www.citizensinspace.org/2012/02/teachers-in-space-becomes-citizens-in-space-2/ |archivedate=26 October 2012 |date=February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Internet===\n\n[[File:SAH stopmo 1.webm|thumb|How your gameplay helps [[ScienceAtHome]] build a quantum computer]]\n\nThe Internet has been a boon to citizen science, particularly through [[gamification]].<ref name=BBC_NewEra/> One of the first Internet-based citizen science experiments was [[NASA]]'s [[Clickworkers]], which enabled the general public to assist in the classification of images, greatly reducing the time to analyze large data sets. Another was the Citizen Science Toolbox, launched in 2003, of the Australian Coastal Collaborative Research Centre.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://research.usc.edu.au/vital/access/manager/Repository/usc:1413 |title=The Citizen Science Toolbox : Citizen Science: Linking communities, scientists and decision-makers |first1=J. |last1=Fien |first2=T. F. |last2=Smith |last3=Lazarow |first3=N. S. |last4=Pembleton |first4=J. |last5=Rosenthal |first5=K |last6=Alcock |first6=D. |last7=Thomsen |first7=D. C. |last8=Hudson |first8=K. |last9=Gleeson |first9=J. |last10=Oliver |first10=P. |last11=Gooch |first11=M. |last12=White |first12=C. |last13=Powell |first13=B. |last14=Whelan |first14=J. |last15=Rickson |first15=R. |last16=Eisner |first16=R. |last17=Dwyer |first17=D. |last18=Malawkin |first18=H. |last19=Tilden |first19=J. |date=2003 }}</ref> Mozak is a game in which players create 3D reconstructions from images of actual human and mouse neurons, helping to advance understanding of the brain. One of the largest citizen science games is [[Eyewire]], a brain-mapping puzzle game developed at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] that now has over 200,000 players.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1145/2908131.2908151 |chapter=Because science is awesome |title=Proceedings of the 8th ACM Conference on Web Science - Web ''Sci'' '16 |pages=45\u201354 |year=2016 |last1=Tinati |first1=Ramine |last2=Luczak-Roesch |first2=Markus |last3=Simperl |first3=Elena |last4=Hall |first4=Wendy |isbn=9781450342087 |chapter-url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/390326/1/2016___WebSci___EyeWire_Motivations.pdf }}</ref> Another example is [[Quantum Moves]], a game developed by the Center for Driven Community Research at [[Aarhus University]], which uses online community efforts to solve quantum physics problems.<ref name=SCAH>{{cite web| title=Science at Home - About Us| url=https://www.scienceathome.org/about-us| publisher=Science at Home| access-date=17 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518221342/https://www.scienceathome.org/about-us/| archivedate=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://phys.au.dk/en/research/research-areas/coder/|title=CODER - AU Ideas Center for Community Driven Research|work=au.dk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911161608/http://phys.au.dk/en/research/research-areas/coder/|archivedate=11 September 2017}}</ref> The solutions found by players can then be used in the lab to feed computational algorithms used in building a scalable [[Quantum computing|quantum computer]].\n\nMore generally, Amazon's [[Amazon Mechanical Turk|Mechanical Turk]] is frequently used in the creation, collection, and processing of data by paid citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/inside-amazons-hidden-science-factory/|title=The Internet's hidden science factory|work=PBS NewsHour|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911114807/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/inside-amazons-hidden-science-factory/|archivedate=11 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bohannon |first1=J. |title=Mechanical Turk upends social sciences |journal=Science |date=9 June 2016 |volume=352 |issue=6291 |pages=1263\u20131264 |doi=10.1126/science.352.6291.1263 |pmid=27284175 |bibcode=2016Sci...352.1263B }}</ref> There is controversy as to whether or not the data collected through such services is reliable, as it is subject to participants' desire for compensation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guilty-planet/httpblogsscientificamericancomguilty-planet20110707the-pros-cons-of-amazon-mechanical-turk-for-scientific-surveys/|title=The pros & cons of Amazon Mechanical Turk for scientific surveys|last=Jacquet|first=Jennifer|work=Scientific American Blog Network|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911163048/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guilty-planet/httpblogsscientificamericancomguilty-planet20110707the-pros-cons-of-amazon-mechanical-turk-for-scientific-surveys/|archivedate=11 September 2017}}</ref> However, use of [[Amazon Mechanical Turk|Mechanical Turk]] tends to quickly produce more diverse participant backgrounds, as well as comparably accurate data when compared to traditional collection methods.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Michael Buhrmester, Tracy Kwang, and Samuel D. Gosling|date=2011|title=Amazon's Mechanical Turk: A New Source of Inexpensive, Yet High-Quality, Data?|url=https://www.pomona.edu/sites/default/files/buhrmester_-crowdsourcing-amazon-mturk.pdf|journal=Perspectives on Psychological Science|volume=6|issue=1|pages=3\u20135|via=SAGE|doi=10.1177/1745691610393980|pmid=26162106|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729100125/https://www.pomona.edu/sites/default/files/buhrmester_-crowdsourcing-amazon-mturk.pdf|archivedate=29 July 2016|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref>\n\nThe internet has also enabled citizen scientists to gather data to be analyzed by professional researchers.  Citizen science networks are often involved in the observation of cyclic events of nature ([[phenology]]), such as effects of global warming on plant and animal life in different geographic areas,<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0410/p14s01-sten.html \"Citizen scientists\" watch for signs of climate change] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411230403/http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0410/p14s01-sten.html |date=11 April 2008 }}, ''The Christian Science Monitor'', 10 April 2008.</ref> and in monitoring programs for natural-resource management.<ref>Ballard, H., Pilz, D., Jones, E.T., and Getz, C. (2005). Training Curriculum for Scientists and Managers: Broadening Participation in Biological Monitoring. Corvallis, OR: Institute for Culture and Ecology.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Cooper | first1 = C. B. | last2 = Dickinson | first2 = J. | last3 = Phillips | first3 = T. | last4 = Bonney | first4 = R. | year = 2007 | title = Citizen Science as a Tool for Conservation in Residential Ecosystems | journal = Ecology and Society | volume = 12 | issue = 2 | doi=10.5751/es-02197-120211}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1 = Firehock |first1 = K. |last2 = West |first2 = J. |title = A Brief History of Volunteer Biological Water Monitoring Using Macroinvertebrates |journal = Journal of the North American Benthological Society |volume = 14 |issue = 1 |pages = 197\u2013202 |doi = 10.2307/1467734 |year = 1995 |jstor = 1467734 }}</ref> On [[BugGuide]].Net, an online community of naturalists who share observations of [[arthropod]], amateurs and professional researchers contribute to the analysis. By October 2014, BugGuide has over 808,718 images submitted by more than 27,846 contributors.<ref name=BG_Stats>{{cite web|title=BugGuide System Statistics |url=http://bugguide.net/node/view/11181 |publisher=BugGuide.net |date=6 October 2014 |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425102840/http://bugguide.net/node/view/11181 |archivedate=25 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bubbles Within Bubbles.jpg|thumb|An NASA/JPL image from the Zooniverse's [[The Milky Way Project]] showing a hierarchical bubble structure]]\n\nNot counting [[iNaturalist]] and [[eBird]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/inaturalist.org|title=Alexa.com}}</ref> the [[Zooniverse (citizen science project)|Zooniverse]] is home to the internet's largest, most popular and most successful citizen science projects.<ref name=ESERO>{{cite web|title=New Zooniverse projects \u2013 Bat Detective and Click to Cure|url=http://www.esero.org.uk/news/new-zooniverse-projects-bat-detective-and-click-to-cure|publisher=European Space Education Resource Office|date=30 October 2012|accessdate=8 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014070524/http://www.esero.org.uk/news/new-zooniverse-projects-bat-detective-and-click-to-cure|archivedate=14 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1145/2702123.2702420 |chapter=Designing for Citizen Data Analysis |title=Proceedings of the 33rd Annual ACM Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems - CHI '15 |pages=4069\u20134078 |year=2015 |last1=Tinati |first1=Ramine |last2=Van Kleek |first2=Max |last3=Simperl |first3=Elena |last4=Luczak-R\u00f6sch |first4=Markus |last5=Simpson |first5=Robert |last6=Shadbolt |first6=Nigel |isbn=9781450331456 }}</ref> The Zooniverse and the suite of projects it contains is produced, maintained and developed by the Citizen Science Alliance (CSA).<ref name=CSA>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science Alliance website|url=http://www.citizensciencealliance.org|accessdate=28 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812000639/http://www.citizensciencealliance.org/|archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref> The member institutions of the CSA work with many academic and other partners around the world to produce projects that use the efforts and ability of volunteers to help scientists and researchers deal with the flood of data that confronts them. On 29 June 2015, the Zooniverse released a new software version with a project-building tool allowing any registered user to create a project.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lintott|first1=Chris|title=A Whole New Zooniverse|url=https://blog.zooniverse.org/2015/06/29/a-whole-new-zooniverse/|website=Zooniverse Blog|accessdate=15 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617133346/https://blog.zooniverse.org/2015/06/29/a-whole-new-zooniverse/|archivedate=17 June 2016|date=29 June 2015}}</ref> Project owners may optionally complete an approval process to have their projects listed on the Zooniverse site and promoted to the Zooniverse community.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zooniverse Project Builder Policies, or So You Want To Launch a Project?|url=https://www.zooniverse.org/lab-policies|website=Zooniverse|accessdate=15 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617144633/https://www.zooniverse.org/lab-policies|archivedate=17 June 2016}}</ref> A NASA/JPL picture to the right gives an example from one of Zooniverse's projects [[The Milky Way Project]].\n\nThe website [[CosmoQuest]] has as its goal \"To create a community of people bent on together advancing our understanding of the universe; a community of people who are participating in doing science, who can explain why what they do matters, and what questions they are helping to answer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cosmoquest.org/x/about/|title=About Us|work=cosmoquest.org|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803003859/http://cosmoquest.org/x/about/|archivedate=3 August 2016|date=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nCrowdCrafting enables its participants to create and run projects where volunteers help with image classification, transcription, geocoding and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crowdcrafting.org/about|title=crowdcrafting|author=Scifabric|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102215736/https://crowdcrafting.org/about|archivedate=2 November 2017|access-date=2014-10-04}}</ref> The platform is powered by PyBossa software, a free and open-source framework for crowdsourcing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pybossa.com/|title=PyBossa|author=Shuttleworth Foundation|work=pybossa.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105154726/http://pybossa.com/|archivedate=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nProject Soothe is a citizen science research project based at the University of Edinburgh. The aim of this research is to create a bank of soothing images, submitted by members of the public, which can be used to help others through psychotherapy and research in the future. Since 2015, Project Soothe has received over 600 soothing photographs from people in 23 countries. Anyone aged 12 years or over are eligible to participate in this research in two ways: (1) By submitting soothing photos that they have taken with a description of why the images make them feel soothed (2) By rating the photos that have been submitted by people worldwide for their soothability.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projectsoothe.com/participate/4593532002|author=Project Soothe|title=Participate in Project Soothe|work=projectsoothe.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119235525/http://www.projectsoothe.com/participate/4593532002|archivedate=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Smartphone ===\n\nThe bandwidth and ubiquity afforded by smartphones has vastly expanded the opportunities for citizen science.  Examples include [[iNaturalist]], the San Francisco project, the WildLab, Project Noah,<ref name=PkSc>{{cite web|title=San Francisco Parks Alliance ParkScan|url=http://www.sfparksalliance.org/our-work/policy/research/parkscan|publisher=San Francisco Parks Alliance|date=2014|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805103901/http://www.sfparksalliance.org/our-work/policy/research/parkscan|archivedate=5 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=WiLa>{{cite web|title=The Wildlab|url=http://www.thewildlab.org|publisher=The Wildlab|date=2016|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824232455/http://www.thewildlab.org/|archivedate=24 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=PrjNoah>{{cite web|url=http://www.projectnoah.org|title=Project Noah|publisher=Networked Organisms|date=2016|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812112645/http://www.projectnoah.org/|archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> and Aurorasurus. Due to their ubiquity, for example, [[Twitter]], [[Facebook]], and [[smartphone]]s have been useful for citizen scientists, having enabled them to discover and propagate a new type of aurora dubbed \"STEVE\" in 2016.<ref name=\"Twitter and Citizen science\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gi.alaska.edu/Alaska-Science-Forum/citizen-science-meets-aurora |title=Citizen science meets the aurora |last=Rozell |first=Ned |date=2 April 2015 |website=University of Alaska Fairbanks Geophysical Institute |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731234543/http://www.gi.alaska.edu/Alaska-Science-Forum/citizen-science-meets-aurora |archivedate=31 July 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThere are also [[Mobile app|apps]] for monitoring birds, marine wildlife and other organisms, and the \"Loss of the Night\".<ref name=C.Clarke_YouTube>{{cite web|title=Citizen science: Chandra Clarke at TEDxChathamKent\n |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U7XOcB6_TWw|publisher=YouTube\n |date=14 March 2014|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801223346/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U7XOcB6_TWw\n |archivedate=1 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=lotn_discovery>{{cite news|last=O'Hanlon|first=Larry\n |title=Turn Yourself into a Skyglow Meter\n |url=http://news.discovery.com/space/astronomy/turn-yourself-into-a-skyglow-meter-130501.htm|accessdate=8 May 2013\n |newspaper=Discovery News|date=1 May 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503003739/http://news.discovery.com/space/astronomy/turn-yourself-into-a-skyglow-meter-130501.htm|archivedate=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Android (operating system)|Android]] app Sapelli is a mobile data-collection and -sharing platform designed with a particular focus on non-literate and illiterate users.<ref name=Sap>{{cite web|title=Sapelli\n |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/excites/software/sapelli|publisher=University College London\n |date=2016|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817000416/https://www.ucl.ac.uk/excites/software/sapelli|archivedate=17 August 2016}}</ref> The SPOTTERON app creates synergy effects for projects by sharing a common feature set.<ref>{{Cite book|date=6 November 2018 |publisher=Frontiers Media SA|pages=66\u201369\n |doi=10.3389/978-2-88945-587-4 |isbn=9782889455874|chapter=Austrian Citizen Science Conference 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"The Crowd and the Cloud\" is a four-part series broadcast during April 2017, which examines citizen science.<ref name=Crowd&Cloud>{{cite web| title=The Crowd and the Cloud| url=http://crowdandcloud.org| website=The Crowd and the Cloud| accessdate=24 April 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425030405/http://crowdandcloud.org/| archivedate=25 April 2017}}</ref> It shows how smartphones, computers and mobile technology enable regular citizens to become part of a 21st-century way of doing science.<ref name=Crowd&Cloud/> The programs also demonstrate how CSs help professional scientists to advance knowledge, which helps speed up new discoveries and innovations. The Crowd & The Cloud is based upon work supported by the [[National Science Foundation]].<ref name=Crowd&Cloud/>\n\n===Seismology===\n\nSince 1975, in order to improve earthquake detection and collect useful information, the [[European-Mediterranean Seismological Centre]] monitors the visits of earthquake eyewitnesses to its website and relies on Facebook and Twitter.<ref name=EMSC>{{cite web| title=EMSC History| url=https://www.emsc-csem.org/about| publisher=The European-Mediterranean Seismological Centre| access-date=16 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908143401/https://www.emsc-csem.org/about/| archivedate=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hydrology===\n\nCitizen science has been used to provide valuable data in [[hydrology]] (catchment science), notably flood risk, [[water quality]] and [[water resource management]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Starkey|first1=Eleanor|last2=Parkin|first2=Geoff|last3=Birkinshaw|first3=Steve|last4=Large|first4=Andy|last5=Quinn|first5=Paul|last6=Gibson|first6=Ceri|title=Demonstrating the value of community-based ('citizen science') observations for catchment modelling and characterisation|journal=Journal of Hydrology|volume=548|pages=801\u2013817|date=2017|doi=10.1016/j.jhydrol.2017.03.019|bibcode=2017JHyd..548..801S}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Community Involvement in UK Catchment Management|url=http://www.fwr.org/Catchment/frr0021.pdf|publisher=Foundation for Water Research|accessdate=27 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428053522/http://www.fwr.org/Catchment/frr0021.pdf|archivedate=28 April 2017}}</ref> A growth in internet use and smartphone ownership has allowed users to collect and share real-time flood-risk information using, for example, social media and web-based forms. Although traditional data collection methods are well-established, citizen science is being used to fill the data gaps on a local level, and is therefore meaningful to individual communities. It has been demonstrated that citizen science is particularly advantageous during a [[flash flood]] because the public are more likely to witness these rarer hydrological events than scientists.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newcastle University|title=Communities can fill the gaps on flooding|url=http://www.ncl.ac.uk/press/news/2017/04/communityfloodmonitoring/|accessdate=27 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428051503/http://www.ncl.ac.uk/press/news/2017/04/communityfloodmonitoring/|archivedate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Plastics and pollution===\n{{Further| Plastic pollution}}\n[[File:Pollution plastique 2.jpg|thumb|right|Plastic Pollution in [[Madagascar]]]]\nCitizen science includes projects that help monitor [[plastic]]s and their associated [[pollution]].<ref name=ES_PP1>{{cite news| title=How citizen scientists, technology and people power can help clean up our seas| author=Anna Turns| url=https://www.standard.co.uk/futurelondon/theplasticfreeproject/how-citizen-scientists-technology-and-people-power-can-help-clean-up-our-seas-a4261831.html| work=[[Evening Standard]]| date=15 October 2019| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=TMO_1>{{cite web| title=Finding Solutions to Plastic Pollution (How You Can Help)| url=https://treadingmyownpath.com/2016/11/10/solutions-to-plastic-pollution| publisher=Lindsay Miles| date=10 November 2016| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=ScS_1>{{cite web| title=SciStarter| url=https://scistarter.org| publisher=SciStarter.org| date=2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=CSP_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science Projects on Plastic Pollution| url=https://www.arocha.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/citizen-science-projects.pdf| publisher=A Rocha International| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref> These include [[The Ocean Cleanup]], #OneLess, The Big Microplastic Survey, EXXpedition and Alliance to End Plastic Waste.<ref name=OL_1>{{cite web| title=#OneLess| url=https://www.onelessbottle.org| publisher=OneLess 2017| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=BMS_1>{{cite web| title=The Big Microplastic Survey| url=https://microplasticsurvey.org| publisher=The Big Microplastic Survey 2018| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=EXX_1>{{cite web| title=eXXpedition| url=https://exxpedition.com| publisher=eXXpedition 2019| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=AEP_1>{{cite web| title=Alliance To End Plastic Waste| url=https://endplasticwaste.org| publisher=Alliance to End Plastic Waste| date=2019| access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref> Ellipsis seeks to map the distribution of litter using aerial data mapping by [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s and [[machine learning]] software.<ref name=EE_1>{{cite web| title=Ellipsis| url=https://ellipsis-environmental.com| publisher=Ellipsis Environmental| date=2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> A Zooniverse project called The Plastic Tide (now finished) helped train an [[algorithm]] used by Ellipsis.<ref name=TPT_1>{{cite web| title=The Plastic Tide| url=https://www.zooniverse.org/projects/theplastictide/the-plastic-tide| publisher=Zooniverse| date=2017| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nProjects that use [[Mobile app|apps]] include:<ref name=AWN_1>{{cite web| title=Mobile Apps and Marine Debris| url=https://africanwastenetwork.org.za/news/mobile-apps-marine-debris| publisher=Sustainable Seas Trust| date=29 August 2017| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[European Environment Agency]] launched an initiative called \"Marine Litter Watch\" in June 2018. This uses mobile phones to: (quote) \"help individuals and communities come together to clean up Europe\u2019s beaches.\"<ref name=EEA_1>{{cite web| title=Citizens collect plastic and data to protect Europe's marine environment| url=https://www.eea.europa.eu/themes/water/europes-seas-and-coasts/assessments/marine-litterwatch/briefing| publisher=European Environment Agency| date=8 June 2018| access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref> \n* PlasticPatrol seeks to log and record plastic pollution: (quote) \"The Plastic Patrol app is a real world tool that combines citizen science and scientific analysis to help us gather crucial insight into plastic pollution.\"<ref name=PP_1>{{cite web| title=Plastic Patrol| url=https://plasticpatrol.co.uk| publisher=Plastic Patrol CIC| access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Literati's mission is to eradicate [[litter]]: (quote) \"When millions of people come together, the impossible becomes reality, and change happens.\"<ref name=Lit_1>{{cite web| title=Litterati| url=https://www.litterati.org| publisher=Litterati| date=2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Anecdata helps anyone and any organisation to create a project: (quote) \"Anecdata helps individuals and organizations collect, manage, and share their citizen science data, providing both web-based and mobile solutions for gathering and accessing observations.\"<ref name=Anec_1>{{cite web| title=Anecdata| url=https://www.anecdata.org| publisher=MDI Biological Laboratory| date=2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=MDI_1>{{cite web| title=MDI Biological Laboratory develops Anecdata citizen science mobile app| url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-01/mdib-mbl011718.php| publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science| date=January 2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* In the [[United Kingdom|UK]] #2minutebeachclean seeks to purge plastics in coastal environments.<ref name=BC_1>{{cite web| title=#2minutebeachclean| url=https://beachclean.net| publisher=2 Minute Beach Clean| access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref> They offer an app and a beachclean board, which can be displayed on beaches: (quote) \"We believe that every piece of litter removed from the beach matters. So it doesn\u2019t matter if you do 2 minutes or 30.\"<ref name=BC_1/>\n\nExamples of relevant articles (by date):\n\n* Citizen Science Promotes Environmental Engagement: (quote) \"Citizen science projects are rapidly gaining popularity among the public, in which volunteers help gather data on [[species]] that can be used by scientists in research. And it\u2019s not just adults who are involved in these projects \u2013 even kids have collected high-quality data in the US.\"<ref name=SC_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Science Promotes Environmental Engagement| author=Neha Jain| url=https://magazine.scienceconnected.org/2018/01/citizen-science-environmental-engagement| publisher=Science Connected, Inc.| date=4 January 2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Tackling [[Microplastics]] on Our Own: (quote) \"Plastics, ranging from the circles of soda can rings to [[microbeads]] the size of pinheads, are starting to replace images of sewage for a leading cause of pollution \u2013 especially in the ocean\". Further, \"With recent backing from the Crowdsourcing and Citizen Science Act, citizen science is increasingly embraced as a tool by US Federal agencies.\"<ref name=TM_1>{{cite web| title=Tackling Microplastics on Our Own| author1=Alex Long| author2=Anne Bowser| url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/article/tackling-microplastics-our-own| publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars| date=6 February 2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Citizen Scientists Are Tracking Plastic Pollution Worldwide: (quote) \"Scientists who are monitoring the spread of tiny pieces of plastic throughout the environment are getting help from a small army of citizen volunteers \u2013 and they\u2019re finding bits of [[polymer]] in some of the most remote parts of North America.\"<ref name=Seek_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Scientists Are Tracking Plastic Pollution Worldwide| author=Matt Smith| url=https://www.seeker.com/conservation/citizen-scientists-are-tracking-plastic-pollution-worldwide| publisher=Group Nine Media| date=12 March 2018| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Artificial intelligence]] and citizen scientists: Powering the clean-up of Asia Pacific's beaches:(quote) \"The main objective is to support citizen scientists cleaning up [[New Zealand]] beaches and get a better understanding of why litter is turning up, so preventive and proactive action can be taken.\"<ref name=MAI_1>{{cite web| title=Artificial intelligence and citizen scientists: Powering the clean-up of Asia Pacific's beaches| author=Mike Chan| url=https://news.microsoft.com/apac/2019/04/29/artificial-intelligence-and-citizen-scientists-powering-the-clean-up-of-asia-pacifics-beaches| publisher=[[Microsoft]]| date=29 April 2019| access-date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n* Citizen science could help address [[Canada]]'s plastic pollution problem: (quote) \"But citizen engagement and participation in science goes beyond beach cleanups, and can be used as a tool to bridge gaps between communities and scientists. These partnerships between scientists and citizen scientists have produced real world data that have influenced policy changes.\"<ref name=Conv_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen science could help address Canada's plastic pollution problem| author=Tony Walker| url=https://theconversation.com/citizen-science-could-help-address-canadas-plastic-pollution-problem-121787| publisher=The Conversation Trust(UK) Ltd.| date=12 September 2019| access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nExamples of relevant scientific studies or books include (by date):\n\n* ''Distribution and abundance of small plastic debris on beaches in the SE Pacific ([[Chile]]): a study supported by a citizen science project'': (quote) \"The citizen science project \"National Sampling of Small Plastic Debris\" was supported by schoolchildren from all over Chile who documented the distribution and abundance of small plastic debris on Chilean beaches. Thirty-nine schools and nearly 1000 students from continental Chile and [[Easter Island]] participated in the activity.\"<ref name=VHR_1>{{cite journal| title=Distribution and abundance of small plastic debris on beaches in theSE Pacific (Chile): A study supported by a citizen science project| author1=V. Hidalgo-Ruz| author2=M. Thiel| journal=Marine Environmental Research| date=26 February 2013| volume=87\u201388| pages=12\u201318| doi=10.1016/j.marenvres.2013.02.015| pmid=23541391}}</ref>\n* ''Incorporating citizen science to study plastics in the environment'': (quote) \"Taking advantage of public interest in the impact of plastic on the marine environment, successful Citizen Science (CS) programs incorporate members of the public to provide repeated sampling for time series as well as [[wikt:synoptic|synoptic]] collections over wide geographic regions.\"<ref name=ICS_2>{{cite journal| title=Incorporating citizen science to study plastics in the environment| author1=E.R. Zettler| author2=H. Takada| author3=B. Monteleone| author4=N. Mallos| author5=M. Eriksen| author6=L.A. Amaral-Zettler| journal=Analytical Methods| volume=9| date=14 November 2016| issue=9| pages=1392\u20131403| doi=10.1039/C6AY02716D| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/22cbd784a2c5ca88edef0c474b543d88b8a4c678}}</ref>\n* ''Marine [[Human impact on the environment| anthropogenic]] litter on British beaches: A 10-year nationwide assessment using citizen science data'': (quote) \"Citizen science projects, whereby members of the public gather information, offer a low-cost method of collecting large volumes of data with considerable temporal and spatial coverage. Furthermore, such projects raise awareness of environmental issues and can lead to positive changes in behaviours and attitudes.\"<ref name=MAL_1>{{cite journal| title=Marine anthropogenic litter on British beaches: A 10-year nationwide assessment using citizen science data| author1=S.E. Nelms| author2=C. Coombes| author3=L.C. Foster| author4=T.S. Galloway| author5=B.J. Godley| author6=P.K. Lindeque| author7=M.J. Witt| journal=Science of the Total Environment| date=1 February 2017| volume=579| pages=1399\u20131409| doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2016.11.137| pmid=27913017| bibcode=2017ScTEn.579.1399N}}</ref>\n* ''Determining Global Distribution of Microplastics by Combining Citizen Science and In-Depth Case Studies'': (quote) \"Our first project involves the general public through citizen science. Participants collect sand samples from beaches using a basic [[Protocol (science)| protocol]], and we subsequently extract and quantify microplastics in a central laboratory using the standard operating procedure.\"<ref name=GBD_1>{{cite journal| title=Determining Global Distribution of Microplastics by Combining Citizen Science and In-Depth Case Studies| author1=T. Bosker| author2=P. Behrens| author3=M.G. Vijver| journal=Integrated Environmental Assessment and Management| volume=13| issue=3| pages=536\u2013541| date=9 February 2017| doi=10.1002/ieam.1908| pmid=28440934}}</ref>\n* ''[[Risk perception| Risk Perception]] of Plastic Pollution: Importance of Stakeholder Involvement and Citizen Science'': (quote) \"The chapter finally discusses how risk perception can be improved by greater stakeholder involvement and utilization of citizen science and thereby improve the foundation for timely and efficient societal measures.\"<ref name=RP_1>{{cite book| title=Risk Perception of Plastic Pollution: Importance of Stakeholder Involvement and Citizen Science| author1=K. Syberg| author2=S.F. Hansen| author3=T.B. Christensen| author4=F.R Khan| work=Freshwater Microplastics| publisher=Springer, Cham| date=2018| volume=58| pages=203\u2013221| doi=10.1007/978-3-319-61615-5_10| isbn=978-3-319-61615-5}}</ref>\n* ''Assessing the citizen science approach as tool to increase awareness on the marine litter problem'':(quote) \"This paper provides a quantitative assessment of students' attitude and behaviors towards marine litter before and after their participation to SEACleaner, an educational and citizen science project devoted to monitor macro- and micro-litter in an Area belonging to [[Ligurian Sea Cetacean Sanctuary|Pelagos Sanctuary]].\"<ref name=ACS_1>{{cite journal| title=Assessing the citizen science approach as tool to increase awareness on the marine litter problem| author1=M.Locritania| author2=S.Merlinob| author3=M.Abbate| journal=Marine Pollution Bulletin| date=March 2019| volume=140| pages=0320\u2013329| doi=10.1016/j.marpolbul.2019.01.023| pmid=30803651}}</ref>\n* ''Spatial trends and drivers of marine debris accumulation on shorelines in [[South Eleuthera]], [[The Bahamas]] using citizen science'': (quote) \"This study measured spatial distribution of marine debris stranded on beaches in South Eleuthera, The Bahamas. Citizen science, fetch modeling, relative exposure index and predictive mapping were used to determine marine debris source and abundance.\"<ref name=ST_1>{{cite journal |last1=Ambrose |first1=Kristal K. |last2=Box |first2=Carolynn |last3=Boxall |first3=James |last4=Brooks |first4=Annabelle |last5=Eriksen |first5=Marcus |last6=Fabres |first6=Joan |last7=Fylakis |first7=Georgios |last8=Walker |first8=Tony R. |title=Spatial trends and drivers of marine debris accumulation on shorelines in South Eleuthera, The Bahamas using citizen science |journal=Marine Pollution Bulletin |date=May 2019 |volume=142 |pages=145\u2013154 |doi=10.1016/j.marpolbul.2019.03.036 |pmid=31232287 }}</ref><ref name=ST_2>{{cite web| title=Spatial trends and drivers of marine debris accumulation on shorelines in South Eleuthera, The Bahamas using citizen science| last1=Ambrose |first1=Kristal K. |last2=Box |first2=Carolynn |last3=Boxall |first3=James |last4=Brooks |first4=Annabelle |last5=Eriksen |first5=Marcus |last6=Fabres |first6=Joan |last7=Fylakis |first7=Georgios |last8=Walker |first8=Tony R. | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/331839548| publisher=ResearchGate| date=May 2019| access-date=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n* ''Making citizen science count: Best practices and challenges of citizen science projects on plastics in [[Aquatic ecosystem| aquatic environments]]'':(quote) \"Citizen science is a [[Cost-effectiveness analysis|cost-effective]] way to gather data over a large geographical range while simultaneously raising public awareness on the problem\".<ref name=MCS_1>{{cite journal| title=Making citizen science count: Best practices and challenges of citizen science projects on plastics in aquatic environments| author1=L. Rambonnet| author2=S.C.Vink| author3=A.M.Land-Zandstra| author4=T. Bosker| journal=Marine Pollution Bulletin| date=August 2019| volume=145| pages=271\u2013277|doi=10.1016/j.marpolbul.2019.05.056| pmid=31590787}}</ref><ref name=UL_1>{{cite web| title=How do you make citizen science successful?| url=https://www.universiteitleiden.nl/en/news/2019/06/how-do-you-make-citizen-science-successful| \npublisher=Universiteit Leiden| date=14 June 2019| access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n* ''White and wonderful? Microplastics prevail in snow from the [[Alps]] to the [[Arctic]]'': (quote) \"\"In March 2018, five samples were taken at different locations on [[Svalbard]] (Fig. 1A and Table 1) by citizen scientists embarking on a land expedition by [[ski-doo]] (Aemalire project). The citizens were instructed on contamination prevention and equipped with protocol forms, prerinsed 2-liter stainless steel containers (Ecotanca), a porcelain mug, a steel spoon, and a soup ladle for sampling.\"<ref name=WaW_1>{{cite journal| title=White and wonderful? Microplastics prevail in snow from the Alps to the Arctic| author1=M. Bergmann| author2=S. M\u00fctzel| author3=S. Primpke| author4=M.B. Tekman| author5=J. Trachsel| author6=G. Gerdts| journal=[[Science Advances]]| date=14 August 2019| volume=5| issue=8| doi=10.1126/sciadv.aax1157| pmid=31453336| pmc=6693909| page=eaax1157}}</ref>\n\n===Citizen sensing===\n\nCitizen sensing can be a form of Citizen science: (quote) \"The work of citizen sensing, as a form of citizen science, then further transforms [[Isabelle Stengers| Stengers]]\u2019s notion of the work of science by moving the experimental facts and collectives where scientific work is undertaken out of the laboratory of experts and into the world of citizens.\"<ref name=FCS_1>{{cite journal|title=From Citizen Sensing to Collective Monitoring:Working through the Perceptive and Affective Problematics of Environmental Pollution|author1=H. Pritchard|author2=J. Gabrys|journal=GeoHumanities|date=16 November 2016|volume=2|issue=2|pages=354\u2013371|doi=10.1080/2373566X.2016.1234355}}</ref> Similar sensing activities include [[Crowdsensing]] and [[Participatory monitoring]]. While the idea of using mobile technology to aid this sensing is not new, creating devices and systems that can be used to aid regulation has not been straightforward.<ref name=FCS_1/> Some examples of projects that include citizen sensing are:\n* Citizen Sense (2013-2018): (quote) \"Practices of monitoring and sensing environments have migrated to everyday participatory applications, where users of smart phones and networked devices are able to engage with modes of environmental observation and data collection.\"<ref name=CitSen_1>{{cite web|title=Citizen Sense|url=https://citizensense.net|publisher=Citizen Sense| date=2017| access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=CSEP_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Sensing and Environmental Practice: Assessing Participatory Engagements with Environments through Sensor Technologies|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/rcn/106442/factsheet/en|publisher=EU Publications Office|date=2 August 2019|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Breathe Project: (quote) \"We use the best available science and technology to better understand the quality of the air we breathe and provide opportunities for citizens to engage and take action.\"<ref name=BPr_1>{{cite web|title=Breathe Project|url=https://breatheproject.org|publisher=Breathe Project|date=2019|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* The Bristol Approach to Citizen Sensing: (quote) \"Citizen Sensing is about empowering people and places to understand and use smart tech and data from sensors to tackle the issues they care about, connect with other people who can help, and take positive, practical action.\"<ref name=BrAp_1>{{cite web|title=The Bristol Approach|url=https://www.bristolapproach.org|publisher=The Bristol Approach|date=2018|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=URB_1>{{cite web|title=Citizen sensing - where people act as sensors|url=https://urbact.eu/citizen-sensing-where-people-act-sensors|publisher=URBACT|date=2017|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Luftdaten.info: (quote) \"You and thousands of others around the world install self-built sensors on the outside their home. Luftdaten.info generates a continuously updated particular matter map from the transmitted data.\"<ref name=LDI_1>{{cite web|title=Luftdaten.info|url=https://luftdaten.info|publisher=OK Lab Stuttgart|date=6 October 2016|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* CitiSense: (quote) \"CitiSense aims to co-develop a participatory risk management system (PRMS) with citizens, local authorities and organizations which enables them to contribute to advanced climate services and enhanced urban climate resilience as well as receive recommendations that support their security.\"<ref name=CsSe_1>{{cite web|title=Citizen Sensing \u2013 Urban Climate Resilience through Participatory Risk Management Systems|url=https://citta.fe.up.pt/projects/1-48-citizen-sensing-2013-urban-climate-resilience-through-participatory-risk-management-systems|publisher=CITTA|date=September 2017|access-date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus (COVID19) pandemic===\n{{also| Portal:Coronavirus_disease_2019}}\n{{also| Wikipedia:WikiProject_COVID-19}}\n{{also| COVID-19_apps}}\n\nResources for CS and scientific [[Crowdsourcing#Health-care_crowdsourcing| Crowdsourcing]] projects concerning the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID19) can be found on the internet or as apps.<ref name=CSR1>{{cite web | title=Citizen science resources related to the COVID19 pandemic| url=https://www.citizenscience.org/covid-19| author=CSA team| publisher=Citizen Science Association| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=COIE_1>{{cite web| title=COVID-19 Open Innovation Efforts| url=https://my.usgs.gov/confluence/display/cdi/COVID-19+Open+Innovation+Efforts| publisher=[[University of California, San Francisco]]| date=24 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=HHMI_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen Scientists Are Helping Researchers Design New Drugs to Combat COVID-19| url=https://www.hhmi.org/news/citizen-scientists-are-helping-researchers-design-new-drugs-to-combat-covid-19| publisher=[[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]]| date=26 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> These include:\n\n* The Eterna OpenVaccine project enables video game players to \"design an mRNA encoding a potential vaccine against the novel coronavirus.\"<ref name=\"EOV_1\">{{cite web| title=Eterna OpenVaccine| author=Do Soon & the Eterna Developer Team| url=https://eternagame.org/web/news/9818657/| publisher=Eterna| date=23 March 2020| access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* EU-Citizen.Science has (quote): \"A selection of resources related to the current COVID19 pandemic. It contains links to citizen science and crowdsourcing projects\"<ref name=EUCS_1>{{cite web| title=Citizen science resources related to the COVID19 pandemic| author=Lucie Steigleder| url=http://eu-citizen.science/citizen-science-resources-related-to-the-covid19-pandemic| publisher=EU-Citizen.Science| date=24 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* COVID-19 Citizen Science is (quote): \"A new initiative by [[University of California, San Francisco]] physician-scientists\" that \"will allow anyone in the world age 18 or over to become a citizen scientist advancing understanding of the disease.\"<ref name=UCSF_1>{{cite web| title=New COVID-19 \u2018Citizen Science\u2019 Initiative Lets Any Adult with a Smartphone Help to Fight Coronavirus| author=Jeff Norris| url=https://www.ucsf.edu/news/2020/03/417026/new-covid-19-citizen-science-initiative-lets-any-adult-smartphone-help-fight|  publisher=The Regents of The University of California| date=30 March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* CoronaReport is (quote): \"A citizen science project which democratizes the reporting on the Coronavirus, and makes these reports accessible to other citizens.\"<ref name=CR_1>{{cite web| title=CoronaReport| url=https://www.coronareport.eu| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CR_2>{{cite web| title=Corona Report App (social media)| url=https://www.facebook.com/coronareportapp| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* COVID Symptom Tracker is a crowdsourced study (quote): \"By using this app you're contributing to advance vital research on COVID-19. The app will be used to study the symptoms of the virus and track how it spreads.\" It has had two million downloads by April 2020.<ref name=CST_1>{{cite web| title=COVID Symptom Tracker| url=https://covid.joinzoe.com| publisher=[[King's College London]]| date=March 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=COCO_1>{{cite web| title=New COVID-19 symptom tracker app helps researchers better understand coronavirus| url=https://www.clickorlando.com/health/2020/04/01/new-covid-19-symptom-tracker-app-helps-researchers-better-understand-coronavirus| author=Gwen Baumgardner| publisher=ClickOrlando.com| date=1 April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Covid Near You (quote): \"Uses crowdsourced data to visualize maps to help citizens and public health agencies identify current and potential hotspots for the recent pandemic coronavirus, COVID-19.\"<ref name=CNY_1>{{cite web| title=Covid Near You| author=CNY team| url=https://www.covidnearyou.org/#!/who-we-are| date=April 2020| access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor Coronavirus studies and information that can help enable CS, many online resources are available through [[Open access]] and [[Open science]] websites.(e.g.<ref name=CUP_1>{{cite web| title=Coronavirus Free Access Collection| url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/browse-subjects/medicine/coronavirus-free-access-collection| publisher=Cambridge University Press| date=2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=SPARC_1>{{cite web| title=The Coronavirus and Open Science: Our reads and Open use cases| url=https://sparceurope.org/coronaopensciencereadsandusecases| publisher=SPARC| date=March 2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=TL_1>{{cite web| title=The Lancet COVID-19 Resource Centre| url=https://www.thelancet.com/coronavirus| publisher=2020 Elsevier Inc.| date=April 2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Wil_1>{{cite web| title=Covid-19: Novel Coronavirus Outbreak| url=https://novel-coronavirus.onlinelibrary.wiley.com| publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc.| date=March 2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Spri_1>{{cite web| title=SARS-CoV-2 and COVID-19| url=https://www.springernature.com/gp/researchers/campaigns/coronavirus| publisher=Springer Nature| date=2020| access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>)\n\n==Around the world ==\n{{also|List of citizen science projects|Citizen science#National and regional portals}} \n===Africa ===\n\n*In [[South Africa]] (SA), CS projects include: the Stream Assessment Scoring System (miniSASS) which \"encourages enhanced catchment management for water security in a climate stressed society.\"<ref name=SASS>{{cite web|title=Healthy Rivers \u2013 Healthy people: Citizen Science for sustainable water management in a climate stressed society|url=http://www.wessa.org.za/what-we-do/water-programme/healthy-rivers-healthy-people.htm|publisher=The Wildlife and Environment Society of South Africa|date=2014|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817021400/http://www.wessa.org.za/what-we-do/water-programme/healthy-rivers-healthy-people.htm|archivedate=17 August 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Snapshot serengeti.jpg|thumb|right|Snapshot Serengeti classifies animals at the [[Serengeti National Park]] in [[Tanzania]]]]\n*Also in SA, \"Members of the public, or 'citizen scientists' are helping researchers from the University of Pretoria to identify Phytophthora species present in the fynbos.\"<ref name=CS_Fynbos>{{cite web|title=Citizen engagement in research to protect fynbos \u2013 and forests|author=Joey Hulbert|url=http://saforestryonline.co.za/articles/citizen-engagement-research-protect-fynbos-forests|publisher=SA Forestry Online|date=10 February 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802102813/http://saforestryonline.co.za/articles/citizen-engagement-research-protect-fynbos-forests/|archivedate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n*In June 2016, citizen science experts from across East Africa gathered in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]] for a symposium organised by the Tropical Biology Association (TBA) in partnership with the Centre for Ecology & Hydrology (CEH). The aim was \"to harness the growing interest and expertise in East Africa to stimulate new ideas and collaborations in citizen science.\" Rosie Trevelyan of the TBA said: \"We need to enhance our knowledge about the status of Africa's species and the threats facing them.  And scientists can't do it all on their own. At the same time, citizen science is an extremely effective way of connecting people more closely to nature and enrolling more people in conservation action\".<ref name=TBA_CEH>{{cite web|title=Citizen science takes a leap forward in East Africa|url=http://www.tropical-biology.org/citizen-science-takes-a-leap-forward-in-east-africa|publisher=Tropical Biology Association|date=June 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712090949/http://www.tropical-biology.org/citizen-science-takes-a-leap-forward-in-east-africa/|archivedate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n*The website [[Zooniverse]] hosts several African CS projects, including: Snapshot Serengeti, Wildcam Gorongosa and Jungle Rhythms.<ref name=Zoo_CS>{{cite web|title=Zooniverse Projects|url=https://www.zooniverse.org/projectspublisher=Zooniverse|publisher=[[Zooniverse]]|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807015915/https://www.zooniverse.org/projectspublisher=Zooniverse|archivedate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Nigeria]] has the Ibadan Bird Club whose to aim is to \"exchange ideas and share knowledge about birds, and get actively involved in the conservation of birds and biodiversity.\"<ref name=IBC>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science and Bird Conservation in Nigeria|url=https://www.africanbirdclub.org/sites/default/files/2013_Bird_Identification_Workshop_Nigeria.pdf|publisher=Nigerian Conservation Foundation|date=March 2014|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017002631/https://www.africanbirdclub.org/sites/default/files/2013_Bird_Identification_Workshop_Nigeria.pdf|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n*In [[Namibia]], Giraffe Spotter.org is \"project that will provide people with an online citizen science platform for giraffes\".<ref name=GS>{{cite web|title=Citizen science project will benefit Africa's giraffes|author=Megan Hamilton|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/environment/citizen-science-project-will-benefit-africa-s-giraffes/article/403071|work=Digital Journal|date=15 September 2014|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822191901/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/environment/citizen-science-project-will-benefit-africa-s-giraffes/article/403071|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n*Within the [[Republic of the Congo]], the territories of an indigenous people have been mapped so that \"the Mbendjele tribe can protect treasured trees from being cut down by logging companies\". An Android open-source app called Sapelli was used by the Mbendjele which helped them map \"their tribal lands and highlighted trees that were important to them, usually for medicinal reasons or religious significance. Congolaise Industrielle des Bois then verified the trees that the tribe documented as valuable and removed them from its cutting schedule. The tribe also documented illegal logging and poaching activities.\"<ref name=Mb_Sapelli>{{cite web|title=Mapping Indigenous Territories in Africa|url=http://www.esri.com/esri-news/arcnews/winter16articles/mapping-indigenous-territories-in-africa|publisher=Esri|date=2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801073639/http://www.esri.com/esri-news/arcnews/winter16articles/mapping-indigenous-territories-in-africa|archivedate=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n*In [[West Africa]], the eradication of the recent outbreak of [[Ebola virus disease]] was partly helped by CS. \"Communities learnt how to assess the risks posed by the disease independently of prior cultural assumptions, and local empiricism allowed cultural rules to be reviewed, suspended or changed as epidemiological facts emerged.\" \"Citizen science is alive and well in all three Ebola-affected countries. And if only a fraction of the international aid directed at rebuilding health systems were to be redirected towards support for citizen science, that might be a fitting memorial to those who died in the epidemic.\"<ref name=WA_Ebola>{{cite web|title=How black bin bags and common sense helped end an epidemic, and what we can learn from it|author=Paul Richards|url=http://africanarguments.org/2016/05/19/how-black-bin-bags-and-common-sense-helped-end-ebola-and-what-we-can-learn-from-it|publisher=African Arguments|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630015128/http://africanarguments.org/2016/05/19/how-black-bin-bags-and-common-sense-helped-end-ebola-and-what-we-can-learn-from-it/|archivedate=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n* The [[Hong Kong Bird Watching Society|Hong Kong Birdwatching Society]] was established in 1957, and is the only local civil society aiming at appreciating and conserving Hong Kong birds and their natural environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hkbws.org.hk/web/eng/index_eng.htm|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u89c0\u9ce5\u6703 Hong Kong Bird Watching Society|website=www.hkbws.org.hk|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> Their bird surveys go back to 1958, and they carry out a number of Citizen Science events such as their yearly sparrow census.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sparrow795.wixsite.com/hkbws-sparrow|title=hkbws-sparrow|website=hkbws-sparrow|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n* The Bird Count India partnership consists of a large number of organizations and groups involved in birdwatching and bird surveys. They coordinate a number of Citizen Science projects such as the Kerala Bird Atlas and Mysore city Bird Atlas that map the distribution and abundance of birds of entire Indian states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birdcount.in/|title=Bird Count India|website=Bird Count India|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n* The Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network, founded in 2011 and consists of more than 16,000 members as of 2019, is a Citizen Science project where [[roadkill]] across Taiwan is photographed and sent to the Endemic Species Research Institute for study. Its primary goal has been to set up an eco-friendly path to mitigate roadkill challenges and popularize national discourse on environmental issues and civil participation in scientific research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://roadkill.tw/|title=\u53f0\u7063\u52d5\u7269\u8def\u6b7b\u89c0\u5bdf\u7db2 Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network {{!}} \u6539\u5584\u8def\u6b7b\u3001\u74b0\u5883\u6559\u80b2\u3001\u5168\u6c11\u79d1\u5b78\u3001\u73cd\u60dc\u751f\u547d|website=roadkill.tw|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> The members of the Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network volunteer to observe the animals\u2019 corpses caused by roadkill or other reasons in Taiwan, and upload pictures and geographic locations of the roadkill to an internet database or send the corpses to the Endemic Species Research for making specimen. Because the members come from different areas of the island, the collection of data could serve as an animal distribution map of the island. According to the geographical data and pictures of dead animals collected by the members, the community itself and the sponsor the Endemic Species Center could find out the hotspots and the reasons of animals\u2019 death. One of the most renowned case is that the community successfully detected rabies cases due to the massively collected data and the corpse of Melogale moschata have been accumulated for years and alarmed the government authority to take actions to prevent the prevalence of rabies in Taiwan immediately. Another case in 2014 that some citizen scientists discovered birds that died from unknown causes near an agricultural area, then Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network cooperated with National Pingtung University of Science and Technology and engaged citizen scientists to collect bird carcass. The volunteers collected 250 bird corpses for laboratory tests, which con\ufb01rmed that the bird deaths were attributable to the pesticides used on crops. This prompted the Taiwanese government to restrict pesticides, and the Bill of Pesticide Management amendment, establishing a pesticide control system, was passed after the third reading in the Legislative Yuan. The results indicated that Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network developed a set of shared working methods and jointly completed certain actions. Furthermore, the community of Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network have made real changes on road resign to avoid roadkill, improved the management of usage of pesticide, epidemic prevention, and so on.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hsu|first=Chia-Hsuan|last2=Lin|first2=Te-En|last3=Fang|first3=Wei-Ta|last4=Liu|first4=Chi-Chang|date=2018-10-10|title=Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network: An Example of a Community of Practice Contributing to Taiwanese Environmental Literacy for Sustainability|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/328208270|journal=Sustainability|volume=10|issue=10|pages=3610|doi=10.3390/su10103610}}</ref>\n*The AirBox Project was launched in Taiwan to create a participatory ecosystem with a focus on PM2.5 monitoring with AirBox devices. At the end of 2014, the public paid more attention to the PM2.5 level because the air pollution problem became worse, especially in central and southern Taiwan. High PM2.5 level is harmful to our health, such as respiratory problems, so it aroused public concerns and led to an intensive debate about air pollution sources. Some experts indicated that the air quality was affected by pollutants from Mainland China, while some environmentalists believed that it is the result of industrialization such as exhaust fumes from local power plants or factories; however, no one knew the answer because of insufficient data. Dr. Ling-Jyh Chen, a researcher of the Institute of Information Science, Academia Sinica, launched The AirBox Project. His original idea is inspired by a popular Taiwanese slogan Save Your Environment by Yourself. As an expert in Participatory Sensing System, he decided to take this bottom-up approach to collect PM2.5 level data, and through open data and data analysis to have a better understanding of the possible air pollution source. In this ecosystem, massive data was collected from the AirBox device. Data was instantly revealed online to inform people of PM2.5 level so that they take proper action, such as wearing a mask or staying at home, to prevent themselves from directly exploring to polluted environment. Data could be also analyzed to understand the possible sources of pollution and provide recommendations for improving the situation. To be precise, there are four main steps in this project. '''I)''' Develop the AirBox device. Developing a device that could correctly collect the data of the PM2.5 level was time-consuming. It took more than three years to develop AirBox that can be easily used, but with both high accuracy and low cost. '''II)''' Broad installation of AirBox. In the beginning, very few people were willing to install it at their homes because of their concerns about the possible harm to their health, power-consuming problem and maintenances of it, so that AirBoxs were only installed in a relatively small area. Thanks to the help from Taiwan's LASS (Location Aware Sensing System) community, AirBox appeared in all parts of Taiwan. As of February 2017, there are more than 1,600 Air Boxes installed in more than 27 countries. '''III)''' Open Source and Data Analysis. All measurement results were released and visualized in real-time to the public through different media, such as [https://pm25.lass-net.org/ their website] and [https://www.facebook.com/groups/pm25opendata/ Facebook page]. Data can be analyzed to trace pollution sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://research.sinica.edu.tw/pm25-air-box/|title=\u7a7a\u6c23\u76d2\u5b50\u63a8\u624b\uff1a\u7a7a\u6c23\u8b8a\u9ad2\u4e86\uff0c\u96e3\u9053\u6c92\u6709\u8fa6\u6cd5\u55ce\uff1f\u2502\u7814\u4e4b\u6709\u7269 - \u4e2d\u592e\u7814\u7a76\u9662\u8cc7\u6599\u79d1\u5b78\u7814\u7a76|date=2017-02-16|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n*Japan has a long history of citizen science involvement, the 1,200-year-old tradition of collecting records on [[cherry blossom]] flowering probably being the world's longest-running citizen science project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technology.org/2015/03/25/cherry-blossom-season-emperors-sake-and-citizen-science/|title=Cherry blossom season, Emperor's sake and Citizen Science|date=25 March 2015|website=Technology Org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref> One of the most influential citizen science projects has also come out of Japan: [[Safecast (organization)|Safecast]]. Dedicated to open citizen science for the environment, Safecast was established in the wake of the [[Fukushima nuclear disaster]], and produces open hardware sensors for radiation and air-pollution mapping. Presenting this data via a global open data network and maps<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.safecast.org/|title=Safecast|website=Safecast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\n===South America ===\n[[File:Ashaninca children in school.jpg|thumb|right|Ash\u00e1ninka children in school]]\n*In 2015 the [[Ash\u00e1ninka people]] from Apiwtxa, which crosses the border between [[Brazil]] and [[Peru]], began using the Android app Sapelli to monitor their land. The Ashaninka have \"faced historical pressures of disease, exploitation and displacement, and today still face the illegal invasion of their lands by loggers and hunters. This monitoring project shows how the Apiwtxa Ashaninka from the Kampa do Rio Am\u00f4nia Indigenous Territory, Brazil, are beginning to use smartphones and technological tools to monitor these illegal activities more effectively.\"<ref name=Ash_Api>{{cite web|title=Ashaninka Land Monitoring Initiative|url=http://forestcompass.org/case-studies/ashaninka-land-monitoring-initiative|publisher=Global Canopy Programme|date=April 2016|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423075020/http://forestcompass.org/case-studies/ashaninka-land-monitoring-initiative|archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref>\n*In [[Argentina]], two smartphone [[Android (operating system)|Android]] applications are available for CS. '''i)''' AppEAR has been developed at the Institute of [[Limnology]] and was launched in May 2016.<ref name=AppEAR>{{cite web|title=AppEAR: una aplicaci\u00f3n para estudiar ambientes acu\u00e1ticos con colaboraci\u00f3n ciudadana|author=Marcelo Gisande|url=http://www.conicet.gov.ar/appear-una-aplicacion-para-estudiar-ambientes-acuaticos-con-colaboracion-ciudadana|publisher=CONICET|date=7 June 2016|accessdate=1 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812041610/http://www.conicet.gov.ar/appear-una-aplicacion-para-estudiar-ambientes-acuaticos-con-colaboracion-ciudadana/|archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> Joaqu\u00edn Coachman is a researcher who developed an \"application that appeals to the collaboration of users of mobile devices in collecting data that allow the study of aquatic ecosystems\" (translation).<ref name=AppEAR/> Coachman stated: \"Not much of citizen science in Argentina, just a few more oriented to astronomy specific cases.  As ours is the first.  And I have volunteers from different parts of the country that are interested in joining together to centralize data.  That's great because these types of things require many people participate actively and voluntarily\" (translation).<ref name=AppEAR/> '''ii)''' eBird was launched in 2013, and has so far identified 965 species of birds.<ref name=Arg_ebird>{{cite web|title=Ciencia ciudadana: la cultura de la colaboraci\u00f3n|author=Federico Kukso|url=http://fkukso.com/post/86028119770/ciencia-ciudadana-la-cultura-de-la-colaboraci%C3%B3n|date=2016|accessdate=1 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829065141/http://fkukso.com/post/86028119770/ciencia-ciudadana-la-cultura-de-la-colaboraci%C3%B3n|archivedate=29 August 2016}}</ref> eBird in Argentina is \"developed and managed by the Cornell Lab of Ornithology at [[Cornell University]], one of the most important ornithological institutions in the world, and locally presented recently with the support of the Ministry of Science, Technology and Productive Innovation of the Nation (MINCyT)\" (translation).<ref name=Arg_ebird/>\n*Projects in [[Brazil]] include: '''i)''' Platform and mobile app 'Missions' has been developed by [[IBM]] in their [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] research lab with Brazil's Ministry for Environment and Innovation (BMEI).<ref name=Mission>{{cite news|title=IBM and SAP open up big data platforms for citizen science|author=Kristine A. Wong|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/tech-giants-ibm-sap-citizen-science-big-data|date=27 January 2014|accessdate=2 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826070641/https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/tech-giants-ibm-sap-citizen-science-big-data|archivedate=26 August 2016}}</ref> Sergio Borger, an IBM team lead in S\u00e3o Paulo, devised the crowdsourced approach when BMEI approached the company in 2010. They were looking for a way to create a central repository for the rainforest data.<ref name=Mission/> Users can upload photos of a plant species and its components, enter its characteristics (such as color and size), compare it against a catalog photo and classify it. The classification results are juried by crowdsourced ratings.<ref name=Mission/> '''ii)''' Exoss Citizen Science is a member of Astronomers Without Borders and seeks to explore the southern sky for new meteors and radiants.<ref name=Exoss>{{cite web|title=Exoss Citizen Science|url=http://astronomerswithoutborders.org/my-awb/our-current-affiliates/network.html?id=510|publisher=Astronomy Without Borders|date=July 2015|accessdate=2 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818054051/http://astronomerswithoutborders.org/my-awb/our-current-affiliates/network.html?id=510|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> Users can report meteor fireballs through uploading pictures on to a webpage or by linking to [[YouTube]].<ref name=Exoss/> [[File:Jaguar in Pantanal Brazil 2.jpg|thumb|right|A jaguar in [[Pantanal]]; an example of Brazilian [[biodiversity]].]] '''iii)''' The Information System on Brazilian Biodiversity (SiBBr) was launched in 2014 \"aiming to encourage and facilitate the publication, integration, access and use of information about the biodiversity of the country.\"<ref name=SiBBr>{{cite web|title=SiBBr completes one year with six million records on biodiversity|url=https://www.rnp.br/en/noticias/sibbr-completa-ano-seis-milhoes-registros|publisher=RNP|date=26 November 2015|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920002851/https://www.rnp.br/en/noticias/sibbr-completa-ano-seis-milhoes-registros|archivedate=20 September 2016}}</ref> Their initial goal \"was to gather 2.5 million occurrence records of species from biological collections in Brazil and abroad up to the end of 2016. It is now expected that SiBBr will reach nine million records in 2016.\" Andrea Portela said: \"In 2016, we will begin with the citizen science. They are tools that enable anyone, without any technical knowledge, to participate. With this we will achieve greater engagement with society. People will be able to have more interaction with the platform, contribute and comment on what Brazil has.<ref name=SiBBr/> '''iv)''' The Brazilian Marine Megafauna Project (Iniciativa Pro Mar) is working with the European CSA towards its main goal, which is the \"sensibilization of society for marine life issues\" and concerns about pollution and the over-exploitation of natural resources.<ref name=IPM>{{cite web|title=Brasil Megafauna Marinha|url=http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/profile-supporter_profile/490|publisher=ECSA|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818122208/http://ecsa.citizen-science.net/profile-supporter_profile/490|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> Having started as a project monitoring [[manta ray]], it now extends to [[whale shark]] and educating schools and divers within the Santos area.<ref name=IPM/> Its social media activities include a live streaming of a CS course to help divers identify marine megafauna.<ref name=IPM/> '''v)''' A smartphone app called Plantix has been developed by the [[Leibniz Centre for Agricultural Landscape Research]] (ZALF) which helps Brazilian farmers discover crop diseases quicker and helps fight them more efficiently.<ref name=Zalf>{{cite web|title=Crop protection via smart phone: ZALF and PEAT start new Citizen Science project|url=http://www.zalf.de/en/aktuelles/meldungen_alle/Pages/LSA/Plantix.aspx|publisher=Leibniz-Zentrum f\u00fcr Agrarlandschaftsforschung|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818020517/http://www.zalf.de/en/aktuelles/meldungen_alle/Pages/LSA/Plantix.aspx|archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> Brazil is a very large agricultural exporter, but between 10-30% of crops fail because of disease.<ref name=Zalf/> \"The database currently includes 175 frequently occurring crop diseases and pests as well as 40,000 photos. The identification [[algorithm]] of the app improves with every image which records a success rate of over 90 per cent as of approximately 500 photos per crop disease.\"<ref name=Zalf/> '''vi)''' In an [[Atlantic Ocean]] forest region in Brazil, an effort to map the genetic riches of soil is under way.<ref name=DFD>{{cite web|title=Citizen scientists sift soil for new antibiotics|author=Penny Sarchet|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn26825-citizen-scientists-sift-soil-for-new-antibiotics|publisher=RBI|date=20 January 2015|accessdate=3 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413024228/https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn26825-citizen-scientists-sift-soil-for-new-antibiotics/|archivedate=13 April 2016}}</ref> The Drugs From Dirt initiative, based at the [[Rockefeller University]], seeks to turn up [[bacteria]] that yield new types of antibiotics- the Brazilian region being particularly rich in potentially useful bacterial genes.<ref name=DFD/> Approximately a quarter of the 185 soil samples have been taken by Citizen Scientists without which the project could not run.<ref name=DFD/>\n*In [[Chile]] CS projects include (some websites in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]): '''i)''' Testing new cancer therapies with scientists from the Science Foundation for Life.<ref name=Ch_CS>{{cite web|title=Chilecientifico Ciencia Ciudadana|publisher=Chilecient\u00edfico|url=http://chilecientifico.cl/participar.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628075551/http://chilecientifico.cl/participar.html|archivedate=28 June 2016}}</ref> '''ii)''' Monitoring the population of the Chilean [[bumblebee]].<ref name=BB_FB>{{cite web|title=Saving Chile's bumblebee from extinction|publisher=Bee Safe|url=http://www.bee-safe.eu/save-chiles-bumblebee-from-extinction|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916060258/http://www.bee-safe.eu/save-chiles-bumblebee-from-extinction/|archivedate=16 September 2016}}</ref> '''iii)''' Monitoring the invasive [[Coccinellidae|ladybird]] Chinita arlequ\u00edn.<ref name=Ch_Ar>{{cite web|title=Chinita arlequin: Harmonia axryidis en Chile|author1=A.A. Grez|author2=T. Zaviezo|url=http://www.chinita-arlequin.uchile.cl|publisher=Chinita Arlequ\u00edn en Chile|date=2015|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802030754/http://www.chinita-arlequin.uchile.cl/|archivedate=2 August 2016}}</ref> '''iv)''' Collecting rain water data.<ref name=Ch_RW>{{cite web|title=Pluvi\u00f3metros Ciudadanos|url=http://milluvia.dga.cl/index.php|publisher=Direcci\u00f3n General de Aguas: Ministerio de Obras P\u00fablicas|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820124029/http://milluvia.dga.cl/index.php|archivedate=20 August 2016}}</ref> '''v)''' Monitoring various pollinating [[fly]] populations.<ref name=MFC>{{cite web|title=Moscas Floricholas de Chile|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/774986852548819|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122141323/https://www.facebook.com/groups/774986852548819|archivedate=22 January 2017}}</ref> '''vi)''' Providing information and field data on the abundance and distribution of various species of [[Sebastidae|rockfish]].<ref name=Ch_RFish>{{cite web|title=Lanzamiento Programa Primera Red de Buzos Deportivos para la Conservaci\u00f3n de Peces de Roca|url=http://www.costahumboldt.org/2015/01/27/lanzamiento-programa-primera-red-de-buzos-deportivos-para-la-conservacion-de-peces-de-roca|publisher=Costa Humboldt|date=27 January 2015|accessdate=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008002133/http://www.costahumboldt.org/2015/01/27/lanzamiento-programa-primera-red-de-buzos-deportivos-para-la-conservacion-de-peces-de-roca/|archive-date=8 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:\u00c1rboles en Bogot\u00e1 - Humedal de C\u00f3rdoba Vegetaci\u00f3n.JPG|thumb|right|[[C\u00f3rdoba (wetland)|C\u00f3rdoba wetland]]]]\n*Projects in [[Colombia]] include (some websites in Spanish): '''i)''' The Communications Project of the Humboldt Institute along with the Organization for Education and Environmental Protection initiated projects in the [[Bogot\u00e1]] [[wetlands]] of [[C\u00f3rdoba (wetland)|Cordoba]] and [[El Burro]], which have a lot of [[biodiversity]].<ref name=HI_Wet>{{cite web| title=Concluy\u00f3 proyecto piloto de ciencia ciudadana en humedales de Bogot\u00e1| url=http://www.humboldt.org.co/es/noticias/notas/item/243-concluyo-proyecto-piloto-de-ciencia-ciudadana-en-humedales-de-bogota| publisher=Humboldt Institute| date=2014| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816145953/http://www.humboldt.org.co/es/noticias/notas/item/243-concluyo-proyecto-piloto-de-ciencia-ciudadana-en-humedales-de-bogota| archivedate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=OpEPA>{{cite web| title=Organizaci\u00f3n para la Educaci\u00f3n y Protecci\u00f3n Ambiental| url=http://www.opepa.org| publisher=OpEPA| date=2016| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810092951/http://opepa.org/| archivedate=10 August 2016}}</ref> '''ii)''' In the Model Forest of Risaralda, the Colombia {{lang|es|'proyecto de Ciencia Abierta y Colaborativa'}} promotes citizen participation in research related to how the local environment is adapting to climate change. The first meeting took place in the Flora and Fauna Sanctuary Ot\u00fan Quimbaya.<ref name=PCA>{{cite web| title=Ciencia ciudadana en el Bosque Modelo Risaralda, Colombia| author=Comunicaci\u00f3n RIABM editor| url=http://www.bosquesmodelo.net/ciencia-ciudadana-en-el-bosque-modelo-risaralda-colombia| publisher=Red Iberoamericana de Bosques Modelo| date=4 August 2015| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017063902/http://www.bosquesmodelo.net/ciencia-ciudadana-en-el-bosque-modelo-risaralda-colombia/| archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref> '''iii''') The Citizen Network Environmental Monitoring (CLUSTER), based in the city of [[Bucaramanga]], seeks to engage younger students in [[data science]], who are trained in building weather stations with open repositories based on free software and open hardware data.<ref name=Cluster>{{cite web| title=Red Ambiental Ciudadana de Monitoreo (RACIMO)| url=http://halley.uis.edu.co/tierra/?page_id=143| publisher=Racimo| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809220831/http://halley.uis.edu.co/tierra/?page_id=143| archivedate=9 August 2016}}</ref> '''iv)''' The Symposium on Biodiversity has adapted the CS tool iNaturalist for use in Colombia.<ref name=SIB>{{cite web| title=SIB Report No.2| url=http://www.sibcolombia.net/web/sib/2013-2| publisher=Sistema de informaci\u00f3n sobre Biodiversidad de Colombia| date=2013| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818085623/http://www.sibcolombia.net/web/sib/2013-2| archivedate=18 August 2016}}</ref> '''v)''' The [[Sinchi Amazonic Institute of Scientific Research]] seeks to encourage the development and diffusion of knowledge, values and technologies on the management of natural resources for ethnic groups in the Amazon. This research should further the use of participatory action research schemes and promoting participation communities.<ref name=Si_Inst>{{cite web| title=Funciones del Instituto| url=http://www.sinchi.org.co/index.php/funciones| publisher=The Sinchi Institute| accessdate=30 July 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820091926/http://www.sinchi.org.co/index.php/funciones| archivedate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n*Since 2010, the Pacific Biodiversity Institute (PBI) seeks \"volunteers to help identify, describe and protect wildland complexes and roadless areas in South America\". The PBI \"are engaged in an ambitious project with our Latin American conservation partners to map all the wildlands in South America, to evaluate their contribution to global biodiversity and to share and disseminate this information.\"<ref name=PBI>{{cite web|title=Citizen Science Volunteers needed for mapping South American Wetlands|url=http://www.pacificbio.org/helpout/volunteer-south-america.html|publisher=Pacific Biodiversity Institute|accessdate=20 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827190519/http://www.pacificbio.org/helpout/volunteer-south-america.html|archivedate=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Conferences==\n\nThe first Conference on Public Participation in Scientific Research was held in Portland, Oregon in August 2012.<ref name=\"Rosner2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Rosner |first1=Hillary |title=Data on Wings |journal=Scientific American |date=14 January 2013 |volume=308 |issue=2 |pages=68\u201373 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0213-68 |pmid=23367787 |bibcode=2013SciAm.308b..68R }}</ref> Citizen science is now often a theme at large conferences, such as the annual meeting of the [[American Geophysical Union]].<ref name=AGU_Meeting>{{cite web|title=ED51A. Era of Citizen Science: Intersection of Outreach, Scientific Research and Big Data I Posters|url=http://fallmeeting.agu.org/2013/scientific-program-2/session-search/sessions/ed51a-era-of-citizen-science-intersection-of-outreach-scientific-research-and-big-data-i-posters|publisher=American Geophysical Union|date=13 December 2013|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409001310/http://fallmeeting.agu.org/2013/scientific-program-2/session-search/sessions/ed51a-era-of-citizen-science-intersection-of-outreach-scientific-research-and-big-data-i-posters/|archivedate=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, 2012 and 2014 there were three Citizen Cybersience summits, organised by the [[Citizen Cyberscience Centre]] in [[Geneva]] and [[University College London]].<ref name=CitCyb>{{cite web| title=Citizen Cyberscience Summit (2014 - 2012 - 2010)| url=http://www.citizencyberlab.org/events.html#one| publisher=CERN, unitar, Universite de Geneve| access-date=17 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604171916/http://citizencyberlab.org/events.html#one| archivedate=4 June 2016}}</ref> The 2014 summit was hosted in [[London]] and attracted over 300 participants.<ref name=CitCyb/>\n\nIn January 2015, the [[ETH Z\u00fcrich]] and [[University of Z\u00fcrich]] hosted an international meeting on the \"Challenges and Opportunities in Citizen Science\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsb.ethz.ch/news-and-events/events/citizenscienceworkshop/Program.html|title=Program|work=ethz.ch|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103001056/http://www.imsb.ethz.ch/news-and-events/events/citizenscienceworkshop/Program.html|archivedate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first citizen science conference hosted by the Citizen Science Association was in San Jose, California, in February 2015 in partnership with the AAAS conference.<ref name=CSA_Feb2015>{{cite web|title=Conference 11\u201312 February, San Jose, California, USA|url=http://citizenscienceassociation.org/conference|publisher=Citizen Science Association|accessdate=15 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915231307/http://citizenscienceassociation.org/conference/|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The Citizen Science Association conference, CitSci 2017, was held in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], [[Minnesota]], United States, between 17 and 20 May 2017. The conference had more than 600 attendees.<ref name=Conf_2>{{cite web| title=2017 CSA Top Ten Year in Review| url=http://citizenscience.org/2017/12/28/2017-csa-top-ten-year-in-review| publisher=The Citizen Science Association| date=2017| accessdate=16 January 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229010851/http://citizenscience.org/2017/12/28/2017-csa-top-ten-year-in-review/| archivedate=29 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=CSA_Conf>{{cite web|title=CitSci2017: May 17\u201320th in Saint Paul, Minnesota|url=http://citizenscience.org/2016/07/13/citsci2017-may-17-20th-in-saint-paul-minnesota|publisher=Citizen Science Association|date=13 July 2016|accessdate=1 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017063905/http://citizenscience.org/2016/07/13/citsci2017-may-17-20th-in-saint-paul-minnesota/|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref> The next CitSci is in March 2019 in [[Raleigh]], USA.<ref name=Conf_2/>\n\nThe platform \"\u00d6sterreich forscht\" hosts the annual [[Austria]]n citizen science conference since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizen-science.at/eventarchiv|title=Eventarchiv|website=Citizen Science Platform \"\u00d6sterreich forscht\"|access-date=31 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017004036/http://www.citizen-science.at/eventarchiv|archivedate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Columns-list|\n* {{annotated link|Genealogy}}\n* {{annotated link|Independent scientist}}\n* {{annotated link|Independent scholar}}\n* {{annotated link|List of citizen science projects}}\n* {{annotated link|List of distributed computing projects}}\n* {{annotated link|Open science}}\n* {{annotated link|Open-source intelligence}}\n* {{annotated link|Open-Source Lab (book)}}\n* {{annotated link|Outsider art}} (produced by artists that are non-institutionalized, in the same way as citizen scientists)\n* {{annotated link|Public participation (decision making)}}\n* {{annotated link|Reinventing Discovery}}\n* {{annotated link|Popular science}}\n* {{annotated link|Public participation}}\n* {{annotated link|Scientific instrument}}\n* {{annotated link|Virtual volunteering}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite web|website=The Conversation|url=https://theconversation.com/as-heat-strikes-heres-one-way-to-help-fight-disease-carrying-and-nuisance-mosquitoes-128466|title=As heat strikes, here's one way to help fight disease-carrying and nuisance mosquitoes|first1=Cameron|last1=Web|first2=Craig|last2=Williams|first3=Larissa Braz|last3=Sousa|first4=Seamus|last4= Doherty|first5=Stephen 