{"title_page": "Ali Shilatifard", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image       =          Dr. Ali Shilatifard, scientist, biochemist.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  =         <!--{{birth date |1966}}-->\n| birth_place =         <!--{{birth place |Tehran, Iran}}-->\n| death_date  =         <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields      = \n| workplaces  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Northwestern University Feinberg School of Medicine]]\n* [[Stowers Institute for Medical Research]],\n* [[St. Louis University School of Medicine]]\n}}\n| education   = \n| alma_mater  = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Georgia|University of Georgia, Athens]]\n*[[University of Oklahoma College of Medicine]]\n* [[Kennesaw State University]]\n}}\n| known_for   = \n| awards      = Elected Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS)\nASBMB-AMGEN Award<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pinholster|first1=Ginger|title=2016 AAAS Fellows Honored for Advancing Science to Serve Society|url=https://www.aaas.org/news/2016-aaas-fellows-honored-advancing-science-serve-society|website=AAAS|publisher=AAAS|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n| spouse      =         Laura Shilatifard \n| children    = 4\n}}\n'''Ali Shilatifard''' is an American [[biochemist]]/[[molecular biologist]], the [[Robert F. Furchgott|Robert Francis Furchgott]] Professor and Chairman of the department of biochemistry and molecular genetics, and the director of the Simpson Querrey Center for Epigenetics<ref>{{cite web|title=Northwestern Receives $10 Million for Epigenetics Center|url=https://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/northwestern-receives-10-million-for-epigenetics-center|website=Philanthropy News Digest|publisher=Foundation Center|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> at the [[Northwestern University Feinberg School of Medicine]]. He has served as a senior editor for the journal ''Science'', and currently serves as the Editor for ''Science''<nowiki/>'s open access journal ''[[Science Advances]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://advances.sciencemag.org/content/editorial-board|title=Editorial Board {{!}} Science Advances|website=advances.sciencemag.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shilatifard |first1=Ali |title=Impactful science as the guiding principle |journal=Science Advances |volume=4 |issue=7 |pages=eaau1696 |pmid=29978047  |pmc=6031368 |year=2018 |doi=10.1126/sciadv.aau1696 }}</ref> Research in Shilatifard's lab focuses on the cause of childhood leukemia through chromosomal translocations, the role of [[ELL (gene)|ELL]] in this process, and the discovery of the Super Elongation Complex as being a central complex linking [[MLL (gene)|MLL]] translocations into a diverse number of genes to leukemic pathogenesis.\n\n== Biography ==\nShilatifard has said he developed his love of science as a young boy working with and observing his grandfather,<ref name=\"STL biz journal\">[http://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/stories/2006/07/24/focus19.html Ali Shilatifard: Discovering the roots of cancer, St. Louis Business Journal, Jul 23, 2006]</ref> a physician/scientist and professor of medicine of the [[University of Tehran]].   Shilatifard moved to the United States in 1984 where he began his study of organic chemistry at [[Kennesaw State University]] in Georgia.  He began to work on his doctoral degree in biochemistry at the [[University of Georgia| University of Georgia, Athens]]. Shilatifard completed his Ph.D. from the [[University of Oklahoma]] where his mentor, Dr. [[Richard D. Cummings|Richard Cummings]], had moved his program.  As a [[Jane Coffin Childs Memorial Fund for Medical Research|Jane Coffin Childs Postdoctoral Fellow]] at the Oklahoma Medical Research Foundation, Shilatifard identified the first function of any of the MLL translocation partners found in leukemia<ref name=\"ASH1996\">{{cite journal| pmid=8596958 | volume=271 | issue=5257 | title=An RNA polymerase II elongation factor encoded by the human ELL gene | date=March 1996 | journal=Science | pages=1873\u20136 | last1 = Shilatifard | first1 = A | last2 = Lane | first2 = WS | last3 = Jackson | first3 = KW | last4 = Conaway | first4 = RC | last5 = Conaway | first5 = JW | doi=10.1126/science.271.5257.1873| bibcode=1996Sci...271.1873S }}</ref> and proposed that transcriptional elongation control is central to leukemia pathogenesis. Shilatifard began his independent lab in the Edward A. Doisy Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology at the St. Louis University School of Medicine, where he identified the first histone H3 lysine 4 (H3K4) methylase in ''[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae]]'': which he named Set1/COMPASS;<ref name=\"Miller2001\">{{cite journal | last1 = Miller | first1 = T. |display-authors=et al | year = 2001 | title = COMPASS: a complex of proteins associated with a trithorax-related SET domain protein | url = | journal = Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A | volume = 98 | issue = 23| pages = 12902\u201312907 | doi=10.1073/pnas.231473398| bibcode = 2001PNAS...9812902M | pmc = 60797 | pmid=11687631}}</ref><ref name=\"Krogan2002\">{{cite journal | last1 = Krogan | first1 = N. J. |display-authors=et al | year = 2002| title = COMPASS, a histone H3 (Lysine 4) methyltransferase required for telomeric silencing of gene expression | url = | journal = J Biol Chem | volume = 277 | issue = 13| pages = 10753\u201310755 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.C200023200 | pmid=11805083| doi-access = free }}</ref> and defined the pathway of histone H3K4 methylation which is highly conserved from yeast to human.<ref name=\"Smith2010\">{{cite journal | last1 = Smith | first1 = E. | last2 = Shilatifard | first2 = A. | year = 2010| title = The chromatin signaling pathway: diverse mechanisms of recruitment of histone-modifying enzymes and varied biological outcomes | journal = Mol Cell | volume = 40 | issue = 5| pages = 689\u2013701 | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2010.11.031 | pmid = 21145479 | pmc=3037032}}</ref><ref name=\"Lee2007\">{{cite journal | last1 = Lee | first1 = J. S. |display-authors=et al | year = 2007| title = Histone crosstalk between H2B monoubiquitination and H3 methylation mediated by COMPASS | url = | journal = Cell | volume = 131 | issue = 6| pages = 1084\u20131096 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2007.09.046 }}</ref> Studies from Shilatifard\u2019s laboratory linking epigenetic factors and transcription elongation control to malignancies have provided therapeutic approaches for the treatment of these cancers.<ref name=pmid28263307>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nm.4296 |pmid=28263307 |title=Therapeutic targeting of polycomb and BET bromodomain proteins in diffuse intrinsic pontine gliomas |journal=Nature Medicine |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=493 |year=2017 |last1=Piunti |first1=Andrea |last2=Hashizume |first2=Rintaro |last3=Morgan |first3=Marc A |last4=Bartom |first4=Elizabeth T |last5=Horbinski |first5=Craig M |last6=Marshall |first6=Stacy A |last7=Rendleman |first7=Emily J |last8=Ma |first8=Quanhong |last9=Takahashi |first9=Yoh-hei |last10=Woodfin |first10=Ashley R |last11=Misharin |first11=Alexander V |last12=Abshiru |first12=Nebiyu A |last13=Lulla |first13=Rishi R |last14=Saratsis |first14=Amanda M |last15=Kelleher |first15=Neil L |last16=James |first16=C David |last17=Shilatifard |first17=Ali |pmc=5667640}}</ref><ref name=pmid28065413>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2016.12.011 |pmid=28065413 |pmc=5351781 |title=Therapeutic Targeting of MLL Degradation Pathways in MLL-Rearranged Leukemia |journal=Cell |volume=168 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=59\u201372.e13 |year=2017 |last1=Liang |first1=Kaiwei |last2=Volk |first2=Andrew G |last3=Haug |first3=Jeffrey S |last4=Marshall |first4=Stacy A |last5=Woodfin |first5=Ashley R |last6=Bartom |first6=Elizabeth T |last7=Gilmore |first7=Joshua M |last8=Florens |first8=Laurence |last9=Washburn |first9=Michael P |last10=Sullivan |first10=Kelly D |last11=Espinosa |first11=Joaquin M |last12=Cannova |first12=Joseph |last13=Zhang |first13=Jiwang |last14=Smith |first14=Edwin R |last15=Crispino |first15=John D |last16=Shilatifard |first16=Ali }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Lu|last2=Zhao|first2=Zibo|last3=Ozark|first3=Patrick A.|last4=Fantini|first4=Damiano|last5=Marshall|first5=Stacy A.|last6=Rendleman|first6=Emily J.|last7=Cozzolino|first7=Kira A.|last8=Louis|first8=Nundia|last9=He|first9=Xingyao|date=2018-05-21|title=Resetting the epigenetic balance of Polycomb and COMPASS function at enhancers for cancer therapy|journal=Nature Medicine|volume=24|issue=6|pages=758\u2013769|doi=10.1038/s41591-018-0034-6|issn=1546-170X|pmid=29785026|pmc=6055231}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2019, Shilatifard presented \"Childhood Leukemia: On the Edge of Extinction!\"  at [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx]]UofIChicago<ref>{{cite web |title=TEDxUofIChicago |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/31267 |website=ted.com |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{PubMedAuthorSearch|Shilatifard|A}}\n* {{Google Scholar id|M-pazfcAAAAJ}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shilatifard, Ali}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American biochemists]]\n[[Category:American molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:Kennesaw State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oklahoma alumni]]\n[[Category:Iranian biochemists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image       =          Dr. Ali Shilatifard, scientist, biochemist.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  =         <!--{{birth date |1966}}-->\n| birth_place =         <!--{{birth place |Tehran, Iran}}-->\n| death_date  =         <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields      = \n| workplaces  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Northwestern University Feinberg School of Medicine]]\n* [[Stowers Institute for Medical Research]],\n* [[St. Louis University School of Medicine]]\n}}\n| education   = \n| alma_mater  = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Georgia|University of Georgia, Athens]]\n*[[University of Oklahoma College of Medicine]]\n* [[Kennesaw State University]]\n}}\n| known_for   = \n| awards      = Elected Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS)\nASBMB-AMGEN Award<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pinholster|first1=Ginger|title=2016 AAAS Fellows Honored for Advancing Science to Serve Society|url=https://www.aaas.org/news/2016-aaas-fellows-honored-advancing-science-serve-society|website=AAAS|publisher=AAAS|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n| spouse      =         Laura Shilatifard \n| children    = 4\n}}\n'''Ali Shilatifard''' is an American [[biochemist]]/[[molecular biologist]], the [[Robert F. Furchgott|Robert Francis Furchgott]] Professor and Chairman of the department of biochemistry and molecular genetics, and the director of the Simpson Query Center for Epigenetics<ref>{{cite web|title=Northwestern Receives $10 Million for Epigenetics Center|url=https://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/northwestern-receives-10-million-for-epigenetics-center|website=Philanthropy News Digest|publisher=Foundation Center|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> at the [[Northwestern University Feinberg School of Medicine]]. He has served as a senior editor for the journal ''Science'', and currently serves as the Editor for ''Science''<nowiki/>'s open access journal ''[[Science Advances]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://advances.sciencemag.org/content/editorial-board|title=Editorial Board {{!}} Science Advances|website=advances.sciencemag.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shilatifard |first1=Ali |title=Impactful science as the guiding principle |journal=Science Advances |volume=4 |issue=7 |pages=eaau1696 |pmid=29978047  |pmc=6031368 |year=2018 |doi=10.1126/sciadv.aau1696 }}</ref> Research in Shilatifard's lab focuses on the cause of childhood leukemia through chromosomal translocations, the role of [[ELL (gene)|ELL]] in this process, and the discovery of the Super Elongation Complex as being a central complex linking [[MLL (gene)|MLL]] translocations into a diverse number of genes to leukemic pathogenesis.\n\n== Biography ==\nShilatifard has said he developed his love of science as a young boy working with and observing his grandfather,<ref name=\"STL biz journal\">[http://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/stories/2006/07/24/focus19.html Ali Shilatifard: Discovering the roots of cancer, St. Louis Business Journal, Jul 23, 2006]</ref> a physician/scientist and professor of medicine of the [[University of Tehran]].   Shilatifard moved to the United States in 1984 where he began his study of organic chemistry at [[Kennesaw State University]] in Georgia.  He began to work on his doctoral degree in biochemistry at the [[University of Georgia| University of Georgia, Athens]]. Shilatifard completed his Ph.D. from the [[University of Oklahoma]] where his mentor, Dr. [[Richard D. Cummings|Richard Cummings]], had moved his program.  As a [[Jane Coffin Childs Memorial Fund for Medical Research|Jane Coffin Childs Postdoctoral Fellow]] at the Oklahoma Medical Research Foundation, Shilatifard identified the first function of any of the MLL translocation partners found in leukemia<ref name=\"ASH1996\">{{cite journal| pmid=8596958 | volume=271 | issue=5257 | title=An RNA polymerase II elongation factor encoded by the human ELL gene | date=March 1996 | journal=Science | pages=1873\u20136 | last1 = Shilatifard | first1 = A | last2 = Lane | first2 = WS | last3 = Jackson | first3 = KW | last4 = Conaway | first4 = RC | last5 = Conaway | first5 = JW | doi=10.1126/science.271.5257.1873| bibcode=1996Sci...271.1873S }}</ref> and proposed that transcriptional elongation control is central to leukemia pathogenesis. Shilatifard began his independent lab in the Edward A. Doisy Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology at the St. Louis University School of Medicine, where he identified the first histone H3 lysine 4 (H3K4) methylase in ''[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae]]'': which he named Set1/COMPASS;<ref name=\"Miller2001\">{{cite journal | last1 = Miller | first1 = T. |display-authors=et al | year = 2001 | title = COMPASS: a complex of proteins associated with a trithorax-related SET domain protein | url = | journal = Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A | volume = 98 | issue = 23| pages = 12902\u201312907 | doi=10.1073/pnas.231473398| bibcode = 2001PNAS...9812902M | pmc = 60797 | pmid=11687631}}</ref><ref name=\"Krogan2002\">{{cite journal | last1 = Krogan | first1 = N. J. |display-authors=et al | year = 2002| title = COMPASS, a histone H3 (Lysine 4) methyltransferase required for telomeric silencing of gene expression | url = | journal = J Biol Chem | volume = 277 | issue = 13| pages = 10753\u201310755 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.C200023200 | pmid=11805083| doi-access = free }}</ref> and defined the pathway of histone H3K4 methylation which is highly conserved from yeast to human.<ref name=\"Smith2010\">{{cite journal | last1 = Smith | first1 = E. | last2 = Shilatifard | first2 = A. | year = 2010| title = The chromatin signaling pathway: diverse mechanisms of recruitment of histone-modifying enzymes and varied biological outcomes | journal = Mol Cell | volume = 40 | issue = 5| pages = 689\u2013701 | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2010.11.031 | pmid = 21145479 | pmc=3037032}}</ref><ref name=\"Lee2007\">{{cite journal | last1 = Lee | first1 = J. S. |display-authors=et al | year = 2007| title = Histone crosstalk between H2B monoubiquitination and H3 methylation mediated by COMPASS | url = | journal = Cell | volume = 131 | issue = 6| pages = 1084\u20131096 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2007.09.046 }}</ref> Studies from Shilatifard\u2019s laboratory linking epigenetic factors and transcription elongation control to malignancies have provided therapeutic approaches for the treatment of these cancers.<ref name=pmid28263307>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nm.4296 |pmid=28263307 |title=Therapeutic targeting of polycomb and BET bromodomain proteins in diffuse intrinsic pontine gliomas |journal=Nature Medicine |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=493 |year=2017 |last1=Piunti |first1=Andrea |last2=Hashizume |first2=Rintaro |last3=Morgan |first3=Marc A |last4=Bartom |first4=Elizabeth T |last5=Horbinski |first5=Craig M |last6=Marshall |first6=Stacy A |last7=Rendleman |first7=Emily J |last8=Ma |first8=Quanhong |last9=Takahashi |first9=Yoh-hei |last10=Woodfin |first10=Ashley R |last11=Misharin |first11=Alexander V |last12=Abshiru |first12=Nebiyu A |last13=Lulla |first13=Rishi R |last14=Saratsis |first14=Amanda M |last15=Kelleher |first15=Neil L |last16=James |first16=C David |last17=Shilatifard |first17=Ali |pmc=5667640}}</ref><ref name=pmid28065413>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2016.12.011 |pmid=28065413 |pmc=5351781 |title=Therapeutic Targeting of MLL Degradation Pathways in MLL-Rearranged Leukemia |journal=Cell |volume=168 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=59\u201372.e13 |year=2017 |last1=Liang |first1=Kaiwei |last2=Volk |first2=Andrew G |last3=Haug |first3=Jeffrey S |last4=Marshall |first4=Stacy A |last5=Woodfin |first5=Ashley R |last6=Bartom |first6=Elizabeth T |last7=Gilmore |first7=Joshua M |last8=Florens |first8=Laurence |last9=Washburn |first9=Michael P |last10=Sullivan |first10=Kelly D |last11=Espinosa |first11=Joaquin M |last12=Cannova |first12=Joseph |last13=Zhang |first13=Jiwang |last14=Smith |first14=Edwin R |last15=Crispino |first15=John D |last16=Shilatifard |first16=Ali }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Lu|last2=Zhao|first2=Zibo|last3=Ozark|first3=Patrick A.|last4=Fantini|first4=Damiano|last5=Marshall|first5=Stacy A.|last6=Rendleman|first6=Emily J.|last7=Cozzolino|first7=Kira A.|last8=Louis|first8=Nundia|last9=He|first9=Xingyao|date=2018-05-21|title=Resetting the epigenetic balance of Polycomb and COMPASS function at enhancers for cancer therapy|journal=Nature Medicine|volume=24|issue=6|pages=758\u2013769|doi=10.1038/s41591-018-0034-6|issn=1546-170X|pmid=29785026|pmc=6055231}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2019, Shilatifard presented \"Childhood Leukemia: On the Edge of Extinction!\"  at [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx]]UofIChicago<ref>{{cite web |title=TEDxUofIChicago |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/31267 |website=ted.com |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{PubMedAuthorSearch|Shilatifard|A}}\n* {{Google Scholar id|M-pazfcAAAAJ}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shilatifard, Ali}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American biochemists]]\n[[Category:American molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:Kennesaw State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oklahoma alumni]]\n[[Category:Iranian biochemists]]\n", "name_user": "68.129.149.217", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_Shilatifard"}
{"title_page": "Carolina Crown Drum and Bugle Corps", "text_new": "{{Infobox drums corps\n| name= Carolina Crown<br />Drum and Bugle Corps\n| logo= Carolina Crown Drum and Bugle Corps.png\n| logo_size      = 240px\n| location=[[Fort Mill, South Carolina]], United States\n| division=World Class\n| founded=1988\n| director=Jim Coates\n| titles=1993 (Div. II)<br />2013 (World Class)\n| uniform=(2018) Metallic jacket with scale pattern and drapes on the sleeves<br />Black pants <br />Frontal green fabric covering middle of body<br />Black shoes<br />Three triangle helmet with and opening and an orange strap on top [[shako]]\n| website        = {{URL|www.carolinacrown.org}}\n}}\n'''Carolina Crown Drum and Bugle Corps''' is a World Class competitive junior [[drum and bugle corps (modern)|drum and bugle corps]]. Based in [[Fort Mill, South Carolina]], United States, Carolina Crown is a member corps of [[Drum Corps International]] (DCI).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dci.org/corps |title=Corps |publisher=Drum Corps International |date= |accessdate=24 February 2018 }}</ref> On August 10, 2013, Carolina Crown won the [[Drum Corps International World Class Champions|2013 DCI World Class Championship]], the first former Open Class/Division II corps to do so.\n\n[[File:Carolina Crown Drum and Bugle Corps march in the Bristol Rhode Island July 4th Parade 2017.jpg|thumb|Carolina Crown Drum and Bugle Corps marches in the [[Bristol Fourth of July Parade|Bristol, Rhode Island Fourth of July Parade]] in 2017.]]\n\n==History==\nThe Carolina Crown organization was founded in 1988 as the Charlotte Drum Corps Association, a group of local drum corps fans who gathered on an irregular basis to talk about drum corps and watch drum corps video. After organizing themselves with Bill Loelius as president, Kevin Smith as vice president, and Luanne Bialecki as Secretary-Treasurer, the group hosted two drum corps shows, Southern Gold Classic at [[Davidson College]] and NightBEAT at Charlotte's Memorial Stadium. Southern Gold Classic drew a small audience and lost money. NightBEAT was much better attended, but the group was unable to pay the stadium rental. When NightBEAT Chairperson Doug Madar, Bill Loelius, and Kevin Smith met with Charlotte Parks & Recreation Department Superintendent Marvin Billups to discuss working out some sort of payment schedule, they were surprised when Billups not only wrote off the bill for the 1988 NightBEAT but offered the Department's sponsorship for future shows. In 1989, a gift of $1000 was offered by the Queen City [[Optimist International|Optimists]] with the proviso that the organization start a performance group; after discussions initially centered on starting a drumline, Carolina Crown Drum and Bugle Corps was born.<ref name=\"crown\">{{Cite web |url=http://carolinacrown.org/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83&Itemid=96# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823050834/http://carolinacrown.org/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=83&Itemid=96# |archive-date=2008-08-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"reps\">[http://www.corpsreps.com/corpsreps.cfm?view=corpshist&corps=43&corpstype=Junior corpsreps.com - The Drum Corps Repertoire Database<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\"hist\">A History of Drum & Bugle Corps, Vol. 2; Steve Vickers, ed.; Drum Corps World, 2003</ref>\n\nAfter the corps bought a complete set of drums from a defunct drum and bugle corps only to discover that they were seriously damaged, John Cummings of [[Ludwig-Musser|Ludwig Drums]] offered to repair the drums as part of an informal sponsorship of the corps. The name Carolina Crown was adopted to recognize the groups' desire to represent the Carolinas region while still recognizing Charlotte, the Queen City, which has a crown in its logo. The leadership group met, in the fall of 1989, with several young band directors who were also alumni of Suncoast Sound, [[Spirit Drum and Bugle Corps|Spirit of Atlanta]], and the [[Madison Scouts Drum and Bugle Corps|Madison Scouts]] drum and bugle corps to tell them of their efforts to start a new local corps. From this group, Don Taylor, Cecil Adderley, Bill Register, and Van Mathews volunteered to be the corps' first instructors. After locating and purchasing the horns of the defunct California Dons, Carolina Crown began recruiting members. The corps also formed a partnership with the Mecklenburg Council of the [[Boy Scouts of America]] as Explorer Post #588, which aided them in finding school space for auditions and practices.<ref name=\"crown\"/><ref name=\"reps\"/><ref name=\"hist\"/>\n\nIn 1990, fielding a corps of only sixty-one members, Carolina Crown elected to compete in the Open Class (now known as World Class) in DCI. However, not only was the corps out-classed by the other, larger corps in Open Class, but it was also bested in DCI prelims by seven corps that had advanced from Classes A and A60, finishing thirty-third of 33 corps at their first DCI World Championships in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fromthepressbox.com/19900815div1prelims.htm# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-12-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023175801/http://www.fromthepressbox.com/19900815div1prelims.htm# |archive-date=2014-10-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1991, the corps dropped down to Class A. At the DCI Championships in [[Dallas]], Carolina Crown finished in second place in Class A and advanced to Open Class prelims, where they placed twenty-fifth, earning DCI Associate membership. Carolina Crown was third in the 1992 Division II championship in [[Whitewater, Wisconsin]], once more finishing in twenty-fifth place in Division I (which had been renamed from Open Class) prelims in [[Madison, Wisconsin]]. At the 1993 DCI Championships in [[Jackson, Mississippi]], Carolina Crown won the Division II Championship title and finished in twenty-first place in Division I prelims.<ref name=\"crown\"/><ref name=\"reps\"/><ref name=\"hist\"/>\n\nAfter winning Division II in 1993, Carolina Crown opted to compete exclusively in Division I in 1994. That year, the corps finished seventeenth in DCI semifinals in [[Boston]]. In 1995, in only its sixth season, Carolina Crown earned a spot as one of DCI's Top Twelve Finalists, taking eleventh place in quarterfinals and holding that position through Finals. Since that first Finals appearance, Carolina Crown has failed to make DCI Finals only once (2002), finishing in fourth place in 2008, 2010, 2011, 2018, and 2019, third place in 2016 and 2017, second place in 2009, 2012 and 2015, and winning the World Class DCI World Championship in 2013.<ref name=\"dci.org\">[http://www.dci.org/news/view.cfm?news_id=49f8a973-d562-4c9c-b14a-16d4f3866e41 DCI.org News: A New Champion is 'Crowned'<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In recent years, Crown has become renowned for its hornline, consistently one of DCI's best. In the championship year of 2013, the brass scored the first (and only) perfect score in DCI Finals history<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/business/press-releases/article/Carolina-Crown-Drum-and-Bugle-Corps-Wins-First-4738023.php (accessed Sept. 3, 2013)]</ref> and won the Jim Ott Award for Best Brass Performance for the 4th time in the preceding five years. The corps would win the award again in 2016, 2017, and 2019.\n\nIn 1995, the corps moved from Charlotte to [[Belmont, North Carolina]]. Following the 1997 season, the corps relocated to its present home of [[Fort Mill, South Carolina]].<ref name=\"crown\" /><ref name=\"reps\" /><ref name=\"hist\" />\n\n==Sponsorship==\nCarolina Crown, Inc. is a [[501(c)(3)]] musical organization that has a board of directors, corps director, and staff assigned to carry out the organization's mission.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.carolinacrown.org/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=76&Itemid=441# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425222945/http://carolinacrown.org/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=76&Itemid=441# |archive-date=2012-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Jim Coates is the corps director.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.carolinacrown.org/web/index.php?option=com_contact&view=category&catid=12&Itemid=443# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425222744/http://carolinacrown.org/web/index.php?option=com_contact&view=category&catid=12&Itemid=443# |archive-date=2012-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Show summary (1990\u20132020) ==\n''Source:''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpsreps.com/dcx/index.cfm?view=corpslist&Corpsid=43 |title=Carolina Crown/Repertoire |publisher=DCX: The Drum Corps Xperience |accessdate=1 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\n''Gold background indicates DCI Championship; pale blue background indicates DCI Class Finalist; pale green background indicates DCI semifinalist.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width:100%\"\n|-\n! Year !! Theme !! Repertoire !! Score !! Placement\n|-\n|1990 ||'''The Music Man'''||Goodnight, My Someone / Ya Got Trouble / Lida Rose / Marian the Librarian / Till There Was You / <br>Goodnight Ladies / 76 Trombones<br>All from The Music Man by [[Meredith Willson]] ||58.600 ||33rd\n|- style=\"background:#afeeee;\"\n|1991 ||'''The Music of Prokofiev'''||Piano Concerto No. 3 / March, Opus 99 / Troika (4th Movement from Lieutenant Kije Suite) / <br>Alexander Nevsky / Ivan the Terrible <br>All by [[Sergei Prokofiev]] ||91.500<br>66.400 ||2nd Class A<br>25th Open Class\n|- style=\"background:#afeeee;\"\n|1992 ||'''The Dances of <br>Malcolm Arnold'''||English Dance I (Set One, Op.27) / English Dance II (Set Two, Op. 33) / English Dance IV (Set One, Op. 27) / <br>Four Scottish Dances III (Op. 59) / Four Cornish Dances IV (Op. 91) <br>All by [[Malcolm Arnold]] ||90.500<br>69.700 ||3rd Division II<br>25th Open Class\n|- 